{[%evp 0,108,30,30,28,-16,36,19,30,35,43,43,28,26,25,38,49,44,12,28,59,62,54,
51,46,31,30,19,18,2,9,6,8,-20,-8,0,-14,-30,-6,-2,6,-32,-25,-73,-79,-86,-79,
-112,-82,-107,-114,-116,-97,-96,-86,-102,-81,-129,-118,-137,-137,-136,-137,
-142,-138,-149,-145,-98,-110,-98,-116,-356,-341,-447,-444,-444,-448,-467,-389,
-443,-491,-522,-523,-554,-494,-510,-508,-519,-484,-484,-526,-542,-572,-666,
-676,-788,-644,-672,-582,-765,-615,-628,-650,-811,-613,-739,-679,-719,-805,
-854,-912]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {One of the most favorable structures for the
Slav player to tame the white bishop pair is the Carlsbad one.} ({In
comparison, in the usual Carlsbad, Black needs a ton of time to swap his
light-squared bishop.} 2... e6 {[%csl Gc8]} 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. cxd5 exd5
6. Qc2 {Ignore the move order.} c6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Nf8
{[%csl Gg6,Gd3][%cal Gg7g6,Gf8e6,Ge6g7,Gc8f5] Next, one of the main ideas for
Black is to swap off his light-squared bishop with the manoeuvres g7-g8,
Nf8-e6-g7 and eventually Bc8-f5. In the Slav things are much simpler for the
second player.}) 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 {[%csl Gg7] The Schelcher Slav.
} 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6 {[%csl Gd5,Gc6,Ge6,Gf7,Gg6,Gh7,
Gb7] This pawn formation we hall study in detail in the next examples. After
the trade of the light-squared bishop Black is following the so-called
Capablanca principle and as rule tries to place as many of his pawns on the
opposite colour of his bishop.} 10. Rd1 Nbd7 {[%csl Gf7,Ge6,Gd5,Gc6,Gb7,Gg6,
Gh7,Bg7,Ge4,Gb5,Ga4][%cal Ge3e4,Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Ga2a4,Gh3h4,Gh4h5,Gg2g4]} 11. Bd2
Re8 12. cxd5 {This leads to the Carlsbad structure.} exd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Gc6,
Ge4,Gc4]} 13. Be1 ({After:} 13. a4 {[%csl Gb7]} a5 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4][%cal Gd7b8,
Gb8a6,Ga6b4] Black fixes a nice outpost for his knight. Always a most-welcomed
occurance in the battle betwee the knights and the bishops.}) ({Stronger was
the immediate:} 13. b4 a6 ({Or:} 13... b5 14. a4 a6) 14. a4 b5 15. Ra2 {
[%cal Gd1a1] In order to build pressure along the a-file after:} (15. a5 {
[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf6e8,Ge8d6,Gd6c4]} Qe7 {[%csl Re4,Rc4,Gb4][%cal Gf6e4,Ge4d6,
Gd6c4,Gd7f6,Ge7b4]}) 15... Nb6 16. Rda1 {With the tactical idea:} Bf8 {[%csl
Gb4][%cal Gf8b4]} ({However:} 16... Rb8 $1 {leaves Black wonderfully
positioned and he at least does not experience any problems.}) 17. axb5 axb5
18. Rxa8 Nxa8 19. Rxa8 Qxa8 20. Qxf6) 13... a5 $1 {A typical Carlsbad idea.}
14. Rac1 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6,Ge6g5,Gg5e4]} 15. a3 Ne6 16. b4 {This only helps
Black.} axb4 17. axb4 b5 $1 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Gb5,Gc4,Ge4,Rb4][%cal Gb5c4,
Gd5c4,Gc4e3] Fixes the c4 outpost on which Black will soon land with a
"Petrosian knight."} 18. Bb1 Nd7 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Bd7b6,Bb6c4]} 19. Ne2 Rc8 20.
Qg3 Nb6 21. f3 Nc4 $19 {All the black pieces are superior to their
counterparts, Black is strategically winning.} 22. Qf2 Bh6 23. Rc3 f5 (23...
Ng7 $1 {[%csl Re3,Rc4,Gb4][%cal Gg7f5,Gf5e3,Rh6e3,Rc4e3,Gd8e7,Ge7b4,Ge7e3]})
24. f4 Bf8 {[%csl Rb4]} 25. Rb3 Rc7 26. g4 Ng7 27. Qf3 Be7 28. Kg2 Bh4 $1 {
[%csl Ye1,Yh4]} 29. Bxh4 Qxh4 30. Ng3 Rce7 31. Nf1 Qf6 32. Rdd3 h5 33. g5 Qd6
34. Qf2 Ne6 35. Rdc3 Nxd4 36. exd4 Re2 37. Rc2 Rxf2+ 38. Rxf2 Re1 39. Bd3 h4
40. Kf3 Qe7 41. Ra2 Rxf1+ 42. Bxf1 Qe4+ 43. Kf2 Qxf4+ 44. Rf3 Qxd4+ 45. Ke1 Ne3
46. Ra8+ Kf7 47. Be2 Qxb4+ 48. Kf2 Qd4 49. Rc8 Nc4+ 50. Kg2 Ne5 51. Ra3 Ke6 52.
Raa8 Qf4 53. Re8+ Kd6 54. Rad8+ Kc5 {White resigns.} 0-1

