{[%evp 0,54,30,30,28,-9,35,35,35,33,31,33,33,33,33,46,35,33,42,46,55,38,37,32,
26,25,35,28,42,0,4,7,23,14,19,19,3,3,3,-9,-9,-2,-8,0,18,1,0,-29,-29,-29,-36,
-113,-159,-252,-228,-231,-251]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 {As usual, the play of the
world champion is highly instructive, even in blitz.} 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 5.
h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 e6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. a3 g6 9. Bd2 Bg7 10. cxd5 {As we know it,
already good for Black.} ({Keeping the pressure with something like:} 10. g4 $5
{[%cal Bh3h4,Bg4g5,Bh4h5] looks more in the spirit of the position. The
knights should be restrained as early as possible.}) 10... exd5 11. Bd3 O-O {
[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge3e4]} 12. O-O a6 (12... a5 $5 {as L'Ami also makes sense.})
13. Rfc1 ({One of White's problems is that he lacks reasonable plan. The play
in the center with:} 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 {[%csl Gd4]} Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nf6 $17 {
[%csl Rd3,Rd2,Gd8,Gf5][%cal Rd3c4,Rc4d4,Gd8d7,Ga8d8,Gf6d5,Gd5e7,Ge7f5,Gf5d4,
Gg7d4,Gd7d4] leads White nowhere.}) 13... Re8 14. b4 b5 $1 {Fixes the outpost
for the knight.} 15. Ne2 Rc8 16. a4 Nb6 17. axb5 axb5 {[%csl Gb5,Gc6,Gd5][%cal
Gb6c4]} 18. Ra6 Nc4 {[%csl Gc4] The knight is a beast at this square, both
defending the backward pawn, but also ready to switch to the kingside attack.}
19. Be1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Gg7][%cal Gg7d4]} Ne4 {[%csl Rc4,Re4]} 20. Nc3 Ned6 {
[%csl Bd6,Bc4]} 21. Rca1 Bh6 {Eyeballing the e3 pawn. The scarifices on this
square as the famous game Benko-Petrosian are already in the air.} 22. Ra7 Rc7
23. g3 $2 {That's all Black needs to wrap up the game.} Rxa7 24. Rxa7 Qb6 25.
Ra2 Nxe3 $1 26. Re2 (26. fxe3 Rxe3 27. Qf1 Qxd4 {[%csl Rd3,Rc3,Re1,Rg1,Rf1]})
26... Qxd4 27. Bb1 Nec4 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

