{[%evp 0,104,28,0,35,35,25,30,29,29,32,26,29,26,41,26,52,33,50,6,50,37,34,35,
36,31,27,26,26,20,23,39,40,14,19,9,9,11,23,26,22,18,31,9,8,-9,-14,-78,-78,-85,
-25,-45,-21,-55,-57,-61,-53,-67,-64,-64,-61,-61,-32,-24,-44,-42,-47,-54,-54,
-44,-33,-87,-67,-191,-211,-246,-239,-262,-259,-281,-279,-301,-293,-341,-363,
-351,-251,-265,-412,-428,-429,-493,-269,-279,-283,-298,-319,-348,-370,-391,
-399,-398,-426,-649,-931,-1040,-1052]} 1. c4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 {The
next structure to study is the symmetrical one.} 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 a6
7. Bd3 Bg4 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gg1f3]} 8. Nge2 {Many autors consider the trade of
the white knight for the enemy bishop in these structures inferior for White.
The black knights are better prepared for the fixed nature of the pawn chains.}
e6 9. Rc1 Bd6 10. f3 Bh5 11. O-O O-O 12. Na4 Bg6 13. Nc5 ({Safer seems:} 13.
Bxg6 hxg6 14. Bg5 $11 {[%csl Bf6,Gg5][%cal Bg5f6]}) 13... Bxc5 14. Rxc5 Qb6 15.
Bxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Gb8][%cal Gg3b8] The bishop on f4 is empty. It looks strong,
but in reality does very little.} 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. axb3 Nd7 18. Rc3 f6 {
[%csl Rf4,Gg5,Gf6][%cal Gg6g5] Black is already better, his knights have
plenty of good squares to fight for.} 19. Bd6 Rfc8 20. Rfc1 (20. h4 $1 {
[%csl Gg5] to gain some space was preferrable.}) 20... Kf7 (20... g5 $1) 21. e4
g5 22. g4 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8g6]} 23. exd5 ({Or:} 23. Bxf8 Rxf8 {[%csl Gd4,Gd8]
[%cal Gd8d4,Gd5e4]} 24. exd5 exd5 $17 {[%cal Ge8e1,Gh8h1]}) 23... exd5 24. f4
gxf4 25. Nxf4 Ne6 26. Nxd5 (26. Nxe6 Kxe6 27. Bc5 Rh8) 26... Nexd4 27. Nb6 Ne2+
28. Kf2 Nxc1 29. Rxc1 Rd8 30. Bc7 Rac8 (30... Rd2+ 31. Ke3 Rad8 32. Bxd8 Rxd8
$15) 31. Nxc8 Rxc8 32. Bb6 Rh8 33. Kg3 Re8 34. Rd1 Re4 35. Rd7+ Kg6 36. Rxb7
Rb4 {[%csl Yb6,Rb7][%cal Yb4b7]} 37. h4 Rxb3+ 38. Kf4 Rb4+ 39. Kg3 Ne5 40. h5+
Kh7 41. g5 fxg5 (41... Nc4 $4 42. g6+) 42. h6 Rb3+ (42... Kxh6) 43. Kf2 Rxb2+
44. Kg3 Rb3+ 45. Kg2 Kxh6 46. Re7 Ng6 47. Re6 Kh5 48. Rd6 Nf4+ 49. Kf2 g4 50.
Be3 g5 51. Rd2 g3+ 52. Kf3 g2 {White resigns.} 0-1

