{[%evp 0,70,28,28,20,-9,29,35,21,25,65,49,35,35,37,24,35,21,30,21,26,25,23,15,
20,17,34,24,29,-2,7,-52,-54,-51,-12,-44,-56,-71,-53,-53,-52,-68,-73,-65,-82,
-130,-104,-123,-170,-163,-171,-179,-188,-294,-266,-266,-303,-303,-290,-335,
-333,-337,-328,-328,-353,-333,-331,-375,-393,-480,-472,-499,-506]} 1. d4 d5 2.
c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Bf4 Nc6 7. e3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3]
Here is another example of the trade being successful for Black:} 8. Bd3 e6 9.
h3 ({The following game was annotated by GM Flear:} 9. O-O {"(it's probably
better to force a decision from Black's bishop before castling)"} Bd6 10. h3
Bh5 $5 {(keeping the tension; does White want to risk g2-g4?)} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6
12. Rc1 O-O 13. a3 (13. Be2 {is safest, but even so after} Rac8 14. Ne1 Bxe2
15. Qxe2 Nd7 16. Nd3 Nb4 {Black had at least equality, R.Hübner-Kr.Georgiev,
German League 1995}) 13... Rac8 14. Na4 Ne4 $1 15. Re1 Na5 16. g4 {(risky)} Bg6
17. Ne5 Nxf2 $1 18. Kxf2 Rxc1 19. Qxc1 Bxd3 20. Nxd3 Qh2+ 21. Kf1 Nb3 {
(threatening the queen and ...Nd2+)} 22. Nf2 Nxc1 23. Rxc1 f5 24. g5 f4 {
0-1 Aamchamp-T.Luther, Internet (blitz) 2003. Yes, I know that it was only a
blitz game, but the pin shouldn't be underestimated!.}) 9... Bxf3 $5 {Black is
not so worried about exchanging his light-squared bishop for a knight as his
remaining pieces should be able to find good moorings (Flear)} 10. Qxf3 Bd6 {
[%cal Gf4g5,Gg5f6]} (10... h6 {(the most solid, preventing Bg5)} 11. Rc1 Bd6
12. O-O O-O 13. a3 Rc8 {with equality, as in P.Nikolic-L. Fressinet, Selfoss
2003 (Flear)}) 11. Rc1 ({Apparently White did not want to allow:} 11. Bg5 Nb4
12. Bb1) 11... O-O 12. O-O Bxf4 13. Qxf4 Rc8 14. Bb1 Qe7 {[%csl Gd8,Gd4][%cal
Gf8d8,Gd8d4,Ge3e4] Preparing for the e3-e4 advance. White hardly has any other
plan as his only knight cannot overcome the opponent's knight pair in the
battle on the queenside.} 15. e4 {This is obviously wrong. White will now lose
the d4 pawn in the long run.} dxe4 16. Nxe4 {[%csl Gb1,Rd4][%cal Gb1e4]} (16.
Bxe4 Rfd8 17. Bxc6 Rxc6 $17) 16... Nxe4 ({Actually, the pawn could have been
taken at once:} 16... Nxd4 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf4e4]}) 17. Qxe4 f5
18. Qe3 Rcd8 19. Rfd1 Qf6 $17 {[%csl Yb1,Rd8][%cal Rf6d4,Rd8d4,Rf8d8,Rd8d6,
Rd6d4,Rc6d4] Black can bring four attackers against the d4 pawn, whereas the
opponent's light-squared bishop is not of any use in the defence of the
isolani.} 20. Rc4 Rd6 21. a3 Rfd8 {[%csl Gd6,Gc6,Gd8,Gf6,Rd1][%cal Gf6d4,Gc6d4,
Gd6d4,Ge6e5]} 22. Ba2 Nxd4 23. Rdc1 f4 24. Qe4 f3 25. Re1 fxg2 26. Kxg2 Rf8 27.
Qe3 Nc2 28. Rxc2 Qg6+ 29. Qg3 Qxc2 30. Bxe6+ Kh8 31. Bg4 Rd2 32. Bf3 Qxb2 33.
Re7 b5 34. Rc7 Qd4 35. Rb7 Rd3 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

