-34,-45,-38,-3,-225,-223,-223,-140,-186,-131,-122,-122,-167,-200,-362,-372,
-366,-382,-382,-324,-316,-316,-391,-401,-488]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4.
e3 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 {The greatest specialist in the Schelcher Slav is GM Kamsky
and his play with the knights is always evry impressive.} 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O a6
8. a4 a5 {[%csl Ga4,Gc8,Rb8][%cal Ga7a6,Ga6a5,Ga2a4,Gb8a6,Ga6b4,Gc8f5,Gf5g4] A
familiar idea from the previous examples. The b4 square is fixed for the
knight.} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. b3 Nc6 11. Ba3 Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 $1 {The knights are
more useful than the bishops as we know it!} 13. Bxf3 Qd7 14. Qd2 ({Once more
note that White cannot open the center:} 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4
Nxd4) 14... Rfc8 15. Rac1 e6 16. Rfd1 Bf8 {[%csl Gb4,Yc2,Rf8][%cal Rf8a3,Ra3f8,
Gc6b4,Gc8c1] Forcing the trade of the bishops, almost always a useful idea.
Without the bishop pair, White as a rule suffers. Kamsky increases the control
over the b4 square and from there controls the whole queenside.} 17. Bxf8 Kxf8
18. e4 $1 {White is correctly trying to prolong the diagonal for the bishop.}
dxe4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Nb4 21. Rc4 ({Missing a chance to equalize with:} 
21. d5 $142 $1 Rxc1 {And now not:} 22. Rxc1 $2 ({But:} 22. Qxc1 $1 exd5 23.
Bxd5 Nxd5 24. Qc5+ $11) 22... exd5 23. Rd1 Rd8 ({Or the alternative win:} 23...
Re8 24. Bxd5 Nxd5 25. Qxd5 Re1+)) 21... Kg8 22. h4 Qe7 23. g3 Rd8 $15 {[%csl
Rd4] The numbers are once more working in Black's favor. He slowly digested
the pawn.} 24. h5 Rd7 25. Qf4 Rad8 26. hxg6 hxg6 27. Bf3 b6 28. Kg2 Qf8 29. Qg4
Qg7 30. Be2 Qf6 31. Bf3 Kg7 32. Be2 Nd5 $3 33. Bf3 Ne7 $1 34. b4 Nf5 {[%csl
Yc4,Yd1,Gd7,Gd8,Rf3,Gf5,Gf6,Yg4][%cal Gb4d5,Gd5e7,Ge7f5,Gf5d4] Four versus
three, the pawn is gone.} 35. bxa5 bxa5 36. d5 exd5 37. Rc5 Rb7 38. Rxa5 Rb2
39. Qf4 Qb6 40. Rd2 Ne3+ 41. Qxe3 Qxe3 42. Rxb2 Qc3 43. Rbb5 Qe1 44. Rxd5 Rh8
45. Bh5 gxh5 46. Rg5+ Kf6 47. Rxh5 Qe4+ 48. Kg1 {Di Berrardino-Kamsky,
Khanty-Mansiysk 2011.} 0-1

