{[%evp 0,24,23,23,32,-23,26,30,37,23,41,20,28,22,19,5,4,9,10,16,13,14,18,13,12,
15,20]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Bd3 ({The bishop can be also
swapped for the other knight after:} 5. Nh4 Bxb1 6. Rxb1 e6 7. a3 Nbd7 {
[%csl Gd5,Gc6,Gb7,Ge6,Gf7,Gh7][%cal Gf7d5,Gb7d5,Gf8d6] We are reaching the
usual set up which keeps the bishop opened. Later Black needs to fix some
weaknesses for either attack them, or to secure some outposts for the kngihts:}
8. Nf3 Bd6 9. b4 O-O 10. Bb2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 b5 12. Bd3 a5 {[%csl Ra3,Rb4][%cal
Gd6a3] The white queenside pawns are perfect targets.}) 5... Bg6 6. O-O e6 7.
Qe2 ({Or:} 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. b3 Bd6 9. Bb2 Ne4 10. Qc2 f5 {(Bologan) switching to
the Stonewall.}) 7... Nbd7 8. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Rb4,Rc3,Rd3,Rg6][%cal Rb4c3,Rg6d3,
Rd3g6] This is one of the good setups for Black. He is ready to swap off one
of his bishops for the knight in a proper moment, but is also able to get rid
of the opponent's bishop pair at once too.} 9. Bd2 ({Or else the knights will
find excellent spots to attack:} 9. a3 Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. a4 Qa5 12. Ba3
Rfc8 13. Qb2 Nb6 {(Bologan)}) 9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 O-O 12. Nd2 Qc7
{With equality.} 1/2-1/2

