-1011,-1239,-1261,-1287,-1289,-1720,-1289,-1717,-1299,-1239,-1279,-1720,-26468,
-29962]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bd3 Bg6 7. O-O
Nbd7 8. Qe2 Bb4 9. Bd2 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 O-O 11. Nd2 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Re8 {This game
is a nice example of Black's strategy executed in a brilliant way.} 13. e4 dxe4
14. Nxe4 Nxe4 {The swap of the knights is favourable for Black.} 15. Qxe4 Qg5
16. Rfe1 Nf6 17. Qe5 Qxe5 18. Rxe5 Nd7 19. Ree1 b5 $1 {A wonderful Caro-Kann
idea. The central d5 square is cleared for the knight.} 20. cxb5 (20. b3 {
would not have solved White's problems due to:} bxc4 21. bxc4 Nb6 $1 {[%csl
Rc4,Gd5] and the pawn needs to move.}) 20... cxb5 21. Ba5 ({Missing the last
chance to bail out with:} 21. d5 $1 exd5 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Rd1 Nb6 24. Bd4 (
24. Ba5) 24... Rd8 25. Rd3 {[%cal Gd3b3,Gb3b5] with compensation for the pawn.}
({Or:} 25. b3 $44)) 21... Nf6 22. Rac1 Rac8 23. Kf1 Nd5 24. g3 $17 {[%csl Gd5,
Ra5] Black plays for a win without any risk. He later managed to create a
second weakness on the kingside.} Kf8 25. Ke2 Ke7 26. Kd3 Kd7 27. Bd2 {[%csl
Gd5,Rd2]} a6 28. g4 h6 29. f3 Rh8 30. h4 h5 31. Rxc8 Kxc8 32. Rh1 Kd7 33. Ke4
Rc8 34. Rc1 Nf6+ 35. Kf4 Rh8 36. Rh1 hxg4 37. fxg4 g5+ 38. Kf3 gxh4 39. Bg5 Nd5
40. Rxh4 Rxh4 41. Bxh4 Nb4 42. a3 Nd3 43. b3 Nc1 44. b4 Nd3 45. Ke4 Nb2 46. d5
Nc4 47. dxe6+ Kxe6 48. Kd4 Nxa3 49. Kc5 Nc4 50. Bg5 Ne5 51. Kb6 Kd5 52. Kxa6
Kc6 53. Bf4 Nxg4 54. Bg3 f5 55. Ka5 Ne3 56. Bf4 Nd5 57. Be5 f4 58. Bd4 f3 59.
Ka6 Nxb4+ 60. Ka5 Nd3 61. Be3 f2 0-1

