{[%evp 0,38,32,30,30,-21,23,41,41,41,42,34,34,33,27,36,43,41,55,28,28,16,2,-2,
2,14,25,19,19,-17,-19,-37,-35,-35,-38,-33,-50,-40,-43,-58,-45]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4
c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 e6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bb4 9. O-O (9.
a3 {will be met with the immediate} Bxc3+) 9... O-O {In some lines of teh Slav
Black can successfully trade both his bishops in order to achieve solid
blockade.} 10. Qd1 ({White has also tried:} 10. Rd1 Re8 11. Bf1 (11. Bd2 e5 {
is tactically justified:} 12. cxd5 $2 Bxc3 {[%cal Gb4c3,Ge5e4] and 13...e4})
11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 Ne4 13. cxd5 exd5 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7b5]} 14. c4 Nb6 15.
cxd5 cxd5 {[%csl Be4,Bd5,Bc4,Rc1][%cal Bb6c4]} 16. Bd2 Nc4 17. Be1 Rc8 18. a4
b6 19. Qe2 a5 20. Rdc1 Qd7 21. Qa2 Ned6 22. Rc3 Ra8 (22... g6 {[%cal Gh7h5]})
23. Rac1 b5 24. axb5 Qxb5 {the blockade led to unclear play in A.Iljin-I.Popov,
Saint Petersburg 2007.}) (10. a3 Bxc3 {retreating the bishop to a5 is okay,
but this is more in the spirit of 8... Bb4 (Vigus)} 11. bxc3 Nb6 $5 ({Or
perhaps even better:} 11... e5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge5e4]} 12. Qg3 e4 13. Be2 Nb6
14. cxd5 cxd5 15. a4 Nc4 16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. Ba3 Re8 {[%csl Gd5,Ra3][%cal Gf6d5,
Ge8e6,Ge6g6] when Black even looked betterin this Nimtzo-Indian-looking
position, D. Shengelia-D.Arutunian, Tbilisi 2000}) 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Rb1 Qc7 14.
Qa2 $5 {(S.Smagin-E.Meduna, Trnava 1987)} dxc4 15. Bxc4 Ne4 {gives Black good
play according to Smagin.}) 10... dxc4 $5 (10... Qe7 {is a good alternative:}
11. Qb3 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nb6 13. Be2 Bd6 14. a4 Nbd5 15. a5 e5 16. Bc4 Rfd8 17.
Bd2 h6 18. Rfe1 e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gd5,Rd2][%cal Gf6d5,Ge7e6,Ge6f5,Gf5g5,Gh6h5,
Gh5h4,Gg7g4] this was comfortable for Black in Y.Kuzubov-P.Cramling, Gibraltar
2007. Notice that we now have the reverse French Defence where Black managed
to achieve full control over the d5 square and enjoys a pleasant step-by-step
attack on the kingside. The white extra bishop is hardly useful here.}) 11.
Bxc4 c5 $5 12. Qb3 cxd4 13. exd4 ({Or:} 13. Qxb4 $6 dxc3 14. Qxc3 Rc8 {and
White has problems with his queenside. (Vigus)}) 13... Qa5 14. a3 Bxc3 15. bxc3
Rac8 {This suggestion of Hübner's looks well worth testing since it's tricky
for White to look after the backward pawn on c3. The position is dynamically
balanced and note that} 16. Bd2 Ne4 17. Be1 {should be met by} Qb6 $1 (17...
Qc7 $6 18. Bxe6 $1) 18. Rc1 Nd6 19. Qxb6 Nxb6 {[%csl Rd4,Rc3,Ra3][%cal Gb6c4,
Gd6c4] , keeping the c3-pawn fixed. (Vigus) The isolated pair of pawns is
beautifully blocked by the black knights and White experiences problems with
his queenside pawns.} 1/2-1/2

