{[#]} 17... h6 $1 {This position arose from another opening (Caro-Kann) but is
nevertheless in the spirit of the Slav. Black's last move is a familiar idea
from before. "Petrosian wants to stop White from playing the bishop to g5 once
and for all". (Engqvist)} 18. Bf3 Rhd8 19. c4 $6 {[%csl Rd4] Now we are in an
optimal Slav with the bishop pair being useless in the defence of the d4 pawn.}
Bc7 20. Bc3 Kb8 21. Rac1 Bb6 22. d5 $5 {White's best chance.} ({Mnatsakanian
clearly understood that he will not survive the grinding after:} 22. c5 {
[%csl Gc7,Gd5,Gd8,Gd7][%cal Gb6c7,Gf6d5,Gc7f4,Gf4g5,Gg5f6,Bd8e8,Rc7d8,Rd8f6,
Re7f8,Rf8g7,Gf6d4,Gd5e7,Ge7f5,Gf5d4]} Bc7 {[%csl Gd4,Rd7,Rd8,Rc7,Rf6,Yf3][%cal
Gd4d5,Gb2b4,Ga2a4,Gb4b5,Rf6f5,Rc7d8,Rd8f6,Rf6d4] as Black can next play for
the 4 versus 3 attackers against the d4 pawn.}) 22... cxd5 23. cxd5 exd5 24.
Be5+ Bc7 25. Bxf6 gxf6 26. Bg4 Ba5 $1 27. Bxd7 Bxe1 28. Rxe1 $2 (28. Bg4 {
gives White definite drawing chances because of his strong control of the
light squares. Now he's entering a rook ending a pawn down and a passed pawn
at that.(Engqvist)}) 28... Rxd7 29. Re8+ Kc7 30. Rh8 $2 (30. Kf1 {would have
still kept serious drawing chances for White.}) 30... d4 {[%cal Rd4d3,Rd3d2,
Rd2d1]} 31. Kf1 $6 (31. Re8 d3 32. Re1 Kc6 {[%csl Ra2,Rb2][%cal Gc6c5,Gc5d4,
Gd7c7,Gc7c2,Gc2b2,Gb2a2]}) 31... Re7 $1 {[%cal Rd4d3,Rd3d2,Rd2d1]} 0-1

