1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. e3 {This is a more
positional approach. 6.Ne5 often leads to sharp battles.} e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 8. O-O
O-O 9. Nh4 {Hunting the bishop. The main line is 9.Qe2.} Nbd7 (9... Bg4 {
used to be the main continuation, trying to provoke some pawn advances which
might weaken the white king. On the other hand, it's not clear if it will
really weaken the kingside position or squeeze Black on that side of the board.
After} 10. f3 Bh5 11. g4 {Black should choose between 11...Bg6 or 11...Nd5.})
10. h3 (10. Nxf5 exf5 {we reach the position which can arise also in the line
6.Nh4 (instead of 6.e3).}) (10. f3 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Qc2 Qa5 13. Rd1 Rac8
14. e4 c5 15. d5 Bxc3 16. bxc3 exd5 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 c4 19. Ba3 Rfe8 {
1/2-1/2 (55) Korobov,A (2674)-Prohaszka,P (2593) Gjakova 2016}) 10... Bg6 11.
Nxg6 hxg6 12. Qb3 Qb6 13. Rd1 Rad8 14. Bd2 {14.Na2 is another logical option -
I tried it myself:} (14. Na2 Be7 15. Bd2 Qxb3 16. Bxb3 c5 17. Rac1 Rc8 18. a5
cxd4 19. exd4 Nb8 20. Bb4 Bxb4 21. Nxb4 Rfd8 22. d5 exd5 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Nxd5
$14 {1-0 (43) Postny,E (2627)-Milov,L (2482) Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2008})
14... Ba5 $146 {Najer is eager to swap queens, but 14... a5 looks more natural.
} (14... a5 15. Be1 Qc7 16. Qc2 Nb6 17. Bb3 Qe7 18. Rac1 Rd7 19. Qe2 Ra8 20. g4
Nbd5 21. f4 Qd8 22. Bf2 $14 {1-0 (42) Van Wely,L (2643) -Kasimdzhanov,R (2690)
Germany 2000}) 15. Rac1 (15. Qxb6 Nxb6 16. Be2) 15... c5 $6 {Najer had not an
easy choice. Black clearly should undermine White's centre by c6-c5 or by
e6-e5. He can do it before or after the exchange of queens.} (15... e5 {
was, probably, the safest.} 16. d5 Qxb3 17. Bxb3 Nc5 18. Bc4 Bxc3 19. Bxc3 Nxd5
20. Bxe5 (20. Bxd5 $2 Rxd5 21. Rxd5 cxd5 {and White can't take on e5 in view
of the fork on d3}) 20... Nb6 21. Bd6 Nxc4 22. Rxc4 Ne6 {and Black should
equalize without many difficulties.}) (15... Qxb3 16. Bxb3 c5 (16... e5 17. Ne2
(17. d5 {- see 15... e5.}) 17... Bxd2 18. Rxd2 exd4 19. Rxd4 Ne5 $14) 17. d5
Bxc3 18. Bxc3 {would transpose to our game via a different move order.}) 16. d5
Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Qxb3 {Najer decided to simplify the position as much, as
possible, but it will be a game for two results only, either White wins or
Black holds.} (17... exd5 18. Bxd5 Nxd5 19. Qxd5 Nf6 20. Qc4 Qc6 $14) 18. Bxb3
Nxd5 19. Bxd5 exd5 20. Rxd5 Nb6 21. Rxc5 Nxa4 22. Rc7 Nxc3 23. R1xc3 (23. bxc3
a5 24. Rxb7 Rb8 {Eventually this will lead to a rook endgame with four pawns
against three on the kingside, which Black should hold with careful defence.})
23... Rd1+ 24. Kh2 Rd2 25. Rxb7 Rxf2 {Of course, this position looks rather
drawish, but Black still needs to be accurate, as one of his rooks is passive.}
26. Kg3 Rf6 (26... Rd2 27. b4 (27. Rcc7 $6 a5 {improves Black's chances}) 27...
a6 28. Rcc7 {Black is still suffering here.}) 27. Rxa7 Rb8 {Black gave a pawn,
but activated the other rook.} 28. h4 Kh7 $6 (28... Rxb2 $4 29. Rc8+ Kh7 30.
Raa8 g5 31. h5 {mating.}) (28... g5 $1 29. hxg5 Rf5 30. Kg4 Rbb5 {would be the
most convincing way to hold the draw.}) 29. Rcc7 Rxb2 30. Rxf7 Rxf7 31. Rxf7 g5
$1 {It's necessary to get the king into play.} 32. hxg5 Rb5 33. e4 Kg6 34. Ra7
Rxg5+ 35. Kf3 Rb5 36. Kf4 Rb6 37. Ra2 Kf6 $2 {This is the losing move, but
it's not obvious at first sight.} (37... Rf6+ 38. Ke5 Rf1 39. Kd6 Rb1 {was the
right defensive idea.} 40. e5 Rb6+ 41. Kc5 (41. Kd7 Rb7+ 42. Kc6 Rb1 {also
holds.}) 41... Rb1 {White can't push his passed pawn, as Black's king is
nearby.} 42. g4 Kf7 43. Kd5 Rd1+ 44. Ke4 Kg6 $1 {White can torture his
opponent, but can't make real progress.}) 38. e5+ $1 Ke6 (38... Kg6 39. Ra4 $1
{An important move.} Rb2 40. Ra6+ Kf7 41. g4 Rf2+ 42. Kg5 Rf1 43. Ra7+ {
and the king gets to g6.}) 39. Ra7 Rb4+ 40. Kg5 Rb5 (40... Kxe5 41. Rxg7 $18)
41. g4 Kxe5 42. Rxg7 {Black's king in the wrong place, so it's lost.} Ke4+ 43.
Kh6 Kf4 44. g5 Kg4 45. Ra7 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

