1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Qb3 Qc7 6. Nc3 e6 7. Nh4 Bg6 8. Nxg6
hxg6 9. g3 (9. Bd2 Nbd7 10. h3 (10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O {After white castles
long, with the queen on b3, Nb6 followed by a5, a4 and Nc4 is generally a good
plan.} Nb6 12. h3 a5 13. f3 a4 14. Qc2 Nc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. Ne4 b5 17. Nxf6+
gxf6 18. Qe4+ Be7 19. Bb4 {1/2-1/2 Moskalenko-Panelo Munoz Badalona 2008.
Black is at least equal after 19...f5}) 10... Nb6 {I like the immediate Nb6
here. Development with Be7 is also fine for black eg} (10... Be7 {With the
white rook coming to c1, black does not want to put the bishop on d6 where it
can run into a future Nb5.} 11. Rc1 Nb6 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bd3 g5 $5 14. a4 g4
$146 (14... a5) 15. a5 Nc4 16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. Qxc4 Qxa5) 11. cxd5 (11. Rc1 Nxc4
12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Rd8 14. e4 Qd7 15. Be3 b5 16. Qe2 b4 17. Na4 Nxe4 18.
Qc2 Nf6 19. Qxc6 Be7 20. Ke2 Nd5 21. Rc4 Qxc6 22. Rxc6 Rd6 23. Rc8+ Rd8 24. Rc6
Rd6 {Azmaiparashvili-Sandipan, Pune 2004}) 11... exd5 {The plans are the same
in these variations. Black plays the N to b6 with the idea of forcing white to
decide what to do with the c pawn. Black tends to recapture on d5 with the e
pawn, put the black bishop on e7, and then as soon as white castles queenside,
go for a5 and a4 and if white castles kingside, look to see if g5-g4 is on.}
12. Bd3 Be7 13. O-O-O (13. O-O g5 $1 $146 {The white king will not get an easy
time on either side of the board.} 14. e4 g4 15. e5 gxh3 16. exf6 hxg2 17. Kxg2
Qh2+ 18. Kf3 Qh5+ 19. Ke3 Bxf6 {Is very dangerous for white although white can
probably force a draw with accurate play.} 20. Rh1 Qg4 21. Rxh8+ Kd7 22. Bf5+
$3 (22. Rxa8 Bxd4#) 22... Qxf5 23. Rxa8 Nc4+ 24. Ke2 Qg4+ 25. Kd3 Qf5+) 13...
a5 $1 {The standard to response to queenside castling.} 14. Kb1 a4 15. Qc2 Nc4
16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. Nxa4 O-O 18. h4 Ra7 19. Nc5 Rfa8 20. a3 b6 21. Ne4 Nxe4 22.
Qxe4 Bxa3 {Khismatullin-Dreev, Warsaw with a dangerous initiative for black.})
9... Nbd7 10. Bd2 (10. Bg2 Be7 11. O-O (11. Bd2 Nb6 {is a little annoying for
white as the black knight can come to c4 attacking the bishop on d2.} 12. cxd5
exd5) 11... Rd8 (11... Nb6 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bd2 Nc4 14. Rad1 Qb6 15. Na4 Qxb3
16. axb3 Nxd2 17. Rxd2 g5 {1/2-1/2 Mchedlishvili,M (2656) -Malakhov,V (2712)/
Konya TUR 2012/The Week in Chess 924 (73)}) 12. Rd1 (12. Bd2 Nb6) 12... O-O 13.
cxd5 exd5 14. Qc2 Nb6 15. b3 Rfe8 {and black is ready for central action.})
10... Be7 11. Rc1 Nb6 12. cxd5 (12. c5 Nbd7 13. Bg2 e5 14. O-O O-O 15. Qc2 Rfe8
16. b4 Nf8 17. b5 Ne6 {Jussupow-Akopian, Yerevan 2001}) 12... exd5 13. Bg2 Nc4
14. Qc2 Qd7 15. Na4 O-O 16. O-O Rfe8 {and black went on to win in
Azmaiparashvili-Gelfand, Moscow 2001} 17. Bc3 Qf5 18. b3 Nd6 19. Nc5 Nfe4 20.
Bb4 a5 21. Ba3 Nxc5 22. Bxc5 Qxc2 23. Rxc2 Nb5 24. a4 Nc7 25. Bh3 f5 26. Rd1
Na6 27. Bxe7 Rxe7 28. Bf1 Nb4 29. Rc5 g5 30. Rc3 f4 31. exf4 gxf4 32. Bh3 Rf8
33. Bg4 Rf6 34. Kg2 Kf7 35. Bf3 fxg3 36. hxg3 Ke6 37. Re3+ Kd6 38. Rde1 Rxe3
39. fxe3 Re6 40. Re2 c5 41. dxc5+ Kxc5 42. Bg4 Re4 43. Bf5 Re5 44. g4 Nc6 45.
Bc8 Re7 46. Rc2+ Kb4 47. Rc1 Kxb3 48. Bxb7 Nb4 49. Bc8 Kxa4 50. Rc5 Ra7 51. Be6
Ka3 52. Kf3 a4 53. e4 dxe4+ 54. Kxe4 Ra6 55. Kf5 g6+ 56. Kf6 Kb2 57. Rb5 Kc3
58. Rc5+ Kd2 59. Kf7 a3 60. Bc4 Rc6 61. Rxc6 Nxc6 62. Ba2 Ne5+ 63. Kf6 Nxg4+
64. Kxg6 Kc3 65. Kf5 Kb2 66. Be6 Nf2 67. Ke5 Nd3+ 68. Kd4 Nc1 {0-1 (68)
Azmaiparashvili,Z (2674)-Gelfand,B (2701) Moscow 2001} 0-1

[Event "Tata Steel Masters"]
[Site "lichess.org"]
[Date "2021.10.29"]
[Round "2.3"]
[White "Donchenko, Alexander"]
[Black "Caruana, Fabiano"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "D12"]
[WhiteElo "2668"]
[BlackElo "2823"]
[Annotator "GM Dejan Bojkov"]
[PlyCount "64"]
[EventDate "2021.??.??"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2
Be7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 {Caruana chose a very solid line which he already tested at
the last-year (ongoing) Candidates.} 10. Qc2 Nbd7 (10... a6 11. O-O-O b5 12. c5
Qc7 13. g4 Rxh2 14. Bd3 Rxh1 15. Rxh1 Qg3 16. Qd1 Nbd7 17. Qf1 Qc7 18. Rh8+ Nf8
{with compensation for a pawn in Ding, L (2791)-Grischuk, A (2777) Chess.com
INT 2020}) 11. O-O-O {Donchenko castles under a pawn attack but hopes to open
the centre and make it to the enemy king first.} (11. cxd5 {is the other
continuation.}) 11... a6 {[#] Here a7-a6 is aiming for a quick queenside
action.} (11... Nb6 12. c5 Nbd7 13. Kb1 Qb8 14. h4 g5 15. Be1 g4 16. e4 gxf3
17. gxf3 b6 18. exd5 exd5 19. cxb6 axb6 {in Giri,A (2763)-Caruana, F (2842)
Ekaterinburg 2020}) 12. g4 $146 {A novelty, played after ten minutes of
thought. But since Donchenko blitzed his next moves, it might have been only
memory refreshment.} (12. Be1 b5 13. c5 Qc8 14. g4 Bd8 15. h4 Bc7 16. Bd3 Qb7
17. h5 gxh5 18. g5 Ng8 19. g6 f5 20. e4 fxe4 21. fxe4 Ngf6 22. exd5 exd5 23.
Qe2+ {Adly,A (2637) -Ibrahimov,R (2518) Riadh 2017}) 12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 b5 {
Obvious, and somewhat provocative.} 14. Be2 {White simply retreated.} (14. Bb3
{does not seem to pose problems for Black after either the immediate:} c5 (
14... Rc8 $5 {In order to preserve the d5 square in case of:} 15. g5 Nd5) 15.
g5 c4 16. Bxc4 bxc4 17. gxf6 Bxf6 18. Qa4 {with unclear play.}) (14. Bxe6 $5
fxe6 15. g5 {Then after both:} Nh5 (15... Nd5 16. Qxg6+ Kf8 17. h4) 16. Qxg6+
Kf8 17. Qxe6 Bxg5 18. Kb1 {White has compensation for the piece due to the
weakened black king. However, since Caruana was practically blitzing and
knowing the high-level preparation of the American there is little doubt that
this was accurately checked at home.}) 14... c5 15. d5 $5 {The first real
in-depth thought in the game (more than half an hour). As it was mentioned
before White should logically try to get to the enemy king before the
queenside explodes and he is ready to part with a pawn for this aim.} (15. dxc5
Nxc5 16. Kb1 Rc8) 15... Nxd5 {And an alternative amount of time spent by Black.
} (15... exd5 16. g5) 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. f4 {The point behind the sacrifice.
White is ready to seize the light squares after Be2-f3!} b4 {In order to
secure the a5 square for the queen.} (17... Qb6 18. Bf3 c4 {and claims
approximate equality.} (18... Rd8)) 18. e4 {Another tough decision by the
German GM.} (18. Bf3 {would be nicely met with:} Qa5 19. Bxd5 Rc8 {When c5-c4!
break cannot be easily blocked, e.g:} 20. Kb1 (20. Bc4 Nb6 21. Kb1 Nxc4 22.
Qxc4 Qb5 $1 23. Rc1 Rd8 {with pleasant endgame for Black.}) 20... c4 $1 21.
Bxc4 Nb6 22. b3 Nxc4 23. bxc4 {With promising position for the second player
after both:} Qb6 (23... Qc5)) 18... d4 $1 {This pawn will play an important
part in Caruana's counter-attack.} (18... dxe4 $2 19. h4 $1 {is very strong in
order to meet the castling with mating attack:} (19. Qxe4 {is not bad neither.}
) 19... O-O 20. h5) (18... c4 19. exd5 {Here both pawn advances seem promising
for Black:} c3 $1 (19... b3 $1 20. axb3 cxb3 21. Qd3 O-O 22. Kb1 {when the Bd2
covers the a5 square, thus stopping the mate for the time being.}) 20. Be3
cxb2+ 21. Kb1 Rc8 {with strong initiative for the second player. But in a
hindsight this might have been the lesser evil for White.}) 19. e5 {With the
idea of e5-e6!} (19. h4 {Black's attack runs by itself with:} c4 20. Bxc4 Rc8
21. b3 Nb6 22. Qd3 Nxc4 23. bxc4 Qc7 24. Kb2 {Now Black may even reject the
pawn and play for attack with:} Qc5 (24... Qxc4 25. Qxc4 Rxc4)) 19... Nb6 {
Out of the tempo.} (19... c4 {might have been equally good:} 20. Bxc4 (20. e6
d3 $1 21. exf7+ Kf8 22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Qxd3 Nf6 {and Black should convert the
piece.}) 20... Nb6 21. Kb1 Rc8 22. b3 {Here:} Rh3 $1 {leads to an even better
version of the attacking position from above.}) 20. e6 {Donchenko is opening
the black king.} Qd5 $1 {But Caruana is as cold-blooded as he could be.} 21.
exf7+ Kf8 $1 {The king is pretty safe here.} (21... Kxf7 22. Bd3 Qxa2 23. Bxg6+
Kg8 24. Rde1 {when White has his chances.}) 22. h4 (22. b3 {although Black's
attack is running by itself here as well with:} a5) 22... Qxa2 23. Qxg6 b3 {
Both the kings are exposed, but the black one is hiding nicely behind the
opponent's own pawn.} 24. Be1 c4 $1 {An excellent inclusion of another piece
in the attack. The dark-squared bishop is decisively reinforcing the queenside
pressure.} (24... Qa1+ 25. Qb1 Qxb1+ 26. Kxb1 a5 27. g5) 25. Rxd4 (25. h5 c3
26. bxc3 Ba3#) 25... Na4 26. Qb1 Ba3 $1 {The point. White is helpless.} 27.
Qxa2 (27. bxa3 b2+ 28. Kc2 Qb3+ 29. Kd2 Qc3+) 27... bxa2 28. Kc2 Rb8 {Caruana
extracts the maximum out of the position.} (28... a1=Q 29. Bb4+ Bxb4 30. Rxa1
Nb6) 29. Rd8+ (29. bxa3 Rb2+ 30. Kd1 a1=Q#) 29... Rxd8 30. bxa3 c3 $1 {Black
is winning another piece:} 31. Bg3 Rd2+ 32. Kb3 Nc5+ {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

