{[%evp 0,79,27,-11,-9,-12,0,1,6,7,44,46,34,53,54,41,47,45,52,4,4,-2,-16,-13,0,
-11,5,-2,12,12,18,0,17,-12,12,12,59,23,35,10,20,0,0,20,-71,-103,-88,-104,-108,
-98,-112,-142,-130,-150,-64,-106,-110,-110,-104,-122,-120,-109,-105,-100,-102,
-104,-104,-100,-108,-116,-112,-112,-117,-130,-136,-136,-132,-142,-137,-137,
-137,-137]} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. d4 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 dxc4 7.
Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. e4 b4 10. Na4 c5 11. e5 Nd5 12. Nxc5 Bxc5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 {
[%csl Gd5,Gc5] "Overcoming the fear of losing the right to castle." (Kasparov)}
14. Bb5+ Kf8 {"It turns out that, with such a powerful knight at d5, Black can
permit himself certain liberties." (Kasparov) Ideally, Black needs to swap off
the queens and then will enjoy the pluses of his position in a symmetrical
pawn structure- the king will be centralized, the central knights will block
both the open files.} 15. Qd4 {It is not so easy for White to exploit the
pluses of his position.} Qb6 16. Be2 h6 17. O-O g6 $1 (17... Ba6 18. Bxa6 Nxa6
19. Qh4 Kg8 20. Re1 Rc8 21. Be3 $1 Qb7 22. Rac1 {the fact that the rook at h8
is out of play would be felt. Therefore Larsen consistently carries out the
plan of artificial castling.}) 18. Bd2 Kg7 19. Rac1 Rac8 20. Qh4 $6 (20. Rfd1
$1 {would still have left White with an initiative:} Na4 (20... Ba6 21. Bxa6
Nxa6 22. Qh4 {and Black experiences some discomfort}) 21. Qh4 $5 (21. Rxc8 Qxd4
22. Nxd4 Rxc8 23. Rb1 a5 24. f3 {is also not bad, with the better endgame})
21... Rxc1 (21... g5 22. Qg4) (21... Nxb2 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. Rb1 Na4 24. Bxb4 {
is no better for Black}) 22. Bxc1 {, and after the routine} Ba6 {an elegant
combination is possible:} 23. Rxd5 $1 exd5 24. Qf6+ Qxf6 25. exf6+ Kxf6 26.
Bxa6 {etc. The voluntary withdrawal of the queen from the centre allows Black
to unexpectedly sharpen the situation to his advantage.}) 20... g5 $1 {The
start of a bold manoeuvre, based on Black's domination of the centre.} (20...
Qd8 $6 {and after} 21. Qg4 a5 22. h4 h5 23. Qd4 Ne7 24. Bg5 Bxf3 25. Bf6+ $1
Kh7 26. Qxd8 Rhxd8 27. Bxf3 {he was forced to turn to passive defence.}) (20...
Ba6 21. Bxa6 Qxa6 22. Be3 Nd3 {with equality, Gelfand-Oll, Vilnius 1988.
Although the correct path for Black had been demonstrated before the players
in these games were even born!}) 21. Qg4 (21. Nxg5 $5 hxg5 22. Qxg5+ Kf8 23.
Bf3 $1 (23. Rc4 $2 Ba6 24. Rh4 Rxh4 25. Qxh4 Bxe2 26. Qh8+ Ke7 27. Qxc8 Bxf1
28. Bg5+ f6 29. exf6+ Nxf6 {and wins}) 23... Rg8 $1 {could have cast doubts on
his dashing attack;} (23... Ne7 24. Qf6 Ng6 25. Be3 $1 Bxf3 26. Qxf3) (23...
Nd3 24. Rxc8+ Bxc8 25. h4 $1 Ba6 26. Be4 {White would probably have sufficient
compensation for the material given up). However, in any case there would have
been considerable scope here for flights of fantasy. But Ivkov, hardly
surprisingly, was thinking of creating positions with other, more earthly
categories...})) 21... Ne4 $3 {[%csl Ge4,Gd5][%cal Gb7d5,Gd5e4] The point of
Larsen's pretty idea.} 22. Rxc8 $2 {An incorrect exchange of this active rook,
which could have led to problems due to the loss of control of the c-file.} (
22. Rcd1 $1) 22... Rxc8 23. Qxe4 Nf4 24. Qe3 Qxe3 25. fxe3 Nxe2+ 26. Kf2 g4 $2
(26... Ba6 $1 27. Rb1 Rc2 28. Ke1 g4 29. Nd4 Nxd4 30. exd4 Bd3 {, condemning
White to the passive defence of a highly unpleasant position.}) 27. Ng1 $1 (27.
Ne1 Ba6 28. Bxb4 Rc1 29. Rh1 Rb1 30. b3 Rb2 {. Larsen probably did not see a
great difference between this position and the one that could have arisen
after 26...Ba6!, but.. .}) 27... Nxg1 28. Rc1 $3 {A wonderful saving find:
without the rook invasion at c2, Black's winning chances quickly evaporate.}
Rxc1 29. Bxc1 Bxg2 30. Kxg1 Bd5 {The extra pawn in this pure opposite-coloured
bishop ending is faint consolation for the missed opportunity of complete
domination.} 31. Bd2 $1 Bxa2 32. Bxb4 Kg6 33. Kf2 Kf5 34. Bc3 h5 35. Kg3 Kg5
36. h4+ $1 {Now the draw is obvious.} Kf5 37. Bd4 a5 38. Bc3 a4 39. Bd4 Ke4 40.
Kf2 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

