{I include the analysis of Renato Quintillano to the lecture because he
explains very well the positions after 5.Qb3 and 5.Nc3. In the main line we
have different opinions and I think for the readers will be interesting and
useful to check his analysis.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 $5 {I
remember back when I was a child, this move was considered to be harmless
against the Slav because Black develops the bishop and gets a "solid Catalan
without the bad bishop". This was more than 10 years ago though, and recently
this move gained a lot of popularity among strong players, as White doesn't
seek advantage from the very first move, but instead looks for a complicated
positional battle in the middlegame. Another point of this move is that the
game may transpose into other openings, as we shall see.} Bf5 {I would like to
suggest two options to face this line. This is the move to keep the game "Slav
style".} ({I checked} 4... Bg4 $5 {, which seems interesting, but from a
practical point of view. I think after} 5. Bg2 ({Black's idea is to provoke} 5.
Ne5 Bf5 {, but I couldn't find an advantage for White here.}) 5... e6 6. O-O
Nbd7 {we have transposed to a kind of Reti-Catalan where White has plenty of
options, so although Black is, of course, solid, I think playing this way
gives much more freedom to the first player.} 7. Nc3 (7. b3) (7. Qb3) (7. Nbd2)
(7. cxd5) (7. h3)) ({But I like} 4... dxc4 $5 5. Bg2 Nbd7 $1 {The goal here is
not necessarily to keep the pawn, but since it will take White some moves to
regain the material, Black can develop in the meantime.} ({It is possible to
play materialistically as well.} 5... b5 $5 6. O-O Bb7 7. Ne5 e6 {, when the
game transposes to the actual Catalan Opening.} 8. a4 a6 9. b3 $5 {, with a
complicated battle ahead. Practice has shown that White has great compensation
for the pawn.}) 6. O-O (6. a4 {is a clever idea, aiming to attack the pawn and
answer Nb6 with a4-a5, so Black should play} a5) (6. Qc2 {and} Nb6 7. Nbd2 g6 {
likely transpose.}) 6... g6 $1 {With this move we enter Grunfeld territory. I
like this way of development because the bishop seems more useful on the long
diagonal than on its natural square e7, as it helps Black to press White's
centre in the future. White can just play to regain the pawn on c4, but that
usually allows Black to finish his development without problems. The most
ambitious ideas for the first player are related to building a strong centre
e4/d4 first and later recapturing the pawn, playing for a space advantage, but
this usually leads to the exchange of one or two pieces, when Black should be
also fine.} 7. Qc2 (7. a4 a5 $1 {Black should secure b6 for the knight.} 8. Na3
{[%csl Ga3] Normally White prefers the route a3-c4 for this knight, as on d2
it would be in the way of the dark-squared bishop.} (8. Nc3 {was played in one
game, in gambit style.} Bg7 9. e4 O-O 10. Qe2 Nb6 11. h3 Ne8 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5,
Ye8d6,Ye8c7,Yc7d5] A typical manoeuvre in this line. The knight can go to d6
and even make it harder for White to regain the pawn c4. Another point is that
Black has f7-f5 to weaken White's centre, and in that case, also c7-d5 becomes
an attractive route for the knight.} 12. Rd1 f5 $5 13. Bg5 {Klemm,D (2241)
-Gauglitz,G (2388)/ BL2-Ost 0708 2007 (9.8)/0-1 After something like} fxe4 14.
Nxe4 h6 15. Bd2 Nd6 16. Ne5 Qe8 $1 17. Nc5 Nd5 $13 {[%cal Yb7b6,Gc8f5] the
position remains complex, but Black found some good squares for his pieces in
the centre.}) 8... Nb6 9. Ne5 Be6 $1 {Another nice point of leaving the pawn
on e7 is that Black is able to support c4 with the bishop.} 10. e4 Bg7 11. Be3
{This is an important moment because White plans either Rc1, regaining the
pawn, or f2-f4, with potential pressure on the kingside. Therefore Black plays}
Nfd7 $1 {, which is good against both ideas.} 12. Nxd7 (12. f4 $6 Nxe5 13. dxe5
{[%cal Ye3b6,Yf4f5]} Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Nxa4 15. f5 {Black correctly decided to
sacrifice the piece here.} Nxb2 $1 16. fxe6 {Niemi,K (2342)-Puuska,H (1928)/
Naantali Avoin op 2017 (4)/ 1-0 , but the best continuation now was} fxe6 {
, when Black will have at least four (!) pawns for the piece.} 17. Rb1 Bxe5 18.
Bh3 b5 19. Bxe6 Rd8 20. Bf7+ Kd7 21. Bb6 Ra8 $17 {[%csl Ya5,Yb5,Yc4,Yc6][%cal
Gh8b8]}) (12. d5 $2 {looks aggressive but it is just bad.} Nxe5 13. dxe6 Qxd1
14. Rfxd1 Nxa4 $17) 12... Bxd7 13. Rc1 {Fominykh,M (2313)-Yefimov,M (2050)/
Pardubice Czech op-A 21st 2010 (7)/1-0} (13. Qe2 {Rozum,I (2554)-Baghdasaryan,
V (2372)/ Moscow op-A 2015 (6)/1/2-1/2} c3 $5 14. bxc3 Nxa4 15. c4 c5 $1 $132)
13... Be6 $1 {White still has some work to regain the pawn now.} 14. d5 $5 (14.
Qc2 {is too slow.} O-O 15. Rfd1 Qd6 $1 {[%csl Gb4]} 16. Bf1 Qb4 17. Nxc4 Bxc4
18. Bxc4 {, when Black has the pleasant choice between simplifying to an equal
ending and going for a double-edged position a pawn up.} Qxa4 $5 $13) 14...
cxd5 15. Bxb6 Qxb6 16. exd5 Bf5 17. Nxc4 Qb4 18. b3 O-O $13 {[%csl Yf5,Yg7]
[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] The position should be balanced, but unclear seems a more
correct evaluation, as both sides can play for an advantage.}) 7... Nb6 8. Nbd2
{This is a calmer approach, but White keeps the possibility of playing e2-e4.}
(8. e4 Bg7 9. a4 a5 {[%csl Ga4,Ya5] The inclusion of a4/a5 is useful for both
sides: White can take advantage of the Nb6 hanging in some variations, and
Black can use the b4-square.} 10. Rd1 (10. Na3 O-O 11. h3 (11. Rd1 Be6 12. h3 {
, preparing Be3.} (12. Be3 {Atalik,E (2461)-Mammadzada,G (2426)/TUR-chT Ankara
2018 (5.4)/0-1} h6 13. Ne5 Ng4 $1 {This is a nice point: Black can force
exchanges.} 14. Nxg4 Bxg4 15. Rd2 Be6 $1 16. Bf1 Qd6 17. Nxc4 Nxc4 18. Bxc4
Bxc4 19. Qxc4 {Although White kept a little space advantage because of his
centre, the simplifications were helpful for Black, who has no problem
organizing the pieces here.} Rfd8 20. Rad1 Rac8 21. Qb3 Rd7 22. d5 cxd5 23.
Rxd5 Qe6 $1 $11) (12. Ng5 $6 {Korchmar,V (2405) -Mammadzada,G (2336)/Moscow
Aeroflot op-B 14th 2015 (9)/1/2-1/2 White's last move was a waste of time, as
after} Bd7 13. Nxc4 $2 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 h6 {, he simply loses a pawn.}) 12... Ne8
$1 {This move is very important to regroup the pieces and keep the chance of
fighting for the centre with f7-f5. Otherwise, Black's position would be
cramped and unpleasant.} 13. Ng5 $1 {The most direct way to regain the pawn
without allowing Black's counterplay.} (13. Be3 Nd6 14. Bf1 Kh8 $1 15. Nd2 f5
$132) 13... Bc8 $1 {Black should keep this bishop.} (13... Qc8 $2 14. Nxe6 Qxe6
15. Rb1 $1 $36 {[%cal Yb2b3] , with a strong initiative for White. (Marin)})
14. Nxc4 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 e5 $1 {At the right moment Black fights for the centre.}
16. Nf3 (16. d5 $6 {doesn't seem good, as the pawn can be easily blocked.} h6
17. Nf3 Nd6 18. Qc2 cxd5 19. Rxd5 Be6 $15 {[%cal Ya8c8,Gd8e7]}) 16... exd4 17.
Nxd4 (17. Bg5 $5 {is given by Marin as a strong continuation.} Bf6 18. Rxd4 Qb6
19. Rd2 Be6 20. Qe2 Bxg5 21. Nxg5 Nc7 22. e5 {[%cal Yg5e4]} Qc5 $5 {White
probably keeps a small advantage. But the only problem for Black is the dark
squares on the kingside, which can be defended by the king, so I think he has
good chances of equalizing.}) 17... Nc7 18. Be3 Qe7 19. Qc1 {Although White
still keeps a bit more space, Black is also solid and has no weaknesses in his
camp.} Qb4 $5 (19... Na6 20. f4 Nb4 $11 {Marin}) 20. Ra3 Re8 21. Rc3 $5 Be6 (
21... Qxa4 22. Rc4 Qa2 23. b3 $44 {[%csl Ga2]}) 22. b3 Na6 23. Rdd3 Qe7 {
[%cal Ya6b4] After some inaccuracies from both sides and a tense battle, the
game was eventually drawn in Ding, L (2759)-Giri, A (2769)/Shenzhen Du Te Cup
2017 (7) /1/2-1/2}) 11... Ne8 $1 {Again this move forces some action by White.}
12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Be6 14. Qc3 Nc7 $5 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Yc7a6,Ya6b4] the
knight heads to b4 now, so White tried to prevent this plan with} 15. Bd2 $6 {
Beshukov, S (2389) -Antal, G (2534)/Budapest Spring op 2018 (7)/1-0 , and
Black missed the chance of} f5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] , winning the d5-square, with a
nice position.}) 10... O-O 11. Na3 Be6 {transposes to Ding-Giri.}) 8... Bg7 9.
e4 ({Grischuk played} 9. Nxc4 {, but this is rather harmless and doesn't pose
problems for Black.} Bf5 10. Qc3 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 O-O 12. Rd1 (12. b4 $6 {doesn't
look good as White is not well developed yet to take concrete actions on the
queenside.} Be4 13. a4 Qd5 14. Qc5 Nd7 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Yd4] , and White has
problems with d4 and c4. (Marin)}) 12... a5 $11 {Having exchanged one knight,
Black doesn't suffer from lack of space, and White's centre is not easy to
advance (Marin).}) (9. Rd1 O-O 10. a4 a5 11. e4 (11. Nxc4 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 Qb6 {
[%cal Yc8e6] seems fine for Black.}) 11... Be6 12. Ne5 {White's position looks
just normal here, but actually the Nd2 is misplaced and this becomes evident
after} (12. Bf1 h6 13. Ne5 Ng4 $1 $132) 12... Ng4 $1 {[%csl Gd4]} 13. Nxg4 $2 (
13. Ndf3 $142) 13... Bxg4 14. Nf3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Bxd4 16. Bh6 e5 $1 17. Bxf8
Qxf8 $17 {[%csl Gb4,Gc5,Yd4][%cal Yf8b4] , when Black has a clear advantage.
Senthil, M (2208)-Girish, A (2399)/Abu Dhabi op 23rd 2016 (5)/0-1}) 9... O-O {
White has an interesting idea here.} 10. a4 a5 11. b3 $5 cxb3 12. Nxb3 $44 {
The pawn seems well compensated by the open files on the queenside and the
space in the centre, also because Black may face some issues in development.}
Nbd7 {Black begins an interesting regroupment.} (12... Ne8 13. Bd2 {[%csl Ya5]
might be annoying.}) 13. Re1 Ne8 $5 {Black intends the manoeuvre Nc7-a6-b4,
but this move also clears the path to open the centre with e7-e5.} 14. Bf4 Nc7
15. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Ya5] By hitting a5, White prevents Na6, but White strikes in
the centre now.} e5 $1 16. Bg5 $5 {Aravindh,C (2578) -Kevlishvili,R (2485) /
Wch U20 57th 2018 (5)/1-0} (16. Bxa5 exd4 {[%cal Yb7b6,Yc6c5] seems already
easier for Black.}) ({But} 16. Rad1 {is simple and good.} exd4 17. Nfxd4 Re8 {
[%cal Gd8e7,Yd7f8] Black's position is slightly uncomfortable now, but he can
organize his pieces and it is not so easy for White to create something
concrete in the meantime, for example} 18. Bxa5 Rxa5 $1 19. Nxa5 Bxd4 20. Rxd4
Ne6 {[%csl Ya5,Yd4]}) 16... Bf6 $1 (16... Qe8 $2 {was played in the game, but
Black was in trouble after} 17. d5 $1 $16) 17. Bh6 (17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. d5 {
Black was maybe worried about this position, but he can just play} Na6 $1 19.
Qc3 cxd5 20. exd5 Nb4 $1 {, and his chances are not worse, for example} 21.
Nxe5 Re8 22. f4 Qb6+ 23. Kh1 Nxe5 24. fxe5 Bf5 $132 {[%cal Gb4d3,Ya8c8]}) 17...
Re8 18. Rad1 exd4 (18... Qe7 $6 19. d5 Na6 20. d6 $1 {[%csl Yd6] This pawn can
be annoying.}) 19. Nbxd4 Qe7 $13 {White's compensation is still there, but I
think Black has chances to slowly unravel his game by moves like Nc5, Ne5,
Na6-b4 etc.}) 5. Nc3 {White has some different move orders in this line, but
lately, the text has been mostly played, leaving the bishop on f1 for a while.}
(5. Bg2 {remains the main move in the database.} e6 6. O-O Nbd7 {Since 7.Nc3
transposes to the next note, I checked rare ideas for White here:} 7. b3 {
This is a promising set-up when the light-squared bishop is on c8 or b7, but
in this case, it is just harmless, as the bishop is much better placed on f5
and Black develops his pieces without any problems.} (7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 (8.
Qb3 Qb6 9. Qe3+ $5 {This check hardly poses any serious problem for Black.} Be7
10. Nc3 h6 {[%cal Yf5e6]} 11. Nh4 Bh7 $1 {Now this is the right square for the
bishop, anticipating f4-f5.} 12. Bh3 {this is the only way to find some sense
in White's previous moves, but after} Qd8 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 O-O 15. Qf3 Bd6
$11 {Thybo, J (2479)-Skytte, R (2387)/Odense IM-A 2017 (2)/1/2-1/2 , the
bishops don't look so strong in this structure and Black is solid.}) 8... Bd6 {
After the exchange on d5, Black can develop this bishop more actively.} 9. Nh4
Be6 $1 {Now this is the best way to face the f4-f5-advance.} 10. f4 $5 {
The only way to pose some problems for Black's set-up.} (10. Qc2 O-O 11. Nf5 {
Black can of course exchange on f5 again or simply play} Bc7 $5 {, and the
knight needs constant support on f5.} 12. Bf4 $6 Bxf4 13. gxf4 Nb6 14. Ng3 {
Sergeev,V (2426) -Shinkevich,V (2457)/ St Petersburg White Nights op 2003 (9)/
0-1} Re8 15. e3 Nc4 $1 $17 {[%cal Yc4d6] , and Black has a good play on the
light squares.}) (10. f3 $6 {[%cal Ye2e4] Building a strong centre seems a
natural idea, but there is a drawback...} O-O 11. e4 Be7 $1 {[%csl Gh4] The
knight on the edge is in trouble.} 12. e5 Ne8 13. f4 $5 Bxh4 14. f5 $1 {
The only way to create some imbalance for the pawn, but this is still good for
Black.} Bxf5 15. Rxf5 Be7 16. Qg4 g6 $15 {[%cal Ge8g7]}) 10... Nb6 11. f5 Bd7
12. Bg5 Be7 13. Qd3 {[%csl Yf5] It is necessary to protect f5 in order to
bring the knight back.} O-O 14. Nf3 Ne4 $1 {The following exchanges are more
or less forced now.} 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Ne5 Nxc3 17. bxc3 f6 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 $11 {
[%cal Ya8e8,Gb6c8,Gc8d6] Hug, W (2470)-Jussupow,A (2680)/Hofmann Cup
Baden-Baden rapid 1995 (5)/1/2-1/2 , and Black had no problems.}) 7... Bd6 {
I prefer this square for the bishop, as the queen can go to e7 later.} 8. Bb2 (
8. Nc3 h6 9. Nd2 {[%cal Ge2e4] Preparing the advance e2-e4 is usually a good
idea for White, but Black has a little trick here.} O-O 10. e4 $6 Bb4 $1 {
[%csl Gc3,Ye4] ;Lehner,O (2407) -Sebenik, M (2534)/AUT-chT 1718 2017 (2.2)/0-1
In two games White ended up a pawn down as he was not able to deal with the
attacks on c3 and e4.}) 8... O-O 9. Nbd2 {[%cal Gf3e5] White aims to keep e5
under control.} (9. Nc3 Qe7 10. Nd2 Rfd8 $1 {[%csl Yd4,Gd8] A nice move, which
makes the e4-advance a bit risky for White, as the d4-pawn would become a
target.} 11. Re1 h6 12. e3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Since e3-e4 doesn't look so
appealing now, White tried to close the game with} 13. c5 Bc7 14. f4 {, but
Black found a way to unbalance the game:} Ba5 $1 15. a3 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Ne4 {
[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd7f6] , and Black initiated play on the light squares in
