h6 {As the light-squared bishop is a strong piece here, Black doesn't want to
worry about Nh4.} 10. Ne5 a5 $5 {this advance is a typical idea in these
structures. It is a good way to create practical problems for White without
provoking serious changes in the structure.} 11. a3 ({The following game is a
nice example of how dangerous the rook pawn can be.} 11. Re1 a4 $1 12. Nxd7
Qxd7 13. e4 $2 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 Bb4 $1 16. Re3 a3 $1 17. Bc1 Rfd8
$17 {[%csl Rd4] The pawn is lost. Velez Betancourt,N (2282)-Van Foreest,J 
(2468)/ Paramaribo Srefidensi 2nd 2014 (4)/ 0-1}) 11... Qe7 (11... Bc7 $5 {
[%cal Gd7e5] is another option, preparing to take on e5 with the knight.}) 12.
e3 (12. f3 $2 {[%cal Ge2e4] was played in one game, but Black took the chance
and provoked favourable changes in the structure.} Nxe5 $1 13. dxe5 Bc5+ 14.
Kh1 Nd7 15. f4 {[%csl Gb2,Gg2] Both White's bishops seem restricted now.} Rfd8
16. cxd5 cxd5 {Lyrberg,P (2425) -Barua,D (2520)/Linares Anibal op 03rd 1996/0-1
} 17. Nf3 Be4 18. Qd2 Nb8 $1 $15 {[%cal Yb8c6]}) 12... Rfd8 13. f4 {Leon
Valdes,J (2304)-Lopez Linares,L (2087)/ Montreal Varennes op 2018 (5)/1-0} (13.
Qe2 Bxe5 $1 {Often Black gets a nice position when White is forced to take
with the d-pawn on e5.} 14. dxe5 Ne4 15. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 16. Rfd1 Nc5 $15 {
[%csl Gd3] ;Santos,J (2370)-Cuijpers,F (2425)/ EU-Cup Gr2 Strasbourg 1994/0-1})
13... Ne4 $5 {This position seems equal, as both sides have their knights on
good outposts.} 14. Nxe4 (14. g4 $6 {Moves like this can be risky.} Nxd2 15.
Qxd2 Bh7 16. Nxd7 {Otherwise Nf6-e4.} Qxd7 $11 {Although the position looks
