exd4 16. Ne2 Nxc5 17. Qd1 e5 $17 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5,Ge5] , when the strong centre
gave Black great compensation for the piece in Cernousek, L (2410)-Dearing, E 
(2412)/ BCF-chT 1011 (4NCL) 2010 (10.16)/0-1}) 12. Bf4 Qc8 {Now, according to
Marin in the notes of Mamedyarov-Nakamura, the most promising option for White
seems to be} 13. Bd6 $5 $146 {Now the question is: Will White be able to keep
a firm control in the centre, or will Black manage to open lines with
counterplay.} ({That game went} 13. exd5 $6 Nxd5 $1 14. Nxd5 cxd5 $1 {[%csl
Gc6][%cal Yb8c6] I feel this is an improved version for Black, as we have seen
many games in which the knight is already in d7 and Black has to invest two
tempos with the manoeuvre Nb8-c6.} 15. O-O-O $5 (15. Be2 Nc6 16. Rd1 {Black
has the same idea as in the game here.} g5 $1 17. Be3 f5 {[%cal Ye8f7,Ye7f6]})
({Also harmless is} 15. Bxb8 $2 Rxb8 16. Bb5+ Kf8 {, as losing the right to
castle is not a problem for Black in this position.} 17. Rc1 a6 18. Be2 f5 $15
{[%csl Gd4][%cal Ye7f6,Yf8f7]}) 15... Nc6 16. Kb1 {Mamedyarov probably thought
this position could offer some practical problems for Black because castling
on the kingside looks very dangerous, but Nakamura creatively found another
safe square to the king:} g5 $1 17. Be3 f5 $1 {[%cal Ye7f6,Ge8f7] We have seen
this idea in other games as well, the pawns on f5/g5 prevent any expansion by
White on the kingside, while the king is safe at f7 and Black can exert
pressure on d4. I should add that in this position White is deprived of
another typical idea - the expansion on the queenside with b4-b5 - because
that would compromise his king's safety, which means that Black has no
problems left whatsoever.} 18. g4 (18. f4 $5 {seems safer, but Black is at
least ok after} g4 19. h3 $5 Bf6 20. Bg2 gxh3 21. Rxh3 Rxh3 22. Bxh3 Qd7 {
[%cal Ye8f7,Ga8h8]}) 18... f4 $1 19. Bf2 Kf7 20. Re1 {Now, Mamedyarov decided
to play for some pressure on the e-file, but Black answered} b6 $1 {, when his
initiative was faster in Mamedyarov,S (2760)-Nakamura,H (2772)/Gashimov
Memorial-A 1st 2014 (8)/ 0-1} 21. cxb6 $2 Rb8 $1 $40) ({White also played to
close the position in one game:} 13. Bg2 Nbd7 14. e5 Ng8 15. Be3 {[%cal Yf3f4]
, but this relieves the tension in the centre and allows Black to free the
queenside with} b6 $1 16. cxb6 {Danchevski,O (2356)-Ortega,L (2478)/ EU-Cup
31st Skopje 2015 (6.3)/1/2-1/2} axb6 17. O-O c5 18. Nb5 Qb8 $1 19. Qc2 Nh6 20.
Bf2 O-O $13) 13... b6 $1 {Black has to do something before White consolidates
the position of the Bd6, with an annoying grip in the centre.} (13... Bxd6 $2
14. cxd6 $16 {[%cal Ye4e5]}) ({and} 13... Nbd7 14. e5 $14 {[%csl Gd6] lead to
a pleasant advantage for White.}) 14. Bxe7 {I've checked other options for
White as well. An advice that I like to give black players in this position is
to forget about the engine's evaluation. It usually prefers White here, due to
his space advantage and Black's king being in the centre. However, the
analysis shows that Black has enough dynamic resources. From a practical point
of view, the position is very tense and difficult to play for both sides. As
usual, the lines are not entirely forced, but they provide good examples of
the ideas and resources available.} (14. Qa3 {Black is able to defend the
bishop now.} Qb7 $1 (14... bxc5 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 16. Qxc5+ Kd8 {transposes to the
mainline.}) 15. e5 $5 (15. Bxe7 Qxe7 $1 {looks harmless for Black.}) (15. Qb3
Qc8 $5) 15... Nfd7 $1 {[%csl Yc5,Ye5] Black has to keep some pressure on c5
and e5.} 16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17. b4 $5 (17. cxb6+ {is actively met by} c5 $1 {
, which basically forces an endgame.} 18. dxc5 axb6 19. c6+ Rxa3 20. cxb7 Ra7
21. Nb5 Rxb7 22. f4 {[%csl Gb7] The rook seems misplaced, but Black is about
to free the position with} f6 $1 23. exf6+ gxf6 24. Rc1 Na6 $11 {[%cal Yb7b8]})
17... a5 $1 18. Rb1 b5 $1 (18... axb4 $2 19. Qxb4 b5 20. a4 $16 {is still in
White's favour.}) 19. bxa5 $1 Qc7 20. Qc1 $1 {[%cal Yc1g5,Ga2a4] White has
ideas on both flanks now.} Rxa5 {White can either try to disturb Black's
development or just slowly improve his position, but in both cases Black has
chances of equalizing.} 21. Be2 (21. Qg5+ Kf8 22. Bd3 Ra3 $1 {[%cal Yc7a5]
This immediately creates concrete problems for White.} 23. Rb3 Rxb3 24. axb3 f6
$1 25. exf6 gxf6 26. Qd2 (26. Qxg6 $2 {is bad due to} Qa5 27. Kd2 Qb4 $1 {
, when Black is already better.} 28. Qg4 e5 $17) 26... Kg7 27. O-O e5 $1 28.
Ne2 Re8 29. b4 Nf8 30. Ra1 Nbd7 $13 {[%cal Yf8e6] Although the engine keeps
preferring White's position, I think in practice things should not be so easy,
as Black keeps the tension in the centre.}) 21... Re8 22. Kf2 (22. Qg5+ $2 {
just helps Black now:} Kf8 23. h4 $2 {Too slow.} f6 $1 24. exf6 Nxf6 $17 {
[%cal Ye6e5,Ga5a3] , and Black's initiative comes first.}) 22... Na6 $1 {
A multi-purpose move.} 23. a3 (23. f4 $6 {is careless.} b4 $1 24. Bxa6 bxc3 {
[%csl Ga2,Ga6]} 25. Be2 Rxa2 26. Qxc3 Rea8 $13) 23... Qa7 $1 {We can already
see what is coming here: Black intends to sacrifice a piece in order to
destroy White's centre.} 24. Kg2 Naxc5 $1 25. dxc5 Rxa3 {[%csl Rc5,Re5] White
needs to be very careful in this kind of position, as Black is threatening to
grab too many pawns for the piece.} 26. Qd2 (26. Re1 $2 Qxc5 $17) 26... Nxc5
27. Qd4 (27. Rhc1 $6 Nb3) 27... Nd7 $1 28. Qxa7 (28. Qh4+ Kf8 29. Qh8+ Ke7 30.
Qh4+ $11) 28... Rxa7 {, and the endgame is complicated, but White should not
underestimate Black's passed pawns, for example} 29. f4 Rb8 {[%cal Yb5b4,Yc6c5]
} 30. Rb4 $8 f6 $1 31. exf6+ gxf6 32. Rc1 Kd6 $15) (14. e5 Nfd7 15. Na4 $5 {
is another option, but in this case Black can quickly hit in the centre after}
Bxd6 $1 16. cxd6 (16. exd6 e5 $1 17. dxe5 b5 $1 18. Nc3 Nxe5 19. Ne2 Nbd7 20.
Qe3 O-O $13 {[%cal Yf8e8]}) 16... c5 $1 17. Rc1 Nc6 $1 {A possible line now
could be} 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Nxc5 Ncxe5 $1 20. Bb5 O-O {, still with a complex
fight, but Black enjoys more freedom for his pieces, for example} 21. Qe3 {
[%cal Yc5d7]} Qd8 22. Nxd7 Nxd7 23. Rc7 Nb6 24. Qc5 Qf6 $1 $132) 14... Kxe7 15.
Qa3 $5 ({White can play the materialistic} 15. cxb6 axb6 16. Qxb6 (16. Na4 Nbd7
{doesn't change much.}) 16... Nbd7 17. Qb4+ $1 ({After} 17. Qb3 dxe4 $1 18.
fxe4 Qc7 $44 {[%cal Yh8b8,Ge6e5] Black probably gets more chances of activity
with the queens on the board.}) 17... c5 18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Qxc5+ Nxc5 20. exd5
Nxd5 21. Nxd5+ exd5 {White won a pawn, but his pieces are underdeveloped and
Black's piece activity provides compensation.} 22. a3 ({After} 22. Rc1 $6 Ne6
23. a3 Rhb8 24. Rc2 Nd4 $1 {it is already White who fights for equality.} 25.
Rf2 Rb3 $15 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Ya8b8]}) 22... Rhb8 23. O-O-O $5 Na4 $1 24. b4 (
24. Rd2 Rb3 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Ya8b8]}) 24... Rc8+ $1 25. Kd2 {The king should
go back to the centre now and Black keeps White busy with some threats.} Rc3
26. Ra1 Rac8 $1 {, and White is still not able to make use of the pawn.} 27.
Bb5 (27. Bd3 Nb2 $1 28. Rhe1+ Kd6 29. Bb5 Rc2+ 30. Ke3 Nc4+ 31. Bxc4 R8xc4 32.
Re2 d4+ 33. Kf2 d3 $1 34. Rxc2 dxc2 35. Rc1 Rc3 $11) 27... Rc2+ 28. Ke3 R8c3+
29. Kf4 Nb2 $1 $13) 15... bxc5 $5 {Here I differ from Marin's notes.} ({
He gives} 15... b5 16. exd5 (16. Bg2 a5 17. Ne2 Nbd7 $11) 16... exd5 17. Nxb5
$1 cxb5 18. c6+ {with a complicated fight, although he thinks Black should be
more worried.}) 16. Qxc5+ ({White can try the intermediate} 16. exd5 $5 cxd5 $1
{and now exploit the c-file.} 17. Rc1 {Black should hurry with his king now.} (
{But not} 17. Qxc5+ $2 Qxc5 18. dxc5 Nc6 $17 {[%csl Yd5,Ye6][%cal Gh8c8,Ga8b8]
, when the central pawns are much strong than White's queenside.}) 17... Kf8 $5
18. Na4 Nbd7 19. Nxc5 (19. dxc5 Kg8 {[%cal Gd7e5]}) 19... Kg8 $1 20. Ba6 Qc7
21. O-O Nxc5 22. Rxc5 (22. dxc5 d4 $1 23. b4 Nd5 $132) 22... Qb6 23. Bb5 Kh7
$14 {[%cal Ya8b8,Yh8d8,Gf6e8] Although this position may offer some small
advantage for White, I believe Black is able to neutralize the pressure along
the c-file with correct play.}) 16... Kd8 $1 {[%csl Yd8] The question now is
whether White has enough time to take advantage of Black's centralized king.} (
16... Ke8 17. Nb5 $1 $16) 17. Rc1 Nbd7 18. Qa3 {In this position, Black has
the nice move} ({The endgame arising after} 18. Qa5+ Qc7 19. Qxc7+ Kxc7 {
is probably equal.} 20. e5 (20. Nb5+ Kb6 21. Nd6 Rhf8 $11 {[%cal Yf6e8]}) 20...
Ng8 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7] , and Black's position remains solid, for example} 21.
Nb5+ Kb6 22. Nd6 f6 23. Nf7 $5 {, aiming to misplace the rook, but that is
only a temporary problem.} (23. f4 Ne7) 23... Rh7 24. f4 Ne7 {[%cal Ye7f5]} 25.
Bd3 Rf8 26. Nd6 fxe5 27. dxe5 Nf5 $11) 18... Qb8 $1 {[%csl Yb8] Getting out of
any attacks on the c-file, defending against the possible invasion of the
White queen on d6 and supporting ideas on both flanks.} 19. b4 $5 {[%csl Yc5,
Gc6] The logical explanation of this move is to fix the squares c6 and c5, but
White also prevents a nice idea from Black.} ({For example, after} 19. e5 Ng8
20. Bd3 a5 $1 {[%cal Yb8b4] , Black forces the exchange of queens on b4, with
a nice position.} 21. Na4 Qb4+ 22. Qxb4 axb4 23. b3 Ne7 24. f4 Kc7 25. Rc2 Ra5
$1 26. Kd2 Rha8 {[%cal Yd7b6]} 27. Ra1 {,and Black can even become optimistic
with} Nc8 $5 {, when White should repeat with} 28. Rac1 Ne7 29. Ra1 $11) (19.
exd5 $5 Nxd5 $1 20. Nxd5 cxd5 21. Ba6 Qb6 $1 $132) (19. Na4 {[%csl Yc6] aims
to win a tempo by attacking c6, but still} a5 $1 {is the right move} 20. e5 (
20. Rxc6 dxe4 $13) 20... Ng8 21. Rxc6 $2 Ne7 22. Rc1 Nf5 $15 {[%cal Gf5g3,
Gf5d4]}) 19... Qb6 $1 20. Rd1 (20. b5 Rc8 $1) 20... dxe4 $1 {This is good to
make White's centre more vulnerable.} 21. fxe4 Rb8 22. b5 Rc8 $5 {This seems
the safest option for Black. Both sides have their kings in the centre, which
makes the position very difficult to control.} ({But the paradoxic} 22... e5 $1
{looks playable too, for example} 23. dxe5 Ng4 $1 24. Be2 Qf2+ 25. Kd2 Ngxe5
$13) 23. e5 (23. bxc6 Qxc6 {[%csl Yc3,Ye4]} 24. Rd3 e5 $1 $13 ({But not} 24...
Nxe4 $2 25. Bg2 f5 26. O-O $16)) 23... Nd5 24. Nxd5 cxd5 25. Be2 Rc2 $1 $13 {
With a still complicated position, although Black is at least ok due to his
activity.} *

