Bg2 Nd7 4. c4 e6 5. O-O Ngf6 6. d4 c6 {After some transposition, we reach the
position that can be reached by the move order 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.g3
Bg4 5.Bg2 e6 6.0-0 Nbd7} 7. Nbd2 Be7 8. b3 O-O 9. Bb2 a5 10. a3 Qb6 11. Re1
Rfd8 12. c5 {This move wins some space but doesn't give White any advantage.
Black should prepare one of the two possible pawn breaks in the arising
structure: b7-b6 or e6-e5. White's b2-bishop is very passive, and White can't
easily prepare the b4-b5, and also the e4-break doesn't give anything.} (12.
Nh4 {can be suggested as an alternative, with the idea h3 and g4, but now
Black can blow the centre with} c5) 12... Qa7 13. b4 b6 {it is time, Black's
pieces are almost optimally placed} 14. Qc2 Bf5 15. Qc3 h6 16. Rec1 Rab8 17.
Nb3 $2 {Now too many pieces are hanging on the b-file, and Dreev use this} Ne4
18. Qe3 axb4 19. axb4 Qb7 20. Ba3 bxc5 (20... Bf6 21. Rab1 (21. cxb6 Qxb6 $17 {
[%csl Rb4,Rd4][%cal Rb8a8,Rd8c8]}) 21... Ra8 $1 $19) 21. dxc5 e5 22. b5 Qxb5 $2
(22... Re8 $1) 23. Nfd4 exd4 24. Nxd4 Qb7 25. Nxf5 Bg5 26. f4 Bf6 27. Ra2 $2 ({
White missed} 27. Bxe4 dxe4 28. Nd6 $11 {with double-edged position with equal
chances}) 27... Re8 $1 {now it is over} 28. Qd3 Qa7 29. Rac2 Qa4 30. Nd6 Rb3
31. Nxe8 Rxd3 32. exd3 Qd4+ 33. Kh1 Nf2+ 34. Rxf2 Qxf2 35. Nxf6+ Nxf6 0-1

