{This is a recent game that impressed me a lot. White chooses an ambitious
setup, but Black manages to neutralize the pressure and even win.} 1. d4 d5 2.
c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bg4 5. Ne5 Bf5 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. cxd5 Qxb3 8. axb3 Nxd5 {
very interesting structure. White's structure is damaged, but he has a mobile
pawn centre.} 9. Bg2 Nb4 10. O-O Nc2 {going for some wild compensation. I
should admit that the computer approves Black's play} 11. Ra4 f6 12. e4 Bc8 {
The position is highly unusual. All Black's pieces are on the 8th rank except
the knight on c2, but somehow Black is doing OK here.} 13. Nf3 Be6 14. d5 {
otherwise, White will lose the initiative.} cxd5 15. Ne1 Nxe1 16. Rxe1 Bd7 (
16... d4 $1 {Is another way for Black to equalize} 17. e5 Nc6 18. exf6 Kf7 $11)
17. exd5 Bxa4 18. bxa4 {This position is dynamically balanced. In the later
stage, White makes some inaccuracies, and Black manages to convert his extra
material.} e5 19. dxe6 Nc6 20. Nc3 Bb4 21. Rd1 Rd8 22. Nd5 O-O 23. Bf4 Rfe8 24.
Bc7 Rc8 25. Bf3 (25. Bf4 $5) 25... Ne7 26. Bf4 Nxd5 27. Bxd5 Re7 28. Kf1 Rd8
29. g4 Kf8 30. Ke2 Ree8 31. g5 Ke7 32. Kf3 b6 33. Ke4 Bc5 34. Rd2 Rf8 35. gxf6+
gxf6 36. h4 Rg8 37. Bc7 Rc8 38. Bf4 Rg4 39. Kf3 h5 40. Bg3 Rxa4 41. b3 Rd4 42.
Rxd4 Bxd4 43. Ke4 Bc5 44. Kf5 Bd6 0-1

