{[%evp 0,82,29,23,15,-16,26,26,31,-21,-2,-3,41,29,25,25,28,28,35,47,41,31,51,
56,43,43,41,26,15,15,31,10,18,3,18,16,18,-2,9,22,35,33,10,-7,-7,-15,-9,-5,-1,
10,-6,0,-42,-41,6,2,4,-63,-50,-62,-34,-58,-51,-57,-22,-10,-10,-52,-45,-37,-28,
-23,-4,-4,0,0,-10,0,0,0,0,0,15,15,15]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bf5
5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 $1 {This is considered to be the most dangerous move.} (6. Bg2
{will be met by} h6 $1 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Nd2 Be7 9. e4 dxe4 10. Ndxe4 Nxe4 11.
Nxe4 {We achieved a typical structure "d4" against "c6" and "e6". It is quite
playable for Black because another pawn can't protect the d4-pawn.}) 6... dxc4
$1 {This is my main recommendation. The idea is not new, and you can see it in
Classical Slav after the moves 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.a4 Bf5 6.
Nh4 e6} 7. Nxf5 exf5 {We achieve a very interesting structure. Black gives up
his bishop pair and doubles his pawns, but in exchange gets excellent control
of the important e4-square and the semi-open e-file.} 8. e3 Nbd7 (8... b5 $4 9.
Bg2 $18) 9. Bxc4 Nb6 10. Bb3 Be7 (10... h5 11. Qd3 Qd7 12. Bd2 h4 13. O-O-O
O-O-O 14. f3 Bd6 15. Rhg1 hxg3 16. hxg3 Bc7 17. Kb1 Kb8 18. Bc1 Rhe8 19. e4
fxe4 20. fxe4 Qg4 21. Bf4 Re7 22. Rgf1 Qg6 23. Bc2 Red7 24. Qe3 Qg4 25. a4 Bxf4
26. gxf4 Nc4 27. Qf2 Qe6 28. Qg1 Qe7 29. Bb3 Na5 30. Bc2 Nc4 31. Bb3 {1/2-1/2 
(31) Mamedyarov,S (2764)-Tomashevsky,E (2701) Baku 2014 CBM 163 [Marin, M]})
11. O-O O-O 12. a3 (12. f3) 12... Qd7 {another typical move in this structure.
Black connects the rooks and prepares to put more pressure against the "d4"
pawn.} 13. Qf3 {I don't like this move, because it is not preparing the
advance e4. One of the most dangerous plans for White is f3-e4.} a5 14. Bd2
Rfe8 15. Rfd1 Bf8 16. Be1 Red8 17. Ne2 Nbd5 18. Nc1 Ne4 {Finally Black manages
to install his knights on e4 and d5 squares.} 19. Nd3 Bd6 20. Rac1 Qe6 21. Nc5
Bxc5 22. dxc5 $1 {Opening the a1-h8 diagonal} (22. Rxc5 {In this structure
with the pawn on d4, Black is just better because White's dark-squared bishop
has no prospects.}) 22... g5 {Typical idea, Black wants to fix the pawn
structure.} 23. Qg2 g4 (23... Qe5 {my engine gives an advantage for Black
after this move, but Saric's play is very natural}) 24. h4 a4 25. Ba2 Qe5 26.
Rd4 Nc7 27. Rcd1 Rxd4 28. Rxd4 Ne6 29. Bxe6 fxe6 30. Qf1 Qxc5 {Black wins a
pawn, but his king is very weak, which gives White enough compensation to
maintain the ballance} 31. Qd3 Qf8 32. Bc3 h5 33. Qc4 Qe7 34. Qd3 Qf8 35. Qc4
Qe7 36. Qd3 Nxc3 37. Qxc3 c5 38. Rd3 Rd8 39. Rxd8+ Qxd8 40. Qxc5 Qd1+ 41. Kh2
Qf3 1/2-1/2

