{I want just briefly to mention to you the Semi-Slav setup against g3 and to
give you some directions here.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 e6 (4...
dxc4 5. Bg2 Nbd7 6. Nc3 e6 7. O-O) 5. Bg2 (5. Nc3) 5... Nbd7 6. Nc3 dxc4 7. O-O
{Various move orders can reach this position} Be7 8. e4 O-O 9. a4 {It is the
most popular and logical move, preventing the advance b7-b5} (9. e5 Nd5 $15 {
White doesn't have sufficient compensation for the sacrificing material.}) (9.
Bf4 {Is an interesting try for White, I think that Black should avoid playing
b6 in this position} Re8 {this is a good waiting move and my preference} (9...
b6 10. d5 $1) 10. a4 a5 {Once again, we avoid playing b6} 11. Qe2 b6 {[%cal
Rc8a6]}) (9. Qe2 {is too slow and Black can defend the pawn} b5) 9... e5 10.
dxe5 Ng4 11. Bf4 Qa5 12. e6 {is critical; you can check the games of Alexey
Dreev with the Black pieces.} (12. Qe2 $2 {Is a well-known mistake} Ndxe5 13.
Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. Qxc4 Be6 $19 {Black is simply winning here}) 12...
fxe6 13. Bh3 Qh5 14. Ng5 Ndf6 15. e5 Nxe5 16. Qxh5 Nxh5 17. Bxe5 Bxg5 18. Ne4 {
With enough compensation for the pawn, but probably not more than that. 0-1 
(66) Girya,O (2464)-Nechaeva,M (2359) Moscow 2020} *

