{Chebanenko Slav is outside the scope of our camp, but I just want to point
you the most reliable approach for Black to meet the g3-setup there.} 1. d4 d5
2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. g3 {The g3 setup is possible here too} b5 {
I prefer to continue in a Chebanenko style. I recommend you to study the games
here. According to modern theory, Black is doing fine.} (5... dxc4 6. Bg2 b5 {
is exactly the position which I want to avoid with Black}) 6. c5 (6. cxd5 cxd5
7. Bg2 e6 8. Bf4 Bb7 9. O-O Be7 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Nb1 Nc6 12. Nbd2 Ne4 13. Nxe4
dxe4 14. Nd2 f5 {1/2-1/2 (41) Can,E (2547)-Solak,D (2622) Biel 2015}) 6... g6
7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Ne5 Be6 10. h3 Nfd7 11. f4 Nxe5 12. fxe5 a5 13. Bf4 {
1/2-1/2 (13) Nielsen,P (2680)-Malakhov,V (2707) Helsingor 2009} *

