{[%evp 0,30,20,26,26,-3,35,30,27,13,13,9,55,37,33,41,39,39,40,50,21,27,17,10,
20,18,13,4,7,21,15,-87,-92]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 a6
6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. O-O ({The immediate} 8. e4 {invites major
complications and makes it easier for Black to reach equality. Still, it was
played by many strong players, so we shoudl consider it seriously:} dxe4 9.
Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 (11. Ke2 Nd7 12. Rd1 O-O 13. Bf4 Be7 14. Rd3 {
1/2 (64) Hracek,Z (2619)-Svetushkin,D (2569) Istanbul 2012} Nf6 15. Qe3 b5 16.
b3 bxc4 17. bxc4 Rc8 $11) 11... Be7 12. g3 Nd7 13. Kg2 O-O 14. Qe2 {1/2 (39)
Vidit,S (2695)-Andreikin,D (2725) Chess.com INT 2019} (14. Rd1 Qc7 15. Bf4 Bd6
$11) 14... c5 15. Rd1 cxd4 16. Rxd4 Qc8 17. Bf4 Rd8 18. Rad1 Qc6 $11) 8... Bb4
9. Bd2 {This is the most common move. The opposition of bishops on the
diagonal e1-a5 can be dangerous for Black in view of tactical ideas ..Nxd5} (9.
a3 {was also tested on the highest level} Bxc3 10. bxc3 ({After} 10. Qxc3 O-O
11. b3 Nbd7 12. a4 Ne4 13. Qc2 Rc8 14. Ba3 Re8 {White's bishop isn't better
than Black's knight is the closed type of position.}) 10... Nbd7 11. a4 O-O 12.
Ba3 Re8 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. c4 Nb6 15. cxd5 Qxd5 $11 {Mozharov,M - Amonatov,F
Moscow 2006}) 9... O-O 10. Rfd1 (10. a3 Bxc3 {I see nothing wrong with this
exchange. Black takes control of e4.} (10... Ba5 $5 11. b4 Bc7 12. e4 Nxe4 13.
Nxe4 dxe4 14. Qxe4 {is also very solid for Black. Still, I slightly prefer
White due to his space advantage.}) 11. Bxc3 Ne4 12. Bb4 Re8 13. a4 a5 14. Ba3
Nd7 15. Rac1 Qb6 $11 {White struggles to find any good plan here. Eventually,
he pushed too hard and was outplayed in Laznicka,V - Bologan,V Poikovsky 2015})
(10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Bxd2 12. Nxd2 exd5 {was tested in many games. Black
doesn't have any problems here.}) 10... Ba5 $1 {Black needs his bishops to be
protected.} (10... Nbd7 $2 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Bxd2 13. dxe6 $18) 11. a4 $5
{This ambitious move was recently successfully employed by many strong players.
} ({After} 11. Rab1 Nbd7 12. b4 Bc7 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 {Black can take
advantage of somewhat weakening b2-b4 with} h6 15. Nc5 (15. a4 e5 $11) 15... b5
$1 $11 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gd7b6]}) 11... h6 $1 {By making this vital move Black
prevents the early b2-b4} ({After} 11... Nbd7 12. b4 Bc7 (12... Bxb4 13. Nxd5
Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bxd2 15. dxc6 $14) 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 {White has a pleasant
space advantage.}) 12. Rab1 {0-1 (42) Kaliadzich,M (2049)-Ziaziulkina,N (2357)
Minsk 2018} Nbd7 13. b4 Bc7 14. e4 Nb6 15. c5 Nxa4 $1 *

