{[%evp 0,75,29,23,27,27,70,31,42,10,59,44,56,45,55,31,40,26,38,42,39,42,44,45,
43,43,43,42,45,38,57,55,60,45,53,33,33,51,57,36,58,55,35,46,43,64,72,65,81,52,
47,49,56,57,44,0,0,0,47,38,61,30,57,36,26,58,58,58,58,70,381,487,516,495,604,
611,653,704]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c6 3. c4 d5 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 Bf5 6. Bd3 Bg6 7.
O-O e6 8. Re1 Nbd7 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Bxe4 12. Rxe4 {Firstly,
we examine Typical Slav structure #1 through 5 illustrative examples. This
game is an example of what can happen if Black does not neutralize White's
space advantage in a timely manner.} Be7 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Qe2 {White makes sure
to hinder the freeing ...c5-break.} Bf6 {The bishop is not placed well on this
square. In upcoming examples, we will see that Black should play ...Re8 in
similar positions, instead.} (14... c5 15. d5 Nf6 16. Re3) 15. Rd1 Qa5 16. b3
Rfd8 {[#] Here, Tomashevsky plays a very instructive plan that shows the
dangers that are hidden for Black in this structure, while also highlighting
drawbacks of the Bf6 move.} 17. h4 $1 $40 Nf8 18. g4 {Thanks to his space
advantage, White launches the kingside pawn storm. Black has cannot break in
the center nor exchange any pieces at the moment, so his position soon becomes
difficult.} Be7 19. g5 Bd6 {Antipov finally embarks on the correct strategy,
but piece exchanges come too late.} 20. Be5 Bxe5 21. Nxe5 Ng6 22. h5 Nxe5 23.
Rxe5 Qc7 {Black has managed to trade off the minor pieces, but White already
has the attacking momentum.} 24. g6 {Tomashevsky goes for a direct assault.} (
24. h6 $5 {would create long term problems for Black king, so it also deserved
attention.}) 24... hxg6 25. hxg6 Rd6 26. Rd3 Rf8 27. Rh3 fxg6 28. Rxe6 Rxd4 29.
Rxg6 Rd6 {Black has survived the worst, yet his position is still unpleasant
to play as White keeps the initiative.} 30. Qh5 Rxg6+ 31. Qxg6 Qf4 32. Qh7+ Kf7
33. Rd3 Qg5+ 34. Kf1 Rd8 $2 {A losing mistake.} ({Apparently, Black would have
good chances to save the game if he had played} 34... Qf6) 35. Rf3+ Ke6 36. Rg3
Qf5 37. Rg6+ Ke5 38. Qxg7+ 1-0

