{[%evp 0,61,27,27,27,6,35,35,31,37,11,-14,39,39,32,32,40,32,45,19,51,53,49,47,
48,51,51,55,55,43,57,52,68,66,69,59,59,49,63,67,53,53,39,41,51,48,56,39,57,39,
27,27,33,21,21,8,25,31,23,23,31,24,27,17]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3
Bf5 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. O-O Bb4 9. a3 Be7 $5 {A small finesse.
Provoking White's a2-a3 seems to be useful in the arising pawn structure.
Sometimes White wants to protect the c4-pawn with b2-b3, which would leave the
a3 and b3 pawns a bit weak.} (9... Ba5 10. b4 Bc7 {is also possible.}) 10. e4
dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nd7 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Rad1 {[#] In this game, the
ex-world champion shows us the correct plan for Black.} Re8 $1 {The main goal
of this important move is to clear the f8-square for ...Nd7-f8-g6 manoeuvre.
Since Black has some issues with a lack of space, he needs to regroup his
pieces. Therefore, the knight goes to g6 so that other pieces, preferably a
rook, can take its place on d7, putting pressure on d4-pawn and preparing one
of the central pawn breaks.} ({In the next game, we will examine another good
plan for Black} 14... a5 $5 15. Rd3 a4 {This way, White would not have the Rb3
possibility from the game.}) 15. Rd3 {This rook lift is an integral part of
White's plan to attack black kingside with his pieces.} Nf8 16. Rb3 $1 {
An interesting inclusion, basically forcing the black queen to assume a
defending role on the queenside.} Qc8 17. Rc1 $6 {A somewhat slow move.} (17.
h4 {was more principled, as in Tomashevsky-Antipov game.}) 17... Ng6 18. Bg3
Qd7 19. h4 h5 {Stopping White's kingside expansion.} 20. Ne5 (20. c5 $5 {
was possible to target the b7-pawn. However, after} Rad8 21. Rc4 Qc8 22. Rcb4
Rd7 {Black is solid enough and d5 is a potential outpost.}) 20... Nxe5 21. Bxe5
{[#] Here, Anand fends away White's attacking attempts with an instructive move
} f6 $1 22. Bg3 Bf8 23. Rd3 Qf7 {Importantly, the queen can defend the
h5-weakness from this safe square.} 24. Bf4 Rad8 25. Rcd1 Bd6 {After this
piece trade, the position is completely equal - weaknesses on d4 and e6 cancel
each other out. Please compare it to game 2.1) where the material balance was
the same, but White's pawns on h5 and g5 made all the difference.} 26. Bxd6
Rxd6 27. a4 Red8 28. b3 R6d7 29. R1d2 Rd6 30. Rd1 R6d7 31. R1d2 1/2-1/2

