{[%evp 0,67,30,30,30,-4,40,40,40,40,50,52,48,32,36,36,36,35,35,35,35,35,38,38,
31,38,38,35,48,37,47,43,43,49,51,26,50,45,40,22,57,48,39,39,39,39,46,64,91,96,
129,146,146,101,101,103,106,86,208,208,204,193,193,193,193,193,548,544,29995,
29996]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. Nf3 Bf5 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6
8. O-O Nbd7 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Be7 11. Bf4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 O-O 13. Rfd1 {
[#] In this game, Black opted for the queenside plan with} a5 $5 14. Rd3 Qb6 {
We can see another point behind Black's previous move: the a6-square will
become a comfortable outpost for the black queen.} (14... a4 $5 {[%cal Rd3b3]}
15. Rad1 Re8 {was another sensible option, preventing the Rd3-b3 manoeuvre
that we saw in Karjakin-Anand and speeding up the usual knight manoeuvre. A
sample line:} 16. Qe2 Nf8 17. Bg3 Ng6 18. d5 exd5 19. cxd5 Bf6 $11) 15. Qe2 a4
{Black has neutralized some of White's space advantage by seizing space on the
queenside himself.} 16. Rad1 Rfe8 17. Qc2 Qa6 18. Ne5 {Black does not mind the
piece exchanges on e5.} ({The most testing continuation would have, once again,
been} 18. h4 {when Black would have a choice of pawn breaks at his disposal:}
c5 (18... b5 $5 19. Ng5 Nf8 $13) {and if} 19. d5 exd5 20. Rxd5 {then} Nf6 $11)
18... Rad8 19. h4 h5 $2 {This seems like an automatic reaction if one has seen
Anand's game. However, the crucial difference compared to that game is that
here black queen is far removed from the kingside and Black should therefore
not have created weaknesses around the king. This decision will prove to have
undesired consequences for Smeets.} ({Instead, the simple piece exchange
strategy} 19... Nxe5 20. Bxe5 Bd6 $11 {would have put Black on the fast track
to full equality.}) 20. Qe2 Nxe5 21. Bxe5 {This position is very similar to
game 2.2.), but with a key difference that the queen on a6 cannot participate
in defence of the weakened kingside. Black has some serious problems to solve.}
Bd6 {The c-pawn is defended indirectly.} (21... Qxc4 22. Bxg7 $1 $18) ({
Black cannot play} 21... f6 {as Anand did in a similar position, due to} 22.
Bc7 $18) 22. b3 $1 axb3 23. axb3 Qa5 $2 {This move loses by force.} ({Black
had to play} 23... Bxe5 24. Qxe5 g6 {even though White could keep attacking
with} 25. g4 $1 hxg4 26. h5 $40) 24. Qxh5 f6 25. c5 $1 Bf8 26. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 27.
Rg3+ Bg7 28. Qg6 Re7 29. h5 {White has an irresistible attack. Black sorely
misses his queen in defense.} Rxd4 30. Rxd4 Qa1+ 31. Kh2 Qxd4 32. h6 Qxf2 33.
hxg7 Qf4 34. Qh7+ $1 1-0

