1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 Bf5 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. O-O
Bb4 9. Bd2 O-O 10. a3 Ba5 {This is a slightly different plan for Black, but
still a good one. Black provokes White into pushing his b-pawn. We will see an
important downside of this pawn expansion shortly.} (10... Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Ne4 {
is a more popular alternative as Black keeps control over the e4-square.} 12.
Bb4 Re8 13. a4 {etc.}) 11. b4 Bc7 12. e4 h6 13. a4 ({In the event of} 13. e5 {
Black would have an important intermezzo} dxc4 14. Qxc4 Nd5 15. Ne4 Nd7 $11 {
White would keep the space advantage, but the transformation of the pawn
structure works a bit more in Black's favour.}) 13... Re8 14. Rfe1 Nxe4 15.
Nxe4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 Nd7 17. Bc3 Nf6 18. Qe2 {[#] White's space advantage seems
even more significant than in the previous examples as he has also expanded
his domain on the queenside. However, GM Postny shows how appearances can be
deceiving as he neutralizes it with a thematic pawn break:} b5 $1 {This is a
pawn sacrifice, but Black will get full compensation for the pawn.} 19. axb5
axb5 20. cxb5 Nd5 21. Bd2 cxb5 22. Qxb5 Bd6 {Black knight is untouchable on
the d5-outpost and white b-pawn can be easily blocked and attacked. Black held
White to an easy draw here.} 23. Qc4 Rc8 24. Qb3 Rb8 25. Ra4 ({In the case of} 
25. b5 Re7 26. Reb1 Reb7 27. Qc4 Qd7 {the pawn falls anyway and it is even
White who has to be careful in the arising endgame.}) 25... Re7 26. Ne5 Bxe5
27. dxe5 Rd7 28. Ra2 Qh4 29. Qg3 1/2-1/2

