-19,-31,-25,-16,-13,-19,-6,-5,7,7,25,20,14,10,14,-3,-3,-9,-4,-10,-5,-17,-21,
-18,-20,-28,-20,-27,-15,-14,-14,30,7,25,20,15,18,-7,-17,-31,-31,-246,-262,-262,
-255,-262,-270,-270,-365,-525,-283,-450,-505,-505,-541,-594,-631,-1593,-717]} 
1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 Bf5 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. O-O
Be7 9. e4 O-O $5 10. b3 (10. Bf4 $1 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nd7 13. Rfe1
Re8 14. Qc2 Qa5 {is almost the same like the text.}) (10. e5 dxc4 11. Qxc4 Nd5
12. Ne4 h6 $13) 10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nd7 13. Bf4 {Like in Catalan
white opts for Bf4.} (13. Bb2 Qa5) 13... Qa5 14. Qc2 Rad8 15. Rad1 Rfe8 16.
Rfe1 Bf6 $6 {[#] Now we have an equilibrium over the board, White has more
space but Black has a better bishop. Kuljasevic, D: As in Tomashevsky-Antipov,
this move is slightly inaccurate.} (16... Nf8 {was the correct move.}) 17. h3 (
{Kuljasevic, D: White missed a tactical opportunity to punish Black's last
move:} 17. c5 $1 Rc8 {seems to be the only way to save the queen} (17... Nf8
18. b4 $1 Qxb4 19. Bd2 Qa3 20. Re3 $18) 18. g4 Nf8 19. g5 Be7 20. h4 $40) 17...
Nf8 18. Bd2 ({I was expecting more} 18. Be5 Be7 19. Bg3 Ng6) 18... Qh5 (18...
Qc7 19. Bg5 {would have been dead equal.}) 19. Be3 {Kuljasevic, D: Unlike the
previous games that we have seen, White is playing without a real plan here
and Black has a comfortable game.} Ng6 20. Qe4 {[#] Draw offer.} Nh4 {This
does not change the equality but it requires some nerves to defend a
reminiscent of Kmoch-Rubinstein, Semmering 1926 type of position for white.}
21. Nxh4 Qxh4 22. Qxh4 Bxh4 $11 {[#] Kuljasevic, D: All the piece trades have
worked in Black's favour. The endgame is roughly equal but practically easier
to play with Black. GM Atalik showed good technique to provoke mistakes from
his opponent and convert it into a full point.} 23. Kf1 Rd7 24. Ke2 Red8 25.
Rd2 Be7 $1 {This looks more to the point than Bf6, and Black has to watch for
tactics with d5.} 26. Red1 Bb4 27. Rd3 f6 28. Bd2 Bd6 29. Ba5 Re8 30. Kf3 Kf7 {
So during the last 5 moves black has slightly improved his position and now he
should go for an expansion on the kingside.} 31. Bb6 h5 32. Ke2 $6 ({Why not} 
32. h4 Kg6 33. Ke4) 32... g5 $1 33. a4 Rg8 34. Rh1 Be7 35. f3 h4 $36 {Now
black king has a harbour on f5.} 36. Rhd1 Rc8 {killing the possibility for any
d5.} 37. Kd2 $2 {This is a slight unforced error making space confined for Bb6.
} (37. a5 $11) 37... Bb4+ 38. Kc2 a5 $1 $15 {Now the threat is Ra8-Ra6 thus
for cing a better rook ending.} 39. Rf1 $8 {Creating counterplay down on the f
file.} Ra8 40. f4 gxf4 41. Rxf4 Rg8 $1 {Now g2 is a permanent headache for
white.} 42. Rf2 {Best under the circumstances.} (42. Rxh4 $6 Rxg2+ 43. Kd1 Kg6
44. Re4 (44. Rh8 Kg7 45. Rh4 f5 $17) 44... e5 $17) 42... f5 43. Kd1 $2 {
A bad blunder!} (43. Re2 Rg6 44. Rde3 Re7 (44... Be7 45. Re5 Bb4 46. R5e3 Re7
47. Kd3 Rg8 48. Rf3 Kf6 $11) 45. Kd3 Rg8 46. Re5 Rg3+ 47. R5e3 $11 Re8 $140 $2
48. Rxg3 hxg3 49. Bc7) 43... c5 44. d5 $2 ({Most resilient was to admit the
mistake on the last move.} 44. Kc2 cxd4 45. Rxd4 Rxd4 46. Bxd4 Rg3 47. Re2 f4
48. Rf2 (48. Be5 f3 49. gxf3 Rxh3 $17) 48... Bd6 49. Bb6 e5 50. Bxa5 Ke6 $17)
44... Kf6 45. d6 $4 {loses at once.} (45. Rdf3 Rg5 $1 (45... Rg3 $6 46. Rxg3
hxg3 47. Rf3 exd5 48. cxd5 Rxd5+ 49. Kc1 Rd2 50. Rxg3 Re2 51. h4) 46. Rf4 exd5
$17) 45... Rg3 $1 $19 {now the pawns walk!} 46. Rff3 Rxg2 47. Bc7 e5 48. Rde3
Rd2+ $1 49. Kc1 f4 50. Rd3 {Nothing saves the day for white.} (50. Rf1 Kf5 51.
Ref3 Ke4 52. R3f2 (52. Bb8 Rg7 53. R3f2 Rxf2 54. Rxf2 Ke3 55. Rf1 f3 $19) 52...
Rxf2 53. Rxf2 Ke3 $19) 50... Rxd3 51. Rxd3 e4 52. Rd1 e3 53. Rf1 e2 0-1

