{[%evp 0,107,38,-15,37,26,26,27,40,40,43,-3,4,8,9,14,28,16,14,16,10,0,0,-51,38,
26,30,24,33,17,39,6,17,6,51,13,45,13,13,82,82,16,9,11,20,54,35,49,56,51,54,54,
62,54,95,82,127,121,165,161,156,108,186,153,374,194,165,179,176,179,181,177,
198,150,139,157,161,135,131,150,160,162,159,158,170,179,179,179,179,138,192,74,
80,52,204,134,121,89,105,97,96,87,101,91,99,99,101,100,110,0]} 1. c4 c6 2. d4
d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. e3 e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Qe2 O-O
10. e4 Bg6 11. Bd3 {[#] Let us now examine the typical Slav structure #2. In
this structure, White controls the center even better than in structure #1.
Therefore, it is of paramount importance for Black to either: 1. prepare one
of the central breaks ...c6-c5 or ...e6-e5, or 2. provoke a change in the pawn
structure 3. exchange some pieces In this game, we will see what happens when
Black does neither of that and keeps making 'useful' moves, instead.} a6 {
A waiting approach is not appropriate in this type of position.} ({The best
move is} 11... Bh5 {preparing the ...e5-break. This practically forces White
to, sooner or later, play} 12. e5 (12. Bf4 {is met by} Re8 {and White should
push} 13. e5 {anyway} ({as} 13. Rfd1 $6 {allows} e5 $1 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5
Rxe5 $15) 13... Nd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {which is very similar to the main line.})
12... Nd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 {[#] Now we have a French-like structure where Black
has a 'good bishop' on h5. It also helps that he has exchanged a pair of
pieces and controls the b4-square. He only needs to manoeuvre the knight back
to b8 and c6 to fully neutralize White's space advantage. The game below is a
good example:} 14. Qe3 Be7 {[%csl Rd4,Gd7][%cal Gd7b8,Gb8c6]} 15. Ng5 Bxg5 16.
Qxg5 Qxg5 17. Bxg5 Nb8 $1 18. Bd2 Nc6 19. Bc3 a5 20. Ra3 Bg6 21. Bb5 Rfc8 22.
h4 h5 23. Rfa1 b6 24. f3 f6 $1 25. exf6 gxf6 26. Re1 Kf7 $11 27. Raa1 Rc7 28.
Rac1 Rac8 29. Ba6 Ra8 30. Bb5 Rac8 31. Ba6 Ra8 32. Bb5 Rac8 {1/2-1/2 (32)
Anton Guijarro,D (2694)-Mamedov,R (2659) Wijk aan Zee 2020}) 12. Rd1 h6 13. h3
Rc8 14. Bf4 Re8 15. Rac1 Qa5 {[#] Both sides have made useful developing moves,
but Black lacks a plan since he doesn't have a good way to execute any of the
central breaks nor make a good piece trade. With his next move, White targets
the only real weakness in the solid black position - d6-square.} ({It is too
late for} 15... Bh5 {in the view of} 16. g4 $1 $16) 16. Nd2 $1 b5 {A necessary
move, but a weakening one.} 17. axb5 cxb5 18. Nb3 Qb6 19. e5 $1 {White breaks
in the centre first.} Nd5 20. Nxd5 exd5 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. e6 $1 {The key
breakthrough that allows White to get a superior position.} Nf6 (22... Bxd3 23.
exd7 Bxe2 24. dxc8=Q+ $18) 23. exf7+ Bxf7 24. Be5 $16 {[#] White doesn't have
the strong pawn centre anymore, but his bishops dominate in the centre of the
board. Black king can potentially become a target, as well, so it is clear
that the transformation of the pawn structure has been in the favor of the
first player. Van Wely displayed a strong positional technique to increase his
advantage and bring the point home.} Re8 25. Qc2 Nd7 26. Bg3 Bf8 27. Rc1 $1 {
Preparing to penetrate the c-file with his heavy pieces.} Qf6 28. Qc7 Qd8 29.
Qb7 Nf6 30. Rc7 Bh5 31. Be5 b4 32. Bxa6 $18 Re7 33. Nc5 Rxc7 34. Qxc7 Qxc7 35.
Bxc7 Ne4 36. Nd3 Bf7 37. Ba5 b3 38. Kf1 Be6 39. f3 Ng3+ 40. Kf2 Nf5 41. Bc3 Kf7
42. Nc5 Bxc5 43. dxc5 d4 44. Ba5 Bd5 45. Bd3 Ne3 46. Ke2 Nc2 47. Kd2 Ne3 48.
Bc7 Nxg2 49. Be5 Nh4 50. Bxd4 Nxf3+ 51. Ke3 Ne1 52. Be2 Nc2+ 53. Kd3 Be6 54.
Kc3 1-0

