{[%evp 0,63,38,29,13,25,26,-7,40,24,9,9,16,16,16,16,14,14,27,35,34,28,31,16,60,
57,61,47,53,31,46,8,7,3,18,33,30,-92,7,-16,4,12,13,-4,-3,-38,6,-7,-15,4,-1,-23,
-7,-60,-27,-17,169,197,250,318,317,319,293,316,379,390] Kuljasevic, D: For a
long time, I have considered this game to be a model game for how White should
play positions with a big space advantage against the Slav. However, as I
found out in my own game against Conrad Holt (see game 3.3), modern chess
requires a more dynamic understanding of such positions.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6
3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 {Clearly intending to regain the pawn without
trouble. This continuation gives White a small advantage in view of the freer
development of his pieces. However, he must always bear in mind the one marked
weakness in his camp - the b4 square which will always be under Black´s
control.} Bf5 6. e3 e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 8. O-O O-O 9. Nh4 {The only way to continue
the struggle for an opening advantage. Sooner or later, White exchanges knight
for bishop, obtaining the notorious advantage of the two bishops, which, in
view of the closed nature of the position, only ensures a small edge.} Bg4 10.
f3 Bh5 {The text-move is double-edged, as White´s pawns can mount an attack.}
(10... Nd5 11. fxg4 Qxh4 {is also playable;} 12. Qf3 {is now strongest as
White need, not fear} Nxc3 (12... Nd7 $142 13. Bd2 a5) 13. bxc3 Bxc3 {because
of} 14. Rb1 {[%csl Rb7,Rc3,Rf7][%cal Yc1a3] followed by 15. La3.}) 11. g4 Bg6
12. Nxg6 {This is the first time I have had this position in tournament play.
I knew that the exchange of minor pieces is normally deferred, but I saw an
interesting plan and was very attracted by it.} hxg6 13. Qb3 $5 {This and the
following few moves decide not only the result of the opening stage of the
game but of the game itself. The basic problem for White is the imprisonment
of his bishop on c1. When considering where to develop this bishop, White must
not forget that his pawns have been advanced considerably and that a
counter-thrust by Black in the centre could turn out to be very unpleasant.
Black is planning the advance c6-c5, which would undermine White´s centre, to
strengthen his bishop on b4, and place a knight on the active c6 square. White
clears d1 for a rook with a gain of tempo, as the bishop cannot retreat,
because of the unprotected pawn on b7.} Qe7 (13... Qb6 {is possible, as White
cannot drive the bishop away immediately by} 14. Na2 $6 ({Best would be} 14.
Rd1 {, strengthening the defence of d4 and preparing the pawn advances g4-g5
and e3-e4.}) 14... Be7 {, and the loss of time stops White creating problems
for Black in the ending.}) 14. g5 {This drives the knight away from f6, takes
control of the d5 square, and in the case of c6-c5 (which is now threatened)
allows d4-d5. It was this move in mind that it was necessary to exchange on
move 12, since now if 14...Sfd7 then White has 15 f4.} Nd5 {Forcing events.} ({
After} 14... Nfd7 15. e4 {Black does not have to transfer his knight to b6. It
appears that Portisch did not like his cramped position after 15 f4, which is
now not so worrisome for Black.} (15. f4)) 15. e4 Nb6 (15... Nxc3 16. bxc3 {
only strengthens White´s centre.}) 16. Na2 $1 {When considering his previous
move, Black had relied mainly on the retreat of the bishop on c4, which would
have won him an important tempo for the advance c6-c5. This zwischenzug upsets
these plans as the capture 16...Sxc4 is poor for Black because of 17 Sxb4 with
a decisive spatial advantage for White.} Ba5 (16... Bd6 17. Be2 {[%csl Rb6]
[%cal Ya4a5]}) (16... Nxc4 17. Nxb4) 17. Be2 e5 {The alarming position of his
minor pieces, which are trapped on the queenside, forces Black into extreme
measures.} (17... c5 {does not give the hope for freedom after} 18. dxc5 (18.
Qb5 $143 Nc6 $1 19. Qxc5 (19. dxc5 a6 $1) 19... Qxc5 20. dxc5 Nxa4) 18... Qxc5+
19. Be3) 18. Qc2 $1 {Another preliminary move, threatening the bishop. While
opening the way for an advance of the b-pawn, the queen defends the second
rank, the e4 pawn and controls the c5 square.} N6d7 ({The complications after} 
18... exd4 19. b4 $1 Bxb4 20. Nxb4 Qxb4 21. Ba3 Qa5 22. Bxf8 Qxg5+ (22... Kxf8
23. f4 {[%cal Yf4f5] and the pawn advance is deadly}) 23. Kh1 Kxf8 {leave
Black the worse off after} 24. a5 N6d7 25. Qb2 {[%cal Rb2d4,Rb2b7]} Nc5 26.
Qxd4) 19. dxe5 Qxe5 20. Kh1 {A useful prophylactic move. The king moves away
from the open a7-g1 diagonal and avoids dangerous intermediate checks. A
further point is that f4 is now threatened, White can play this move at any
time, and in preventing it Black has to give way in other parts of the board.}
({Kuljasevic, D: As a matter of fact, there was no need for such prophylaxis.
White could have immediately increased his space advantage with} 20. f4 Qd4+
21. Kg2 $16) 20... Re8 {Portisch considered this move to be the cause of his
troubles, but I, on the other hand, consider it a good move. We now get a keen
struggle "for and against" the advance of White´s centre pawns. The rook
attacks not only the e-pawn but also, behind it, the bishop at e2.} 21. Bc4 Nb6
22. Bd3 Na6 {The threat is stronger than its execution. By defending against
f4 and b4, Black compromises his Q-side pawn structure. However, all is not as
simple as it seems. White still has difficulty in developing his dark-squared
bishop and his a1-rook cannot easily emerge. At the moment Black is better
developed and intends to take advantage of this.} (22... N8d7 23. b4 $1 Qxa1
24. bxa5 Nc8 (24... Nxa4 25. Be3 Qb2 26. Qxa4) 25. Bb2 Qxa2 26. Bc4 $1 {
and the queen is trapped}) ({Possibly he should try} 22... c5 {here.} 23. f4
Qe7 24. e5 Nc6 25. Be3 Rac8 26. Bxc5 Nd4 27. Bxe7 Nxc2) 23. Bxa6 bxa6 24. Rd1
$1 {This fine move is not at all obvious. White has a series of possible
continuations, but all are considerably weaker.} (24. Rb1 $143 c5 {and Black
has no worries}) (24. Nc3 $143 {takes away the powerful effect of the queen on
the c-file, which allows} c5 {, when} 25. Be3 {fails to} Nc4) ({Nor can the
bishop be developed immediately:} 24. Be3 $2 Nd5 $1) 24... c5 (24... Rad8 25.
Be3 Nd5 (25... Qe6 26. b4 Nc4 27. Bxa7 Bc7) 26. Bd4 $1) 25. Be3 {It is now
clear that White has solved all his problems and has emerged from the opening
with an advantage. But it would be ludicrous to suggest that the game would be
all over in another seven moves.} Rac8 26. Nc3 (26. Nc1 $5 {deserves attention,
to be followed by moving the knight to d3 or e2. However, White has a
different plan, control of the d5 square. Now Portisch cannot really permit
White to achieve his regrouping, but, on the other hand, has no means of
preventing it.}) 26... Nc4 27. Bc1 {The bishop retreats from where he came.
Stunned by the rapid and unexpected development of events, Portisch makes a
grave error on the next move, which leads to immediate defeat.} Rb8 $2 {
It is difficult to say what Portisch was thinking about at this moment, what
variations he had calculated or on what he was relying. Clearly, he simply
overlooked that the d5 square could be occupied not only by the rook (with
tempo) but with the knight (with decisive effect).} ({After the necessary} 
27... Bxc3 {there was still a long struggle ahead - Black is only slightly
worse in the ending after} 28. Qxc3 (28. Rd5 Qxd5 $1 29. exd5 Re1+ 30. Kg2 Bxb2
31. Qxc4 Bxa1 $13) 28... Qxc3 29. bxc3) (27... Qe6 28. Nd5 Ne5 29. Kg2 Nxf3)
28. Nd5 {In effect, Black could resign now. Portisch plays a few moves from
inertia.} Nxb2 29. Bf4 Qe6 30. Rdb1 Qh3 31. Bxb8 Rxb8 32. Rxb2 1-0

