{[%evp 0,122,19,31,19,-16,26,22,38,27,8,-5,-5,11,13,18,18,22,27,38,39,27,39,39,
39,45,23,4,39,39,59,59,29,61,83,93,77,31,31,81,102,77,87,49,60,43,87,60,63,46,
31,53,49,49,46,48,29,0,-7,-8,0,-131,-76,-78,-32,-36,-42,-64,-60,-62,-64,-70,
-61,-91,-42,-94,-21,-41,-14,-20,-26,-21,-24,-32,-18,-19,-34,-54,0,-53,-37,-64,
8,0,-11,-91,6,0,8,-24,21,0,0,0,0,0,8,11,4,0,32,11,3,0,0,-39,0,-60,-122,-189,
-189,-805,-969,-1355,-1486]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5
6. e3 e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 8. O-O O-O 9. Nh4 Bg4 {My opponent has played like this
before, so I prepared this variation before the game.} 10. f3 Bh5 11. g4 Nd5
12. Ng2 Bg6 13. Na2 Be7 14. e4 Nb6 15. Bb3 {White has scored very well in this
line and I had a good feeling about my chances to get an advantage from the
opening. However, Holt continued to make his replies quicky and confidently:}
c5 ({The other line that I had looked at before the game was} 15... a5 16. Be3
{but here I made the first mistake by not taking seriously Black's critical
and natural attempt to equalize} c5 $1 ({Instead, I finished my opening prep
with the following feel-good model game:} 16... N8d7 17. Rc1 $14 e5 $2 18. dxe5
Nxe5 19. f4 Nd3 20. f5 Nxc1 21. Nxc1 $18 {1-0 (29) Smirnov,A (2415)-Pankov,G  
(2290) St Petersburg 2004})) 16. a5 {[#]} Nc8 $1 $146 {While I knew that this
was the strongest move in the position according to the engine, I somehow did
not believe that my opponent would play it. I mean, I am playing this FM
teenager that I had barely heard of, so how dare he make such a theoretically
important and daring novelty?! As it had turned out, this was not the first
time in this game that underestimating an underrated youngster, who is a
strong GM now has had a boomerang effect.} ({My pre-game preparation ended
here:} 16... N6d7 $2 17. d5 Qxa5 18. dxe6 {Obviously, the knight is worse on
this square than on c8 because this move comes with a tempo.} Qb6 19. exd7 $1 (
19. exf7+ Bxf7 20. Bxf7+ Rxf7 21. Nc3 $16 {1-0 (48) Shishkin,V (2458)-Vajda,A 
(2427) Tusnad 2004}) 19... c4+ 20. Be3 Qxb3 21. Nc3 $18) 17. d5 Qxa5 18. dxe6 {
If I had taken this critical line seriously in pre-game preparation, I might
have realized that this 'automatic' move is not the best} ({and that} 18. Be3
$1 $36 {brings White excellent prospects in the middlegame. The point is that
Black cannot develop his knights here as easily as in the game, so White gets
a nice lead in development.}) 18... Nc6 19. Be3 ({Several years later, GM
Troff attempted to improve on my play with} 19. Kh1 Nd4 20. exf7+ Bxf7 21.
Bxf7+ Rxf7 22. Be3 Nb6 23. Bxd4 cxd4 24. Qxd4 Rd8 $44 {and although White won
at the end, it feels like Black should have been fine at this point of the
game Troff, K (2532)-Holt, C (2530) Richardson 2015 1-0 (52) .}) 19... Nb6 {
As a result of his concrete opening play, Black has managed to neutralize my
space advantage while obtaining an active and dynamic position.} 20. Nc3 {
[#] When playing this move, I was sure that my opponent would move his queen
to b4 in response. I briefly saw that 20...Rad8 is also an option, but the
optimistic side of my brain said: ''Okay, but what are the chances that he
will play this?" And then, it happened...} Rad8 $5 {Objectively speaking, this
bold move is worse than 20...Qb4. However, it was more unpleasant for me in
the game because it created some new possibilities in the position that I
hadn't calculated at all before making my 20th move. Thus, I attach it a '!?'
sign, even though a '?!' is more appropriate, objectively speaking.} ({After} 
20... Qb4 {I had considered} 21. Nf4 ({and} 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. exd5 $13) ({while
} 21. Na2 Qb5 22. Nc3 Qb4 $11 {was an option to force a draw by move
repetition. I was actually not sure during the game if my much lower-rated
opponent was already playing for a win by avoiding this possibility, which had
made me even more confused!}) 21... c4 22. Ba4 $13 {with a pretty complicated
position.}) 21. exf7+ $6 {I was getting ready to swap the queens, so I
inserted this move in order to force his rook to a worse position. However,
Holt had an unpleasant surprise for me here, as well.} ({In fact, White would
have been better simply with} 21. Rxa5 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Nxa5 23. Nd5 $1 {I do not
remember, but I may have missed this move in the game.} Nxd5 24. Bxd5 $16)
21... Bxf7 22. Bxf7+ {I thought that he recaptures with the rook, we trade the
queens and I take control over the d-file in the endgame. And then...} Kxf7 $5
{[#] ...with the same unperturbed facial expression, Holt mini-shocked me
again. Who would play such a move with all pieces on the board and his queen
hanging, when he can simply recapture with the rook? I did not even think that
king taking on f7 is legal in this position, it shocked me that much when he
played it! And once again, his unexpected counter-intuitive reply is
objectively worse than the natural alternative, but its psychological effect
on me was stronger than its objective merit.} ({White would have retained a
slight plus in the endgame after the 'logical'} 22... Rxf7 23. Rxa5 Rxd1 24.
Rxd1 Nxa5 25. f4 $14) 23. Nd5 $2 {Played with the right idea - to keep the
queens on the board - but in the wrong way.} ({My state of mind was already
disturbed to the point where I missed that I can force a favourable weakening
of Black's pawn structure with} 23. Qb3+ $1 c4 24. Qc2 {and now that black
pawn is on c4, White is simply better in the middlegame since Black's
counterplay with ...Nb6-c4 and ...Nc6-d4 has been neutralized.} Qb4 25. f4 $16)
({Holt's idea was that he would get a better version of the 22...Rxf7 endgame
in case of} 23. Rxa5 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 Nxa5 25. f4 Nac4 26. Bc1 Rd8 $11) 23... Qb5
24. Qc2 Nxd5 25. exd5 Rxd5 26. Qxh7 {This was the idea behind 23.Nd5. Black
king is weak and White threatens to go Ng2-f4 next, with dangerous threats.
Well, as soon as my opponent made his reply, I realized that this was also
wishful thinking...} Qd3 $1 $132 {[#] I had completely missed this strong
defensive move when going for this forced sequence. Black king is safe now and
the position is equal. Holt outplayed me in the rest of the game and won
deservedly, as you can see below.} 27. Qe4 Rd7 28. Qa4 b5 29. Qa2+ Qd5 30. b3
Nb4 31. Qe2 Qd3 32. Qxd3 Nxd3 33. Ra5 Rb8 34. Rb1 Bd8 35. Ra2 Bb6 36. Rc2 Re8
37. Kf1 Rde7 38. Bg5 Rc7 39. Nf4 Nxf4 40. Bxf4 Rd7 41. Rd2 Rxd2 42. Bxd2 a5 43.
h4 b4 44. h5 Ra8 45. Ra1 Ke6 46. Ke2 Kd5 47. Kd3 Rd8 48. Bg5 Rd7 49. Kc2 Rf7
50. Rd1+ Kc6 51. f4 Kb5 52. f5 a4 53. bxa4+ Kxa4 54. Rd6 b3+ 55. Kb2 Bc7 56.
Re6 c4 57. Bd2 Rd7 58. Bc3 Bd6 59. Rxd6 Rxd6 60. Bxg7 Rd2+ 61. Kc1 c3 0-1

