{[%evp 0,95,38,19,19,10,25,19,25,19,58,51,59,64,69,46,58,57,66,49,51,34,43,18,
37,30,26,15,15,23,31,28,25,17,43,47,40,43,55,56,48,48,49,46,70,46,48,49,47,49,
78,53,58,56,64,62,61,65,93,76,124,74,101,90,107,110,168,152,182,194,197,142,
142,142,141,110,181,206,191,191,304,381,362,435,374,377,495,478,1219,1258,1497,
1479,2788,2556,29989,29990,29993,29994] Kuljasevic, D: In the final part of
the lecture, we will examine Typical Slav position #3. As usual, we start with
an example that shows how White can squeeze Black if he doesn't do anything to
challenge or neutralize his space advantage. This game is a perfect example of
this scenario.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 g6 6. Bd3 Bg7 7.
O-O O-O 8. h3 b5 9. b3 Nbd7 10. Qc2 Bb7 11. c5 $1 {Kuljasevic, D: White
increases his space advantage while fixing a long-term weakness on c6 and
burying the b7-bishop.} Ne8 $146 12. Bb2 Nc7 13. b4 a5 14. a3 {[#]} Ne6 $6 {
Kuljasevic, D: Black had to break in the centre; now his position will become
cramped.} (14... e5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Ne2 $5 (17. Nxb5 Bxb2 18.
Nxc7 Bxa1 19. Nxa8 Be5 $1 (19... Qxa8 20. Rxa1 axb4 21. Qb2 $1 $16) 20. Nb6
axb4 21. axb4 Bc7 $11) 17... Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Ne6 19. Rad1 Re8 20. e4 dxe4 21.
Bxe4 $14) (14... Re8 15. Rfe1 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Ne2 (18. e4 $6
axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Bxa1 Qh4) 18... Bxb2 19. Qxb2 $14) 15. Nd2 Qc7 16. f4
axb4 17. axb4 Rxa1 18. Rxa1 Ra8 19. Rxa8+ Bxa8 20. Nf3 {[#] Kuljasevic, D: Now
we have the typical Slav structure #3. Black's pawn bind (the pawn chain from
f4 to c5 limits black's active options significantly.} Bb7 $2 {Kuljasevic, D:
Again, Black is playing too passively in the centre.} (20... f5 $1 21. g4 $6
fxg4 22. hxg4 Nxf4 23. exf4 Qxf4 24. Qe2 (24. Qg2 $4 Qe3+ $19) 24... Qxg4+ 25.
Kf1 {Black needs to choose between two options} Bxd4 (25... e5 26. dxe5 Qh3+
27. Ke1 Qg3+ 28. Kd2 Nxe5 29. Nxe5 Qxe5 30. Qxe5 Bxe5 $14 {I think Black would
be able to draw if he played precisely}) 26. Nxd4 Qxd4 27. Qe6+ Kf8 28. Qxd7
Qxd3+ 29. Ne2 Kf7) 21. g4 $1 $16 {Black has problems on both sides. Probably
the position is strategically winning for White.} Bc8 22. Bc1 Nf6 23. Qa2 h6
24. Ne5 g5 $6 (24... Bb7 25. Kg2 Nd7 26. Nf3 Bc8 27. Qf2 $16) 25. Bf5 (25. Qa8
$1) 25... Nd8 26. Bd3 gxf4 (26... Ne6 27. Qa8 Nd8 28. Kg2 $16 (28. Bf5 $6 Bxf5
(28... e6 29. Bb1 $16) 29. Nxc6 Qxc6 $1 (29... Bxg4 30. Nxd8 $18) 30. Qxd8+ Kh7
31. gxf5 gxf4 32. Qxe7 (32. exf4 Qa6 33. Qa5 Qc8) 32... Qa6 33. exf4 Qa1 34.
Qe1 Ne4 $132)) 27. exf4 Nd7 (27... h5 28. g5 Ne8 29. Kh2 $16) 28. Nf3 Ne6 29.
Ne2 Qb7 (29... Nf6 30. f5 Nf8 31. Bf4 Qb7 32. Ng3 $16) 30. Be3 (30. f5 $5 Nc7
31. Ng3 Nf6 32. Bf4 $16) 30... Qa6 31. Qb2 Nef8 {[#] Kuljasevic, D: Black ran
out of active options long ago and now it is time for White to reap the
benefits of his huge space advantage.} 32. Ng3 $1 e6 33. Nh5 Bh8 34. f5 $18 Nf6
(34... exf5 35. gxf5 Nf6 36. Nxf6+ Bxf6 37. Bxh6 Nh7 38. Qg2+ Kh8 39. Qe2 Bd7
40. Ne5 $18) 35. Bxh6 Ne4 36. f6 $1 Nxf6 $8 (36... Bd7 37. Bxe4 dxe4 38. Nd2)
37. Ne5 Ne4 38. Bxe4 dxe4 39. Qf2 Bxe5 40. dxe5 Qa1+ 41. Kg2 f5 (41... Ng6 42.
Nf6+ Kh8 43. Qd2 $18) 42. exf6 Kf7 43. Bxf8 Kxf8 44. Qd2 Kf7 45. Qd8 Qb2+ 46.
Kg3 Qc3+ 47. Kh4 Qe1+ 48. Ng3 1-0

