[BlackTeamCountry "USA"]

{Finally, let us examine a game in which a strong GM Sam Shankland displayed
many nice ideas for Black in a fairly typical Slav endgame where White holds a
space advantage.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 5. Qb3 Qb6 6. Nc3 e6
7. Nh4 Bh5 8. h3 Na6 $5 {An interesting way to develop the knight, as opposed
to the usual Nbd7. The idea behind it will be revealed shortly.} 9. c5 Qxb3 10.
axb3 Nc7 {[#]} 11. g4 {White increases his space advantage.} ({Now we can see
the role of the knight on c7. In the event of} 11. b4 a6 {[%cal Rb4b5]} 12. b5
{is completely stopped as the rook on a8 is protected.} axb5 13. Rxa8+ Nxa8)
11... Bg6 12. b4 a6 13. f3 O-O-O 14. Bd2 Be7 15. Nxg6 {It is tempting to take
the bishop pair, but this kind of advantage is rather insignificant in such a
closed position.} ({White should have been more flexible with this exchange,
so it was better to play} 15. O-O-O Nd7 16. Be1 {intending to meet White's
pawn break} e5 $2 {with} 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. f4 Nd7 19. f5 {which traps the
bishop.}) 15... hxg6 16. Kf2 Nd7 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black is preparing the ...e5
break and White, naturally, stops it...} 17. f4 g5 $1 {The right pawn break!} (
17... f5 $6 {leaves black pieces rather cramped after} 18. g5 $16) 18. Bd3 {[#]
} g6 $1 (18... Rdg8 {was also possible, preparing to do the second ...g5 break.
} 19. Ne2 gxf4 20. exf4 g5 21. fxg5 Bxg5 22. Bxg5 Rxg5 23. Rag1 $14 {although
White would have an edge here with his kingside passers.}) 19. Kg3 f5 $1 {
Excellent strategy by Black, neutralizing white space advantage and preparing
to slowly bring his knights into the game.} 20. fxg5 $6 (20. Ne2 {was a more
solid choice, keeping control over the e5-square.} Rh7 21. Rag1 Rdh8 $132)
20... Bxg5 21. h4 Be7 22. Ne2 e5 $1 {[%cal Gc7e6] [#] Without the pawn on f4,
Black suddenly gets the upper hand in the centre.} 23. Raf1 $2 (23. dxe5 Nxe5
24. Nf4 $132 {was the last chance for White to obtain some counterplay.}) 23...
Nf6 24. g5 (24. gxf5 e4 $1 25. Bc2 gxf5 26. Rxf5 Rdg8+ 27. Kf2 Ng4+ 28. Ke1
Bxh4+ $19) 24... Nh5+ 25. Kg2 e4 $17 {[#] Similar to Carlsen's game, one has
to marvel at the way Black has constructed a 'Chinese wall' with his pawns.
The pawn chain from a6 to g6 is incredibly strong and White is strategically
busted as Black is eventually going to open the position with the ...f5-f4
break.} 26. Bc2 Ne6 27. Bc3 Rh7 28. Bd1 Rdh8 29. Be1 Bd8 30. Ng3 Nhg7 31. Ne2
Bc7 32. Bf2 Kd7 33. Be1 Ke7 34. Bf2 Nh5 35. Be1 {[#]} f4 36. exf4 Nhxf4+ 37.
Nxf4 Nxf4+ 38. Kg1 Nd3 $19 {The h4-pawn cannot be protected anymore and the
game is effectively over.} 39. Bd2 Rxh4 40. Rxh4 Rxh4 41. Rf6 Nxb2 42. Be2 Rh2
43. Kf1 Nd3 44. Be3 Rh1+ 45. Kg2 Re1 46. Bxd3 Rxe3 47. Bxa6 Rg3+ 48. Kf2 Rxg5
0-1

