{[%evp 0,28,27,31,32,-10,41,14,35,8,5,0,55,43,35,42,43,43,37,33,32,26,53,28,28,
28,28,22,22,-3,3] The Classical Slav is one of the most reliable weapons Black
can opt for against 1.d4. It is an opening I have analyzed extensively and
even published a book on (GM Repertoire: The Classical Slav). Since then, I
have revisited some of the material and over the course of this lecture, I am
going to discuss the new ideas and trends I have noticed.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3.
Nc3 {It does not make a great difference whether White plays Nc3 and Nf3 first;
if 3.Nc3 Black has the additional option of the 3.dxc4 system but, personally,
I prefer to refrain from it} Nf6 4. Nf3 {The main crossroad for Black: he has
3 choices 1) dxc4 (Classical Slav), 2) e6 (Semi-Slav) and 3) a6 (Chebanenko
Slav) . The line which interests us is:} dxc4 (4... e6 {Currently, the
Semi-Slav also enjoys great popularity. I consider} 5. Bg5 {to be the greatest
challenge for Black. The arising lines require a lot of theoretical knowledge
for both sides. Black usually reacts with the Moscow/Anti-Moscow Gambit (5.h6),
the sharp Botvinnik Variation, or the more positional Cambridge-Springs (5.
Nbd7)}) 5. a4 {by far the most popular move} a5 {A new system that is still
rather unexplored. It has been tested by none other GM Baadur Jobava, famous
for his aggressive and imaginative play. Black waits for White to determine
his course of action (e3 or e4) and intends to play Bg4 next move. The
advantage of 5... a5 is that it ensures lively and complicated positions and
at the same time avoids well-established theory.} 6. e4 {the first move Black
should address when preparing the line} (6. e3 Bg4 7. Bxc4 e6 8. O-O (8. h3 {
is a more aggressive approach} Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Ne5 (10. h4 {poses a direct
challenge to Black} Bb4 11. h5 Be4 12. g5 Nd5 13. Bd2 {0-1 (43) Ulybin,M (2589)
-Welling, G (2393) Port Erin 2002} Bxc3 14. Bxc3 (14. bxc3 {runs into} f5 $5
$11 {[%cal Yb8d7] Controlling the centre and setting up a light-squared
strategy. Black needs to be careful not to let White activate Bd2, for if that
happens, he will experience difficulties.}) 14... h6 (14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bxf3
16. Qxf3 Qxg5 17. Rb1 $44 {gives White full compensation: his forces are very
active whereas Black's are not fully developed yet}) 15. gxh6 Rxh6 $13) 10...
Nbd7 {challenging the strong Ne5 right away} 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. g5 (12. Qf3 {
is the positional way to continue} Bb4 13. Bd2 Qe7 14. Bb3 {1-0 (65) Gupta,A  
(2607) -Jobava,B (2712) Reykjavik 2017} Nd5 $13 {[%cal Ge8c8] White needs to
decide where to place his king and that is not necessarily an easy task as
castling on either side is dangerous due to the advancement of the pawns. Most
likely, he will have to delay the king in the centre which also yields
challenges since Black has the breaks of f5, e5 and c5 at his disposal}) 12...
Nd5 13. e4 Nb4 (13... N5b6 {is the other option and has roughly the same
evaluation. Black will attack White's centre with e5 or c5} 14. Bb3 Bb4 $13)
14. Be3 Rh4 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Yh3h4,Yh4h5] is an improvement from Jobava's
game. The idea is to prevent White from connecting his kingside pawns} 15. Qd2
Qc7 16. O-O-O O-O-O $13 {Black has enough counterplay and is by no means worse.
The game will end up in favour of the player who better navigates the
complications}) 8... Nbd7 9. h3 (9. Qb3 Bxf3 (9... Qb6 {0-1 (51) Mamedyarov,S 
(2770)-Jobava,B (2603) Europe Echecs INT 2021}) 10. gxf3 Bb4 11. Na2 {White
needs to play so in case he wants to justify Qb3} Bd6 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qa6 Nd5
{[%csl Gg1] Black wants to activate his queen and make use of White's weak king
} 14. f4 {1-0 (45) Sarana,A (2618)-Kryakvin,D (2588) St Petersburg 2018} Qh4
$15 {[%cal Gh8g8,Gg7g5] seems very dangerous for White to me}) 9... Bh5 10. Qe2
{the most natural continuation} (10. Be2 Bb4 {White's chosen setup does not
pose any real problems to Black} 11. Ne5 $6 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14.
f4 Nc5 $15 {0-1 (40) Arabidze,M (2437)-Jobava,B (2603) Chess.com INT 2020}) (
10. e4 {is more or less a forced line} Bb4 11. e5 Nd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 $5 {
Risky but exactly corresponding to the dynamic style Jobava is renowned for!} (
12... cxd5 {would be my choice instead} 13. Be2 Nb8 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 13. Bd3
O-O (13... Nf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8e6,Gd8e7,Ge8c8] A precise move. The route of the
knight is the same as in Hakobyan- Postny (2020). However, this time Black's
position is way better: Bh5 is active, the queen has the natural e7 square and
most importantly, his king is able to castle queenside and escape to safety})
14. Bf5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (50) Rasulov,V (2478) -Jobava,B (2603) Chess.com INT 2021}
) 10... Bb4 11. Rd1 (11. e4 O-O 12. Bf4 Re8 13. Rad1 Nd5 $1 14. Bd2 h6 $13)
11... O-O 12. e4 Qc7 {[%csl Gf4] stops Bf4 and prepares e5} (12... h6 13. Bf4
$14) 13. Bg5 {1-0 (49) Uhlmann,W-Neckar,L Brno 1975} Rfe8 {[%cal Ge6e5] Always
a useful move. The position is very similar to the classical line of the Slav
with Bf5 and e3} (13... h6 {is a wild line the computer suggests:} 14. Bh4 Qf4
15. Bg3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qg5 17. Qe3 Nh5 18. f4 Qg6 $13 {The position is holding
but I find it dangerous to play in a real game})) (6. Ne5 Ng4 $5 7. Nxc4 e5 8.
e3 (8. dxe5 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Be6 $44) (8. h3 exd4 9. hxg4 Bb4 10. Bf4 {0-1 (18)
Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2613)-Jobava,B (2582) Chess.com INT 2021} Qf6 $146 11.
Be5 $140 Qxe5 $1 12. Nxe5 dxc3 $15 {[%csl Gd1]}) 8... exd4 9. Qxd4 {1/2-1/2  
(48) Nikolov,M (2561)-Biriukov,N (2393) Heusenstamm 2017} Be6 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8
$11) 6... Bg4 7. Bxc4 e6 8. Be3 {a precise move} (8. O-O Bb4 {putting pressure
on the central pawns. White can react in 2 distinct ways:} 9. Qd3 {protecting
e4 and escaping the knight pin} (9. e5 Nd5 10. Ne4 (10. Nxd5 $6 cxd5 11. Bb5+
Nc6 12. h3 Bh5 $15 {0-1 (34) Rogozenco, D (2482)-Jobava,B (2603) Pardubice 2021
}) 10... Nd7 11. h3 Bh5 12. Ng3 Bg6 13. Qe2 (13. Ng5 h6 14. N5e4 {At first
glance, Black's position looks dangerous as White is prepared to launch an
attack with f4-f5 and bring the queen into play. In fact, the two games which
have been played here ended in White's favour. Nonetheless, the improvement I
prepared ensures Black is in good shape:} Qh4 $1 15. f4 (15. Qg4 {Transposing
to an endgame is not something Black is opposed to:} Qxg4 16. hxg4 N7b6 $11 {
[%cal Ge8c8] Black does not have any weaknesses, has great squares for his
pieces and eventually will start putting pressure on d4}) 15... f5 $1 {The key
move! It does not let White press the Black pieces} 16. exf6 N7xf6 17. Nxf6+
Qxf6 $15 {[%csl Rc1,Rg3][%cal Ge8c8] Black is slightly better as White's
forces are uncoordinated}) 13... O-O $146 14. Rd1 Rc8 $13 {Black has a good
version of the Bf5, e4 line}) 9... Nbd7 (9... Bxf3 $6 {I do not approve of
this move. Generally, Black does not want to rush with taking unless he has
something specific in mind} 10. gxf3 Nbd7 11. f4 O-O 12. Rd1 $14 {1-0 (23)
Avrukh,B (2645)-Welling,G (2364) Kemer 2007}) 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5
{Now that White has exchanged Nf3, Bg4 has nothing to do and needs to be
re-routed} Bh5 {[%cal Yh5g6,Yg6e4]} (12... Nd7 $5) 13. f3 Nd7 14. Bg3 Qe7 15.
Rfd1 Rfd8 (15... e5 {is premature} 16. d5) 16. Qe2 Rac8 17. Rac1 Bg6 (17... f6
$2 {is logical since it opens up a path for Bh5 but is, unfortunately, a
mistake. The problem is that after 18.Na2, Black is forced to give up the
bishop pair and defend for the rest of the game} 18. Na2 Bf7 (18... Bd6 19. e5
$18) 19. Nxb4 Qxb4 20. Be1 Qb6 21. Bf2 $16 {1/2-1/2 (24) Cramling,P (2491)
-Brunello,S (2581) Caleta 2012}) 18. Na2 Bd6 $13 {[%cal Yc6c5]}) 8... Bb4 9.
Qd3 {the most critical line} (9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Nd2 {A very common idea: White
evacuates the N in order to start restricting Bg4} (10. O-O Bxf3 (10... O-O)
11. gxf3 Nh5 $146 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gd8f6] ocuppying the f4 square} 12. Ne2 g5
$1 $13) 10... Bh5 11. f3 Bg6 12. O-O (12. Qd1 {0-1 (37) Sarkar,J (2374)-Jobava,
B (2603) Chess.com INT 2020} e5) 12... Nd5 {[%cal Yg6c2] binds the queen to
protect Nc3} 13. Bf2 O-O 14. Rfd1 {0-1 (51) Atabayev,S (2425)-Kryakvin, D  
(2596) Moscow 2019} Nf4 15. Bf1 f5 $132 {a typical way to get Bg6 back into
play}) 9... Nbd7 10. Nd2 (10. Ne5 $2 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd3 12. Bxd3 {1-0 (50) Ten,
V (2204)-Kuporosov,V (2448) Tomsk 2008} Nd7 13. f4 g5 $1 {Black solves the
problems of Bg4 tactically. He has an edge due to his superior pawn structure}
14. g3 O-O-O $36) 10... e5 $5 $146 {[%cal Yg4e6] Changing the structure and
thus finding a place for Bg4} (10... Bh5 {is what I previously considered to
be the right way to play. However, White manages to build the f3- e4 structure
and thus keep Bh5 out of play in the foreseeable future. Still, the position
is very much playable for Black} 11. f3 $14 Bg6 12. Qe2 {White gets away from
the pin so that Black does not have any Nd5 ideas} O-O 13. O-O $14) 11. f3 exd4
12. Bxd4 Be6 13. Bxe6 (13. e5 Bxc4 (13... Nd5 {is possible too. Nonetheless, I
am a little sceptical of the position because of Black's isolated pawn} 14.
Bxd5 cxd5 15. O-O Nc5 16. Qe3 Rc8 $13) 14. Nxc4 Nc5 15. Qd1 Ne6 $11 {is the
computer way to solve the opening trouble for Black}) 13... fxe6 14. Qc2 O-O
$13 {with a complicated game} *

