1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 e6 {My original book
recommendation. More solid than 5...a5} (5... Bf5 {is the most played setup} 6.
Ne5 (6. e3) 6... Nbd7 7. Nxc4 Qc7 8. g3 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 Nfd7 11. Bg2 g5
{the invention of Morozevich} 12. Ne3 (12. Bxe5 Nxe5 13. Qd4 f6 $11) (12. Nxe5
{is also possible. Nonetheless, Black has compensation for the pawn and
chances to equalize due to the bishop pair} gxf4 13. Nxd7 O-O-O (13... Qxd7 14.
Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. O-O-O+ Kc7 16. gxf4 $14) 14. Qd4 Qxd7 15. Qxf4 Bd6 16. Qc1 Kb8
17. O-O a5 $44 {I believe Black is doing well here}) 12... gxf4 13. Nxf5 O-O-O
14. Qc2 Nc5 15. O-O fxg3 16. hxg3 a5 17. Rad1 h5 18. Rxd8+ Qxd8 19. Rd1 Qf6 {
Main theory. The position has been studied extensively: it is equal with both
sides being very solid}) 6. e4 (6. e3 c5 {the point of the line} 7. Bxc4 cxd4
8. exd4 Be7 9. O-O O-O {A classical position from QGD; White has the extra
move of a4 but that is not necessarily in his favour (b4 is weak)} 10. Qe2 (10.
d5 exd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Nd7 (12... Nc6 13. Be3 Bf5 14. Qb3 Nb4 15. Rfd1
{1-0 (63) Ju,W (2584)-Goryachkina,A (2578) Shanghai/Vladivostok 2020} Qe8 $1
16. Nd4 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Bg4 18. Rd2 Bb4 19. Rd3 Qe7 20. Nf5 Qf6 21. Rd4 Qxf5 22.
Qxf5 Bxf5 23. Rxb4 b6 24. a5 Bd7 25. Rd4 Be6 {1/2-1/2 (25) Mirkowski,P (2383)
-Lemutov,I (2389) ICCF email 2017}) 13. h3 Nf6 14. Bc4 b6 15. Qb3 Bb7 16. Bf4
Bd5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (30) Nakamura,H (2746) -Shankland,S (2731) Saint Louis 2019})
10... Nc6 11. Rd1 Nb4 {Taking d5 under control. Note: Typically, Black does
not hurry to jump Nbd5; instead, he keeps the square open for the other knight
or the bishop. By doing so, he gets more flexibility and can exchange pieces
via d5 if needed} 12. Ne5 (12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Bd7 14. Ne5 Rc8 15. a5 a6 16.
Bxf6 Bxf6 17. d5 Bxe5 18. dxe6 Bxh2+ 19. Kxh2 Qh4+ 20. Kg1 Bxe6 21. Bxe6 fxe6
22. Qxe6+ Kh8 $15 {1-0 (46) Xiong,J (2679) -Gledura,B (2645) Chess.com INT 2019
}) 12... b6 {Black wants to develop the bishop on b7 whenever he has the
chance. If not able to do so, he plays Bd7, Bc6 and gives White the
opportunity to snatch the bishop pair. Note: the exchange of Ne5 for Bc6 is
not troublesome for Black as thus he trades pieces and alleviates White's
initiative} 13. Ne4 (13. Qf3 Rb8 14. Qg3 Bb7 15. Bh6 Ne8 {Black has everything
protected} 16. d5 $6 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 exd5 $15 {0-1 (41) Bosiocic,M (2600)-Yu,Y  
(2765) Batumi 2018} 18. Rd4 Bf6 $15 {Black has defended successfully}) 13...
Bb7 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Ra3 {White wants to add one more piece into the attack 
(Ra3). Therefore, Black needs to play actively and trade pieces:} Bd5 $1 {
getting rid of the strong Bc4}) 6... Bb4 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bd2 b5 9. axb5 {forcing
Black to give up the dark-squared bishop} (9. Ng5 h6 10. Nge4 (10. Qh5 O-O 11.
Nge4 f5 $1) 10... O-O 11. Be2 Be7 12. axb5 Qb6 $1 13. Be3 (13. Bxc4 $2 Qxd4 14.
Qg4 Kh8 $17) 13... Nxe3 14. fxe3 cxb5 $15 {0-1 (54) Fier,A (2582)-Debashis,D  
(2446) Korinthia 2012}) (9. h4 h6 10. Rh3 Nd7 11. Rg3 {1/2-1/2 (50) Salem,A  
(2650) -Caruana,F (2813) Douglas 2016} Nxc3 $5 12. bxc3 (12. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 13.
bxc3 O-O 14. Nd2 f5 $1 {[%csl Ge4]}) 12... Bf8 $13 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Ga7a6,
Gc8b7,Gc6c5]}) 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 cxb5 11. Ng5 {immediately trying to take
advantage of the dark squares} Bb7 (11... Nc6 12. Qh5 Qe7 13. Be2 b4 14. O-O
bxc3 15. Bc1 $44 {[%cal Gc1a3] dangerous line}) 12. Qh5 (12. h4 Nd7 13. Rh3 (
13. Qf3 Qe7 14. Ne4 Nc7 $1 15. Nd6+ Qxd6 $1 16. Qxb7 Qb6 $17) 13... Ne7 $5 (
13... Qe7 14. Qb1 Bc6 15. Ra6 (15. Be2 f5 $1) 15... N7b6 16. Ne4 $17 {1-0 (38)
Bogner,S (2504) -Rusev,K (2537) Boeblingen 2009} O-O) 14. Qh5 g6 15. Qg4 h6 16.
Ne4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Nb6 $17) 12... Qe7 13. Be2 (13. h4 Nd7 14. Rh3 (14. Ne4 O-O
15. Nd6 Bc6 16. Rh3 f6 $1 $40) 14... h6 15. Ne4 Nf4 $1 {Black does not give
White the opportunity to exploit d6} 16. Bxf4 Bxe4 17. Qg4 f5 $1) (13. Ne4 Nf4
$1 14. Qf3 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 Nd5 $15) 13... Nd7 14. Bf3 {The critical line} (14.
O-O a5 15. Rfb1 (15. Rfe1 {0-1 (44) Roos,A (2290) -Van Foreest,J (2615)
Netherlands 2017} Nc7) (15. Qh3 Nc7) 15... Bc6 16. Bg4 (16. Ne4 O-O 17. Nd6
Rfb8 $15) (16. Qh3 N7b6) 16... Nc7 17. Bd1 g6 18. Qh3 (18. Qh6 Qf8 19. Qh4 Qe7)
18... h6 19. Bc2 Nb6 20. Ne4 Bxe4 21. Bxe4 Nbd5 22. Qf3 {1/2-1/2 (24) Wang,H  
(2683)-Fressinet,L (2662) Sharjah 2017} (22. Bxd5 Nxd5 23. Rxb5 a4 $11) 22...
Qd7 23. h4 h5 $15) (14. Bg4 Nc7 15. O-O h6 16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 O-O 18. Ra5
Rfb8 19. Qg4 {1/2-1/2 (37) Moiseenko,A (2643)-Postny,E (2627) Maalot-Tarshiha
2008} Nd5 $146 20. Re1 (20. Bxh6 f5 $1) 20... a6 21. Bxh6 f5 $1) 14... a5 $5
$146 (14... N7b6 {Wagner,D (2571)-Grandelius,N (2665) Minsk 2017}) 15. O-O (15.
Ne4 O-O 16. Nd6 Bc6 {[%cal Yf7f6]}) (15. Qh3 b4 $1) 15... Bc6 {The position is
closed and Black is not rushing with 0-0} (15... h6 16. Ne4 O-O 17. Nd6 Bc6 18.
Qg4 $44) 16. Qh3 (16. Ne4 O-O $15) 16... N7b6 17. Ne4 Kf8 $5 (17... O-O {
is dangerous}) 18. Nd6 h5 $13 {[%cal Yg7g6,Yf8g7] Black has managed to protect
everything and has extra material. However, he still needs to be careful with
the position of his king} *

