{The Exchange Slav is sometimes wrongly considered as a boring and drawish
line. If you look at the names of the players using this line for White, it
will become obvious to you that such strong players cannot play for a draw. As
it will become clear by the end of this lecture, not only White but also Black
can create imbalances and fight for the win in this variation. Before
proceeding with the model games, I would like to briefly explain the general
ideas. Of course, you will find more detailed explanations in the video part
of the lecture. The main move order is} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 {
This move order was suggested as the best in the book of Sakaev. Since then,
most of the strong players started playing in this way.} Nc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 ({
Against this exact move order, Black can play} 5... Bf5 {which will be
discussed later in the lecture. For the moment we need to focus on the typical
ideas and structures.}) 6. e3 {At this point, Black is at crossroads. In my
opinion, the most precise move is} a6 {This move is a kind of prophylaxis
against Qb3 that will be played when Black develops his light-squared to f5 or
g4.} ({Another option is (or 6...Bg4) when the critical position arises after} 
6... Bf5 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 {Had Black played ...a7-a6, this check would
have been answered with ...b7-b5.} 9. Qc2 {The point behind White's play. Now,
Black's light-squared bishop will remain behind the pawn chain.}) ({In this
structure, the move} 6... g6 $6 {is generally a bad idea since the bishop has
nothing to do on g7. A possible continuation would be} 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9.
Bd3 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Qe2 {[%cal Gd3a6,Ga1c1,Ga2a3,Gc1c2,Gf1c1] when White
enjoys a clear advantage. The g7-bishop does not cooperate with the rest of
the pieces. White can now develop his queenside play in a flawless way.}) ({
The move} 6... e6 $6 {is strategically risky because the light-squared bishop
remains inside the pawn chain. In this exact move order, White can make use of
the fact that his knight is still on g1 -} 7. Bd3 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. f4 {
[%csl Rc8,Gd3] Had the light-squared bishops been exchanged, this advance
would have been a very bad idea. Now, however, White has decent attacking
chances on the kingside.}) 7. Bd3 Bg4 {Since the f5-square is not available,
Black should develop his bishop to g4. We shall take a look at two main moves.
The most popular one is} 8. Nge2 ({It's very important, however, to know the
basic ideas in the positions with} 8. Nf3 e6 9. O-O Bd6 {We don't mind
exchanging our good bishop since the problematic bishop was successfully
developed.} 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Rc1 O-O 12. h3 Bh5 {A very important moment. In
general, Black will exchange the light-squared bishop for the knight in any
case. Before doing that, however, I mostly like to force the white bishop into
the passive e2-square.} 13. Be2 Bxf3 $1 {By means of this exchange, Black
creates a slight material imbalance. Very often it turns out that the white
bishop is useless in this pawn structure. This is one of the ways to play for
a win in the Exchange Slav.} 14. Bxf3 Rac8 {This is one of the most important
types of positions that you should know. Black's main idea is to transfer his
knight to the perfect d6-square. For example, after a move such as} 15. a3 {
a typical idea to consider would be} Qe7 {[%cal Gf6e8,Ge8d6] followed by ...
Ne8-d6. Note that very often the other knight can go to d6 via the route
a5-c4-d6.} 16. Be2 Ne8 17. Bd3 Nd6 {We can say that Black at on the positive
side of the equality. As you will see in the model games, the white bishop is
often useless in this structure. Black's plan is rather simple. After doubling
the rooks on the c-file he will expand by ...b7-b5 followed by ...Na5-c4.}) ({
As mentioned, after ...a7-a6, the move} 8. Qb3 $6 {is not dangerous anymore
because of} Na5 9. Qa4+ b5 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga5c4] followed by ...Rc8 and ...Nc4
and Black takes over.}) 8... e6 9. O-O Bd6 {I believe that this is the most
precise move order.} ({After} 9... Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Bd6 {White would have the
additional option of} 11. Bg5 {Even here, however, Black has a decent play. A
typical way to fight against the pin on the diagonal h4-d8 is} O-O 12. Rac1 Be7
$1 {A very important move. The idea can be seen after} 13. a3 Ne8 $1 14. Bf4
Bd6 {This is the point. It turns out that the knight will finally reach the
perfect d6-square.}) 10. f3 Bh5 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Nf4 Bg6 {We have
reached a very typical situation in which White must take an important
decision. Many players go wrong by playing} 14. Nxg6 $6 {we already know that
Black is happy to give his light-squared bishop for a knight. White should
have rather exchanged the light-squared bishops.} hxg6 {Now, besides the usual
idea of maneuvring the knight to d6, Black will seriously consider the advance
...e6-e5. This advance works very well when White had played f2-f3. In many
lines, the e3-pawn will be quite vulnerable. In the model games section, you
will find many examples featuring this idea. The last important idea to
remember is the reaction to the advance b2-b4. For example after} 15. a3 Rac8 (
15... e5 {might be even better but I want to illustrate another thematic idea.}
) 16. b4 {Whenever you see such a move, you should always consider} a5 $1 {
when after} 17. b5 Nb8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6] Black's main idea is to transfer
the knight to b6. Black is already fighting for an advantage.} *

