{This is a highly instructive game. The critical position arises on move 14.} 
1. c4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bd3 ({After} 
7. h3 {stopping ...Bg4, Black would play} Bf5) 7... Bg4 8. f3 Bh5 9. Rc1 e6 10.
Nge2 Bd6 11. O-O Bg6 12. a3 Bxf4 13. Nxf4 O-O 14. Nxg6 $2 {I don't like this
decision since the knight is better than the bishop.} ({White should have
played} 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Nd3 {Just like Black wants to put his knight on d6,
White should do the same. At the end of the day, this is a symmetrical
position.} Ne8 16. Qe2 Nd6 $11 {Even though the position is approximately
equal, the draw is far away. In the future, White might experience slight
problems due to the vulnerable e3-pawn. In this line of thoughts, a move such
as ...Nc4 might become really annoying.}) 14... hxg6 15. b4 $6 {After this
typical inaccuracy, the computer immediately shows an advantage for Black.
Moreover, Black has three logical candidate moves.} Ne8 {This is the least
appealing candidate move. Even though it's completely playable, I find it a
bit too passive.} ({In general, when seeing the advance b2-b4, my first
instinct is to break with} 15... a5 $1 16. b5 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge7c8,Gc8b6,Gc6a7,
Ga7c8] As always, after b4-b5, Black should find a way to get his knight to b6.
He can choose between 2 routes - a7-c8-b6 or e7-c8-b6. In this concrete
position, I would prefer} Ne7 {since the e7-square is a bit more flexible. A
possible continuation would be} 17. a4 Nc8 18. Qb3 Nb6 {[%cal Gd8d6,Gf8c8,
Ge6e5] The mission is accomplished. Now, Black should start fighting for the
c-file. Meanwhile, with a pawn on f3, the advance ...e6-e5 is always in the
air. White's basic problem in this position is the completely useless
d3-bishop.} 19. Rc2 Qd6 ({An additional possibility would be} 19... Ne8 {
[%cal Ge8d6] with the idea to increase the control over c4-square.}) 20. Rfc1
Rfc8 $17 21. g3 e5) ({Of course, with a pawn on f3} 15... e5 $1 {always makes
sense. For example, after} 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Be2 Nc6 $15 {Black is already
slightly better due to the vulnerable e3-pawn.} ({A logical alternative is} 
17... Re8 18. Kh1 Nc4 19. Bxc4 dxc4 20. e4 b5 $15 {[%csl Gc4] when the strong
c4-pawn gives Black a slight advantage.}) ({The computer shows the somehow
unhuman} 17... Qb6 18. Qd4 Qe6 $15 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ge5c6] with the idea of
increasing the pressure on e3 by means of ...Nc6.})) 16. Na4 Nd6 17. Nc5 Ne7 $1
{I like this move very much. The knight is heading to f5. Actually, with a
knight on c6, White was already threatening to take on a6.} 18. Re1 Nef5 19. a4
({Taking the knight with} 19. Bxf5 {is suspicious because after} gxf5 {Black
not only increases his central control but also can get the advantage of weak
c4-square. On the other hand, the c5-square is not weak since the move ...
b7-b6 is always possible.}) 19... b5 $1 {A very strong idea. With his moves,
Black demonstrates that the c5-knight is useless.} 20. axb5 axb5 21. Ra1 Qg5 $3
{A very strong idea. Black is trying to provoke further weaknesses.} 22. f4 (
22. Qd2 $2 {is met by} Nxd4 23. f4 Nf3+ $19) 22... Qe7 $17 {Black has an
obvious advantage.} 23. g4 Nh4 24. Qe2 g5 25. Ra5 gxf4 26. exf4 Qf6 27. Qe3
Qxd4 28. Qxd4 Nf3+ 29. Kf2 Nxd4 30. Rea1 Rac8 31. Ra6 Nc4 32. Nd7 Rfd8 33. Nb6
Rb8 34. Bxc4 dxc4 35. Ra8 Nc2 36. R1a5 Nxb4 37. Rxb8 Rxb8 38. Ra8 Rxa8 39. Nxa8
Nd5 0-1

