{[%evp 0,120,61,15,27,-11,33,12,30,29,27,27,12,16,8,7,12,7,10,-2,5,3,13,7,5,2,
14,20,11,0,-5,-25,-33,-25,-30,-45,-31,-31,-29,-37,-35,-39,-26,-31,-23,-26,-29,
-45,-39,-38,-33,-28,-15,-16,-25,-28,-28,-22,-26,-35,-33,-37,-44,-58,-23,-37,0,
0,0,0,-19,-4,21,7,3,13,13,10,10,10,10,10,10,-29,0,-69,-47,-66,-87,-87,-90,-91,
-113,-168,-113,-88,-111,-174,-181,-188,-187,-207,-154,-140,-154,-159,-146,-137,
-174,-297,-240,-353,-362,-365,-358,-473,-333,-746,-806,-920,-848,-716,-849]
This fantastic game shows that there are many subtleties even in seemingly
equal endgames.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 ({More usual move order
is} 4. Bf4 Nc6 5. e3) 4... Nc6 5. Bf4 Bf5 ({White's move order allows Black an
extra option -} 5... e5 6. dxe5 d4 {Even though White is objectively better,
practically speaking, the position is very complicated. As White, I wouldn't
like to play this position against a well prepared opponent.}) 6. e3 e6 {
Later in the lecture, we are going to examine this move order in a greater
detail. The point is that Black does not clarify the position of his g8-knight.
As it often turns out, it's better to develop the knight via e7.} 7. Nf3 Bd6 $5
8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Bd3 Nge7 {Black wants to exchange the light-squared bishops on
his own terms. The idea is to put a knight on f5 and then transfer it to the
perfect d6-square.} ({Another decent option would have been} 9... Bg4 $1 {
As we already know, by exchanging his light-squared bishop for the knight,
Black creates imbalances. A possible follow up would be} 10. Rc1 Nf6 11. O-O
O-O 12. h3 Bh5 {Actually, before taking on f3, I prefer to provoke the move
Be2. In this way, the white bishop will be forced into a passive position.} ({
Of course, there is nothing wrong with} 12... Bxf3 $5 13. Qxf3 Rfc8 {Remember
that it's generally better to put this rook on c8. The other rook can be
employed via a or b-file. The next step would be to transfer the knight to d6 -
} 14. a3 Qd8 15. Qe2 Ne8 $132 {[%cal Ge8d6] I believe that in such positions,
Black is on the positive side of the equality. A possible continuation of the
game would be} 16. Na4 Nd6 17. Nc5 b6 {In general, I like the fact that Black
hadn't played ...a7-a6. Otherwise, in order to prepare for this move, he
should have started with ...a6-a5.} 18. Na6 Ne7 {Even though the position is
objectively equal, the material imbalance allows us to play for a win. Very
often, the d3-bishop is useless in such positions. Since in some cases, the
h7-pawn might be hanging, try to play ...g7-g6, when you have a spare move.})
13. Be2 Bxf3 $1) 10. O-O O-O 11. Bxf5 Nxf5 12. Qd3 Rfc8 {Once again, it's
better to put the king's rook on c8.} 13. Rfc1 Qd8 {[%cal Gf5d6] Preparing ...
Nd6.} 14. Na4 Nd6 15. Nc5 b6 {Now, Black has a small initiative} 16. Na6 $6 {
This move is not precise. As we are going to witness, White will have problems
with this knight.} ({Better would have been} 16. Na4) 16... Qd7 {[%cal Gc6a5]
Black is already preparing ...Na5 that would provide him with an active play
on the queenside. At this point, the game went into an endgame after} 17. Nd2
Na5 18. b3 Rxc1+ 19. Rxc1 Rc8 20. Rc3 Rxc3 21. Qxc3 Qc6 22. Qxc6 Nxc6 {[%csl
Ra6] White already faces big practical problems due to the misplaced knight.
Even though he had some chances to save the game, Black finally managed to win.
} 23. Nb1 Kf8 24. Nc3 Ke7 25. b4 Ne4 26. Nxe4 dxe4 27. b5 Na5 28. Nb4 Kd6 29.
Kf1 Nc4 30. Nc6 a5 31. Ke2 Na3 32. Na7 Kc7 33. Kd2 Kb7 34. Nc6 Kc7 35. Na7 Nc4+
36. Kc3 Nd6 37. a4 Nf5 38. Nc6 f6 39. g3 Kd6 40. Kd2 h5 41. h3 h4 42. g4 Nh6
43. Ke2 Nf7 44. Kf1 Ng5 45. Kg2 Nf3 46. Kf1 Ng5 47. Kg2 Nf3 48. Kf1 e5 49.
dxe5+ Nxe5 50. Nd4 Kd5 51. Nf5 g5 52. Ke2 Nd7 53. Ne7+ Kc4 54. f3 Kb3 55. Nd5
exf3+ 56. Kxf3 Kxa4 57. Ke4 Kxb5 58. Kf5 Kc4 59. e4 a4 60. Ke6 a3 0-1

