{[%evp 0,106,27,27,27,-3,35,16,17,20,15,7,27,24,28,28,68,47,49,60,52,52,42,37,
37,18,31,32,36,-22,0,-27,-13,-14,1,16,22,-13,45,9,3,-44,-36,-40,-35,-46,-20,
-56,-7,-55,-19,-32,15,-20,8,-5,-19,-42,-46,-56,-68,-35,-60,-102,-52,-144,-144,
-158,-150,-213,-313,-320,-306,-302,-323,-323,-333,-332,-151,-760,-99,-115,-111,
-178,-111,-107,-107,-135,-93,-77,-87,-26,-17,-58,-81,-506,-511,-564,-588,-638,
-645,-687,-703,-740,-740,-796,-795,-838,-895]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5
4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 {This is considered to be a bit more
precise move order. White is playing against the c8-bishop.} ({Against} 7. Nf3
{my preference is} Bg4 ({Even though} 7... Bf5 {is playable as well.}) 8. Be2
Bxf3 {The idea of the immediate recapture is to deprive White of the
possibility of Ne5.} ({After} 8... e6 9. Ne5 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Rc8 {Black will
easily parry White's slight initiative.}) 9. Bxf3 e6 10. O-O {This is a type
of position that you will get very often. Below, you will see a line that I
have created myself. The idea is to illustrate one of the favourable scenarios
for Black.} Bd6 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Rc1 Be7 $1 {[%cal Gf6e8] Don't forget this
typical idea. Black is preparing the move ...Ne8.} 13. a3 Ne8 14. Bf4 Bd6 $1 {
Keep in mind that our final goal is to put the knight on d6. Sometimes, less
experienced players opt for} 15. Bg3 $6 {You should be always happy to see
this move. In such a case, we should take immediately on g3 -} Bxg3 16. hxg3
Nd6 {In symmetrical positions, every slight positional achievement is of a
tremendous importance. Therefore, White's doubled pawns on g2 and g3 are an
important victory for Black.} 17. Be2 Qe7 18. b4 a5 $1 {Typical reaction to
b2-b4.} 19. b5 Nb8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6] The knight is heading for b6.} 20. Na4
Nd7 21. Qb3 Rfc8 {In this imbalanced position, Black is definitely fighting
for a win. A very typical endgame would arise after} 22. Nc5 b6 23. Nxd7 Qxd7
24. a4 Rxc1 25. Rxc1 Rc8 26. Qb2 Rxc1+ 27. Qxc1 Qc8 28. Qxc8+ Nxc8 29. Bd3 Nd6
30. f3 f5 $15 {This position is not equal at all. Actually, White will very
much regret playing Bg3. He would have loved to have a pawn on h2 instead of
g3. Black can bring the king to f6, thus preparing the advance ...e6-e5.}) 7...
Bg4 8. f3 {This is the most ambitious continuation.} ({The alternative is} 8.
Nf3 {At this point I prefer} e6 9. O-O Bd6 ({Of course, there is nothing wrong
with} 9... Be7) 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Rc1 O-O 12. h3 Bh5 {As I have pointed out in
my comments to the previous example, I usually like to wait with the exchange
until White goes for Be2.} ({Obviously, the alternative} 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3
Rac8 {would bring us to the same type of position.}) 13. Be2 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Rac8
15. Na4 {Typically, the white knight is heading for the c5-square.} ({A very
important tactical idea can be seen in the following line:} 15. Be2 Rc7 ({
Better is to prepare the d6-square for the knight by playing} 15... Qe7 {
when after} 16. Na4 Ne4 17. Bd3 Nd6 {Black enjoys a very nice game.}) 16. Na4
Rfc8 17. Nc5 {In this position, a typical tactical mistake would be} Nd7 $2 {
when after} 18. Nxb7 $3 Rxb7 19. Bxa6 Rcb8 20. Bxb7 Rxb7 21. Qd2 {White is
practically winning. After taking the c-file under control and neutralizing
Black's immediate ideas, White will start pushing his queenside pawns. Black
does not have any counterplay in this position.} h6 22. Rc3 Nb6 23. b3 Ne7 24.
Rfc1 $18) 15... Nd7 16. Be2 Ne7 17. Qd2 b5 {When the c5-square is well covered,
this move becomes possible.} 18. Nc3 Nb6 19. b3 Qb4 20. Nb1 Qxd2 21. Nxd2 Nf5
22. Bd3 {Once again, we have an equal position but not without chances to
outplay the opponent.} Nd6) 8... Bh5 9. Qb3 Na5 {This move is one of the
classical antidotes to Qb3.} ({If Black wants to avoid forcing a draw, he has
the option of} 9... Ra7 $1 $132 {The rook is only temporarily misplaced on a7.
At the same time, the white queen is a bit misplaced as well.} 10. Nge2 e6 11.
O-O Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Nf4 Bg6 14. Rfc1 O-O {We have reached a kind of a
thematic position we are already familiar with. As we know, a typical
positional mistake would be} 15. Nxg6 $6 hxg6 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Ge6e5] when
Black managed to imbalance the position. Since White has committed to f2-f3,
the advance ...e6-e5 becomes quite tempting. In case of} 16. f4 {I would
consider} b5 ({There is nothing wrong with} 16... Qe7 {[%cal Gf6e8,Ge8d6]
planning ...Ne8-d6.}) 17. a4 Na5 18. Qd1 {At this point, Black can fight for a
win in two different ways -} Nc4 ({or} 18... b4)) 10. Qa4+ Nc6 ({Note that} 
10... b5 $4 {is a blunder. The computer already gives +5.} 11. Bxb5+ axb5 12.
Nxb5 $18 Qd7 13. Nc7+ Kd8 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 15. Nxa8 $18) 11. Rc1 e6 12. Nh3 $6 {
I don't like this move at all. Of course, the knight will be misplaced on h3.}
Be7 {Since the knight is stuck on h3, ...Bd6 does not make so much sense in
this position.} 13. O-O Bg6 $1 14. Be2 O-O 15. a3 b5 {By using the misplaced
white queen, Black starts his typical queenside invasion. The next step is to
transfer the knight to c4.} 16. Qd1 Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4] So far, we have often
seen White transferring his knight to c5. Since the structure is symmetrical,
both sides have the same plans.} 17. a4 {Trying to weaken Black's control of
the c4-square.} ({In case of the passive} 17. Nf2 Nc4 18. Bxc4 bxc4 {Black is
clearly better due to the space advantage on the queenside. Later on, he will
be trying to put pressure along the b-file.} ({even} 18... dxc4 {makes a lot
of sense.})) 17... b4 18. Nb1 Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6]} 19. Nd2 Nd6 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 {
[%cal Ge6e5] Black is clearly better due to the bishop pair and the
possibility of ...e6-e5.} 21. f4 ({In case of} 21. Nf4 e5 22. Nxg6 hxg6 {
Black is better. White will very much regret playing f2-f3.}) 21... Rfc8 {
Black enjoys an obvious advantage.} 22. Nf2 Qb6 23. Nd3 b3 24. g4 h6 25. f5
exf5 26. gxf5 Bh7 27. Bg4 Bg5 28. Nf4 Qb7 29. Nb1 Nc4 30. Qe2 Re8 31. Rc3 Qd7
32. Rxb3 Bxf5 33. Bxf5 Qxf5 34. Qf2 Rab8 35. Rxb8 Rxb8 36. Nc3 Rxb2 37. Qg3 Qc2
38. Ncxd5 Bxf4 39. Rxf4 Qxa4 40. Ne7+ Kf8 41. Ng6+ Kg8 42. Ne7+ Kf8 43. Nf5
Rb1+ 44. Kg2 g5 45. Rf2 Qc6+ 46. Kh3 Rb3 47. Kg4 Nxe3+ 48. Nxe3 Qe6+ 49. Nf5
Rxg3+ 50. hxg3 a5 51. d5 Qxd5 52. Nxh6 Qd4+ 53. Kf3 Qf6+ 0-1

