{This is a very instructive game featuring White's Stonewall setup.} 1. d4 d5
2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 ({In his book
about the Exchange Slav, Dreev suggests} 7. Be2 {when I think that Black
should play} Bf5 {The idea behind Be2 is to win space by means} 8. g4 {but
after} Be4 9. f3 Bg6 {the position is getting double-edged.}) 7... Bg4 8. Nge2
e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. f4 $2 {This is a bad positional decision.
White the black bishop outside the pawn chain, White does not have attacking
chances. Therefore, with his last move, he only creates weaknesses.} ({Of
course, we can understand Nikola Vasovski. He was just afraid that after the
usual} 11. f3 Bh5 12. Rc1 O-O {[%cal Ge6e5] Black will be preparing ...e6-e5
that is usually favourable with a white pawn on f3.}) 11... O-O 12. Rc1 Rfc8
13. Qd2 {Now that the e2-knight is ready to leave its passive position, Black
should play} Bxe2 $1 {The exchange of the light-squared bishop for a knight is
always favourable for Black.} 14. Qxe2 Rc7 ({I think that maneuvring the
knight to d6 by} 14... Ne8 {would be premature since White gets a lot of free
play on the kingside.}) 15. Rf3 ({A terrible positional decision would be} 15.
f5 $2 e5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 {when White is strategically lost due to his numerous
weaknesses.}) 15... Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4] Again, we see the thematic knight
transfer to c4.} 16. Rcf1 Nc4 17. Rh3 {I think that White's attack is more of
an illusion. Black's queenside counterplay is very fast.} g6 18. g4 Qb4 19. g5
Ne8 {Already White should reckon with Black's threats on the queenside.} 20.
Nd1 ({After} 20. Qg4 Nxb2 21. Qh4 Qxc3 $19 {White can only give two checks.})
20... f5 $1 {I like this idea. The c7-rook is joining the defence.} 21. gxf6
Nxf6 22. Rg3 Nd6 23. Nc3 Nf5 {Nothing is left from White's attack. At the same
time, his position is full of weaknesses. Later on, the Swedish GM managed to
convert his big advantage.} 24. Rg2 Rac8 25. Kh1 b5 26. Qe1 Kf7 27. Rc2 Qf8 28.
a3 Qh6 29. Re2 Qh3 30. Qf2 $2 (30. Rg1 $15) 30... Ng4 $19 31. Qf3 Ng3+ 32. Kg1
Qxf1+ 33. Qxf1 Nxf1 34. Kxf1 Rxc3 0-1

