{[%evp 0,62,29,26,21,-7,46,34,49,24,24,7,27,24,41,38,57,34,42,12,34,39,36,29,
27,26,26,25,27,28,24,13,13,18,36,-21,-17,-21,-21,-33,-31,-41,-45,-53,-19,-17,
-21,-48,-41,-52,-33,-68,-23,-93,-88,-125,-29,-33,-15,-55,-31,-111,-130,-106,
-106] This game is a great performance by Black.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6
4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 ({Later in the lecture, I am going to provide a
brief overview of the line} 6. Nf3 a6 7. e3 {when Black's best choice would be}
Bg4 {planning} 8. Be2 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 e6 {with a familiar type of position.}) 6...
a6 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. f3 Bh5 11. Rc1 Bg6 12. Na4 {This is
the most precise continuation.} ({White shouldn't be in a hurry with the
exchange} 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 {because the black queen is very active on d6.}) 12...
Bxd3 13. Qxd3 O-O 14. Bxd6 {Finally, White goes for this exchange.} ({Another
option would have been} 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Qe7 {when Black has decent
counterplay in view of the possible advance ...e6-e5. For example, after} 16.
Rfc1 {White should reckon with the idea of} Nh5 {In a favourable moment, Black
will exchange on f4 and stabilize the position. Despite the objective equality,
we can always rely on some ideas based on ... e6-e5.}) 14... Qxd6 15. Qb3 Rab8
16. Nc5 Qe7 17. f4 $2 {Since White has played f2-f3, he is afraid of a
well-timed ...e6-e5! So, he tries to prevent it with 17.f4? ...but this is
weakening his position too much! Black is taking over. After all, the Slav
Exchange is not a forced draw.} Na5 $3 {The knight as always belongs to d6! ...
even more now, that e4-square (and e3 pawn) are weak!} 18. Qd3 Nc4 19. b3 Nd6
20. Rc2 Rfc8 $17 {Black already enjoys a huge advantage.} 21. Rfc1 Rc7 (21...
Rc6 $1 {was even better}) 22. Nc3 Rbc8 23. N3a4 Rc6 24. h3 h5 $1 {A very nice
positional move, fixing the kingside structure.} 25. Kh2 R8c7 26. Qd1 Nf5 27.
Qd3 Qd8 28. Nc3 Qc8 29. b4 Ne4 $1 30. g4 hxg4 31. hxg4 Nfd6 0-1

