{[%evp 0,84,23,17,17,2,35,29,37,24,24,7,27,20,27,9,9,5,5,1,17,-1,4,-5,0,-7,-27,
-24,-21,-2,-1,1,-11,-14,9,9,-47,-37,-44,-69,-69,-51,-55,-61,-61,-61,-39,-54,
-23,-104,-106,-119,-98,-109,-104,-124,-131,-112,-89,-176,-227,-227,-267,-254,
-254,-283,-297,-323,-308,-308,-315,-406,-346,-390,-405,-440,-459,-457,-465,
-468,-460,-494,-510,-512,-342,-621,-512] A very good game by Black clearly
showing that there are not enough recourses for an attack after all the piece
exchanges! The move 11.f4? was a big mistake!} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4.
cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 Bf5 {Even though this is not my suggested move
order, the game is instructive for the pawn structure.} ({My preference is} 
6... a6) 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 9. Rc1 Bd6 {Of course, there is nothing wrong
with this natural move.} ({When the light-squared bishops are exchanged so
early, however, I prefer} 9... Be7 {The reason is that the e7-bishop will
contribute to our future queenside play. At the same time, the white bishop is
shooting at the emptiness.}) 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. f4 $2 {Even though this move
looks tempting, it's a clear positional mistake. Such a decision would have
been justified with a white bishop on d3 and a black one on d7 or c8! After
the exchange of all the bishops, White does not have attacking resources.} O-O
12. Nf3 Rac8 13. O-O a6 $15 {[%cal Gc8c7,Gf8c8] Preparing to double the rooks.}
14. Ne5 Rc7 15. g4 Rfc8 16. g5 Ne8 $17 17. Nxc6 {Probably White should already
go for this exchange. Otherwise, Black was ready to play the thematic ...Ne7.}
({For example, after} 17. a3 Ne7 18. Qd2 Nf5 {[%cal Gd6d8,Ge8d6] followed by ..
. Qd8, and ...Ned6, Black's knights will be ready to use all the weaknesses in
White's camp. In the endgame, the e5-knight will be chased away by means of ...
f7-f6.}) 17... Rxc6 18. Rf2 Qe7 {[%cal Ge8d6]} 19. Rcf1 Nd6 20. h4 {White's
attack is going no where.} b5 21. a3 ({In the case of} 21. a4 {,besides ...
b5-b4, Black can play the even more precise} bxa4 22. Nxa4 Ne4 {[%csl Ra4]
[%cal Ge7b4] The a4-knight is dominated. Black is ready to follow with ...Qb4
with winning position.}) 21... Nc4 $17 {[%cal Gc4b2] Black already enjoys a
significant advantage that he managed to convert.} 22. Na2 Qb7 23. Qe2 a5 24.
h5 Nd6 25. Qe1 Ne4 26. Rg2 Qb6 27. f5 exf5 28. Rxf5 Rc2 29. Nc3 Rxg2+ 30. Kxg2
Qe6 31. Rf4 Nxg5 32. Qg3 h6 33. Qg4 b4 34. axb4 axb4 35. Nd1 Qxg4+ 36. Rxg4
Rc2+ 37. Kf1 Rd2 38. Nf2 Rxb2 39. Nd3 Rb1+ 40. Ke2 b3 41. Rg2 Ra1 42. Rg4 b2
0-1

