{[%evp 0,82,17,17,17,4,52,24,24,24,24,-11,7,9,5,1,0,-4,21,-15,-15,-14,-14,-14,
-5,-1,2,-22,-30,-39,-34,-34,-34,-50,-50,-50,-50,-38,-31,-31,-47,-67,-65,-85,
-59,-54,-66,-61,-39,-79,-21,-13,0,0,0,0,0,-33,-12,-23,-23,-19,-12,-13,-13,-17,
-22,-524,-503,-503,-549,-569,-569,-569,-592,-592,-599,-29987,-670,-685,-689,
-711,-670,-703,-693] This game illustrates all the typical problems that White
would face if he develops his bishop to g2.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4.
d4 Nc6 5. g3 $6 {Putting the bishop on g2 in the Exchange Slav is as bad as
playing ...g7-g6 followed by ...Bg7 with Black.} Bg4 6. Bg2 e6 7. O-O Bd6 8.
Nc3 Nge7 ({Another option would have been} 8... Nf6) 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 $2 {
Another poor positional move. In the long run, Black will definitely make use
of the weak c4-square. With a bishop on g2, this square is getting even more
vulnerable.} Rc8 {Before going for the thematic ...a7-a5, Black wants to force
the white bishop into the passive b2-square.} ({The immediate} 10... a5 11. b5
Nb8 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6,Gb6c4] would have been possible as well.} ({or
} 11... Na7 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga7c8,Gc8b6,Gb6c4]})) 11. Bb2 a5 {Now, this idea
is even more powerful.} 12. b5 Nb8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6] The knight is heading
for c4.} 13. Rc1 Nd7 14. Na4 Rxc1 15. Qxc1 Nb6 16. Nxb6 ({After} 16. Nc5 Qb8
17. Qb1 Rc8 18. Rc1 Nc4 {Black is dominating. White the c4-square is very weak
(especially with a bishop on g2), the c5-square is not a hole. Black can
always play ...b7-b6.}) 16... Qxb6 17. a4 Rc8 $17 {Black enjoys a clear
advantage due to his better bishops and White's queenside weaknesses. Later on,
he managed to win, not without adventures though.} 18. Qa1 Rc2 19. e3 Qc7 20.
Rc1 Bb4 21. Ne5 Bf5 22. Bf1 Bd2 23. Rd1 f6 24. Nd3 h5 25. Ne1 Bxe1 26. Rxe1 Nc8
27. Be2 Nd6 28. Rc1 h4 29. Bd1 Rc4 30. Bb3 hxg3 31. hxg3 Qf7 32. Ba3 Be4 33.
Kf1 Qh5 34. Ke1 Bd3 35. Bd1 Qh1+ 36. Kd2 Ne4+ 37. Kxd3 Qe1 38. Rc2 Rc3+ 39.
Qxc3 Qxd1+ 40. Qd2 Nxd2 41. Rxd2 Qb3+ 0-1

