{[%evp 0,60,14,14,14,3,24,23,20,19,24,24,24,24,35,24,29,26,22,-1,17,7,21,-11,3,
-4,-7,-6,31,22,12,16,0,-3,13,8,15,2,4,-8,13,11,13,11,10,2,7,-1,7,0,2,4,15,22,
14,2,5,2,0,8,9,5,4] In this example, I will show some typical ideas in the
system with an early Nf3.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6
6. Bf4 a6 7. e3 Bg4 {As always, Black wants to exchange his bishop for the
knight in order to create imbalances.} 8. Be2 e6 9. O-O Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Bd6 11.
Bg5 ({As always, after} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Rc1 O-O {[%cal Gf8c8,Gd6e7,Gf6e8,
Ge8d6] Black will try to bring his knight to d6 via e8. At the same time, one
should never forget about the importance of the c-file.}) 11... O-O 12. Rc1 h6
13. Bh4 {This is a typical way to fight against the pin along the h4-d8
diagonal. Black is planning to exchange the dark-squared bishops by means of ..
.Ne8 or .. .Nd7.} Be7 {[%cal Gf6e8,Gf6d7]} 14. Na4 Nd7 ({A very decent
alternative is} 14... Ne8 15. Bg3 Bd6 $1 {The main point behind Black's
strategy. In the next example, I would like to demonstrate what would happen
if White allows ...Bxg3.} 16. Nc5 Bxg3 17. hxg3 {As I have already pointed out,
in symmetrical positions, you should always try to spoil the opponent's
structure.} Qe7 {When the white knight is on c5, we always need to reckon with
the ideas of Nxb7 and Nxa6.} ({For example,} 17... Nd6 $2 {is answered with}
18. Nxb7 $18 {[%csl Rc6]}) 18. Qd2 Nd6 19. b3 Rac8 20. Rc2 a5 21. a3 (21. Rfc1
Nb4) 21... b6 {Now, Black's strategy consists of getting an endgame knight vs
bishop.} 22. Na4 Qb7 23. Rfc1 Ne7 24. Rxc8 Rxc8 25. Rxc8+ Nexc8 26. Nc3 Ne7 {
Black has good chances to play for a win in this position with a slight
material imbalance. Let's suppose that White exchanges the knights with} 27.
Be2 g6 28. Nb5 Nxb5 29. Bxb5 Nc8 30. Bd3 Nd6 31. Qc2 Kf8 ({Another logical
move is} 31... h5 {fixing the structure.}) (31... Qc8 $2 32. Bxg6 $1) 32. Kf1
Qc8 33. Qxc8+ Nxc8 34. Ke2 Nd6 {This position is not a draw. Having a better
minor piece, Black can keep playing for a long time. Let me show, one
cooperative line that illustrates how we should meet the idea f2-f3 followed
by e3-e4.} 35. Kd2 Kg7 36. f3 f6 37. e4 {At this point. the thematic reaction
is} dxe4 38. fxe4 e5 {Fixing the e4-pawn on the colour of the bishop. For
example, after} 39. d5 f5 {Black has already a winning advantage. The doubled
pawns on g2 and g3 make White's position is even more hopeless.}) 15. Bxe7 Qxe7
16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. Rxc5 {Here, the play will be quite similar to the previous
line. Black will try to exchange all heavy pieces. A typical follow-up would be
} Rac8 18. Qc2 Na7 19. Rc1 b6 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Qd2 Qb7 22. Rxc8+ Nxc8 23. Qc3
Nd6 24. Be2 a5 25. Bd3 Qc8 26. Qxc8+ Nxc8 {Once again, we get the same endgame
structure. This time, however, White has better chances for a draw because
there are no doubled pawns on the g-file. We already know that} 27. f3 {
should be answered with} f6 28. e4 dxe4 29. fxe4 e5 $1 30. dxe5 (30. d5 Nd6 {
is already familiar to us. Black should prepare the advance ...f6-f5.}) 30...
fxe5 31. Kf2 Nd6 {The position is still not equal because the knight is
superior to the bishop. In the future, Black can try to invade via the dark
squares.} *

