{[%evp 0,48,19,31,43,-16,29,32,30,35,25,24,12,14,13,22,8,9,13,8,8,30,6,2,-10,
-9,4,-38,-42,-43,-34,-27,-44,-39,-50,-54,-40,-45,-28,-40,-42,-43,-44,-40,-17,
-6,-21,-11,-8,-5,1]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nc6 5. e3 ({The
same setup works against} 5. Nc3 {as well -} Bf5 (5... e5 {is another
interesting system.}) 6. e3 e6) 5... Bf5 $1 {This is a very interesting, and
less known system in the Slav Exhange. Just like White postpones Nf3, we also
postpone ...Nf6 and in many cases we go ...Nge7 followed by ...f7-f6 and ...
g7-g5. Also, our knight from e7 can go to c8 followed by Bd6!} 6. Nc3 {in my
view, 6.Qb3 is more accurate .. BUT ALMOST ALL PLAYERS WILL START WITH 6.Nc3 ..
.SO YOU MUST KNOW HOW TO PLAY AND GET GREAT POSITIONS FIGHTING FOR THE
INITIATIVE RIGHT FROM THE START!} (6. Qb3 $1 {the only move to pose Black some
problems! Be carefull, 6.Qb3 is a different story than 6.Nc3-e6 7.Qb3-Bb4! ...
sovling all the opening problems at once!} Qd7 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 ({In case of} 
8. Bb5 {Black can play} Nge7 $1 ({Of course} 8... Bd6 $5 {is playable as well.
You can take a look at the following example.} 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Nf3 Nf6 11. Ne5
O-O 12. f4 Nb4 13. Rc1 a6 14. Be2 Rab8 15. O-O Ne4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Bf3 Bxf3
18. Nxf3 Nc6 19. Qd3 Rbc8 20. Ng5 g6 21. Qe2 f6 22. Nf3 Na5 23. b3 Qa3 24. Qd2
Nc6 25. g4 Rc7 26. Rc2 Rd7 27. g5 Qe7 28. Rfc1 h6 29. gxh6 Qh7 30. Qg2 Qxh6 31.
Qg4 Re7 32. Rd2 Kf7 33. Qh4 Rh8 34. Qxh6 Rxh6 35. Ne1 Re8 36. Nd3 Reh8 37. Rc3
Rh3 38. Re2 R8h4 39. Rc1 Rg4+ 40. Kh1 Nxd4 41. Rc7+ Kf8 42. Nf2 Nxe2 43. Nxg4
f5 44. Ne5 Rxe3 45. Nxg6+ Ke8 46. Rxb7 d4 47. Kg2 d3 48. Rb6 Re4 49. Rb8+ Kd7
50. Ne5+ Kc7 51. Re8 Nxf4+ 52. Kf3 Rxe5 53. Kxf4 Re4+ 54. Kg5 d2 55. Re7+ Kd8 {
0-1 Jeszenszky,J-Gelle,I/Hungary 2018/CBMs}) 9. Nf3 Ng6 10. Bg3 Rc8 11. O-O a6
12. Bxc6 Rxc6 13. Rfc1 h5 14. h4 (14. h3 h4 15. Bh2 Qc8 $5 $132 (15... f6 $5
16. Na4 b5 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. dxc5 e5 $132 19. a4 bxa4 20. Qxa4 O-O)) 14... Bg4
$132) (8. Rc1 Rc8 (8... Nge7 $4 9. Nb5 $1 $18) (8... Bb4) 9. Bb5 (9. Nf3 f6 10.
h3 (10. Bb5 a6 11. Bxc6 Rxc6 12. O-O Qc8 (12... Ne7 13. Na4 Rxc1 (13... Qc8 14.
Rxc6 Nxc6 15. Rc1 Be7 16. h3 h5 17. Bg3 Kf7 18. Nd2 h4 19. Bh2 Re8 20. Qd1 g5
21. a3 Qd8 22. Nb3 Bd6 23. Bxd6 Qxd6 24. Nbc5 Re7 25. Qd2 Kg6 26. Rf1 Na7 27.
Nc3 Nb5 28. Nxb5 axb5 29. f4 g4 30. hxg4 Bxg4 31. Qd3+ Bf5 32. Qxb5 Qd8 33. Qe2
b6 34. Na4 Rg7 35. Kh2 Kh6 36. Nc3 Rg3 37. Qf2 Rg4 38. Rc1 Qe8 39. Rg1 Kg7 40.
Ra1 {1/2-1/2 Santos,M-Hofer,R/ICCF 2016/Nikos Updates/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 14.
Rxc1 Nc6 15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. Rxc5 Kf7 $132 (16... O-O $132) 17. Qb6 Rc8 18. Nd2
Ne7) 13. Nd2 Ne7) {SOS !!! WHEN YOU INTEND TO PLAY Nge7 IN THESE LINES...YOU
MUST MAKE SURE THAT WHITE DOES NOT HAVE Nb5 ON HIS NEXT MOVE...THREATENING
BOTH Nd6 AND Nc7 !} 10... Nge7 11. Bb5 (11. Na4 $2 Na5 12. Rxc8+ Nxc8 13. Qb5
Nc4 $17) 11... a6 12. Be2 Ng6 13. Bh2 Na5 14. Qd1 Bb4 15. O-O Ne7 $1 (15... O-O
