{[%evp 0,108,27,27,26,-14,41,19,35,20,32,24,24,32,36,42,69,23,32,30,31,6,21,9,
34,2,-9,-3,-12,-13,-10,-14,2,-11,5,22,39,-1,16,8,9,15,16,-12,-9,-8,-19,-27,-28,
-24,-26,-31,-17,-17,0,-45,-31,-54,-41,-113,-117,-104,-114,-115,-115,-152,-152,
-270,-135,-131,-138,-170,-152,-172,-151,-151,-216,-216,-216,-216,-212,-216,
-162,-170,-167,-174,-167,-203,-219,-330,-338,-338,-381,-475,-357,-302,-314,
-463,-494,-547,-559,-682,-381,-434,-441,-448,-464,-576,-506,-555,-428] A
fantastic performance by Black! Study it carefully and get a feeling of how to
play these positions for a win.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nc6 5.
e3 Nf6 6. Nc3 a6 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Rc1 O-O 12.
Qd2 Bxe2 $1 {now black has the...easier side of equality !} 13. Qxe2 Rac8 (
13... Rfc8 $5) 14. Rfd1 (14. f3 $2 {This weakening of the structure would, of
course, be bad and illogical now! Just imagine White, having played it early
in the opening!} Rfe8 $5 (14... Rc7 $5 15. a3 Rfc8 $15 16. Rc2 Na5 17. Rfc1 Nb3
18. Rd1 g6 $3 19. Qf2 Kg7 $17) 15. Qf2 e5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 $36) 14... Rc7 15. Na4
Rfc8 16. Nc5 a5 17. Qd2 g6 18. h3 b6 19. Na4 Nb4 20. Rxc7 Qxc7 21. Nc3 Nxd3 $1
{Black removes this bishop on purpose..because he saw the key manoeuvre of
Ne8-Nd6!} 22. Qxd3 Ne8 23. g3 Nd6 24. Nb5 $6 Nxb5 25. Qxb5 Qc2 $17 {black has
taken over the only open file! ...his remaining pieces are much more active
than white's !!} (25... Kg7 $5 $17) (25... h5 $5 $17) 26. Rf1 Rc6 27. Re1 Kg7
28. Qe2 Qf5 $1 29. Kg2 Rc2 30. Qf3 Qxf3+ 31. Kxf3 Rxb2 32. Rc1 a4 33. Rc6 Kf6
34. a3 Rb3 35. g4 h5 36. Kf4 g5+ 37. Kf3 h4 38. Kg2 Ke7 39. Rc7+ Ke8 40. Rb7 f6
41. Kf3 b5 42. Kg2 Kd8 43. Rb6 Kd7 44. Rb8 Kc7 45. Rf8 Rxa3 46. Rxf6 Kd6 47. f4
gxf4 48. Rxf4 Rxe3 49. Kf2 Rxh3 50. g5 Rg3 51. Rxh4 Rxg5 52. Rh8 Rg4 53. Ke3
Rg3+ 54. Kd2 Rb3 0-1

